url_title: India: Rats on the menu for Musahar community
url_description: VideoID: 20140518-026 M/S Villagers digging in mud to find rats C/U Villagers digging in mud to find rats C/U Villagers finding a live rat C/U Villager pulling a rat out of the earth C/U Villagers catch two rats C/U Rats struggling to escape C/U Villagers holding live rats by the tail M/S Villagers lifting the rats into the air C/U Rat M/S Villagers holding the rats C/U Rat killing method adopted by the villagers SOT. Member of the Musahar community (in Bhojpuri): "We used to catch rats here and eat the rat meal together with the family." C/U Villager peeling off the rat skin, starts to disembowel the animal W/S Villagers lighting up the dry grass to cook the rats C/U Rats being cooked C/U Villager cleaning the cooked rats before eating M/S Villager eating rats with his family W/S Villagers eating the cooked rats M/S Child eating rat (in Bhojpuri) UPSOUND "Whenever I eat rats, it tastes good." W/S Villagers eating the rats together SCRIPT The Musahar community is a socially marginalised group, placed at the bottom of India's hierarchical caste system. Musahar, which means 'rat eaters' in Bhojpuri, mostly live below the poverty line and many survive by eating rats, their main source of protein. Musahar villagers in the Darbhanga district were seen digging a hole to find rats, Sunday, before killing them by hand. Afterwards the rats are cooked over an open fire before being consumed. The Musahar community can mainly be found in Bihar, where around 250 families live in Darbahanga. They are traditionally rat catchers and generally landless agricultural labourers, who are continuously subjected to discrimination. The Musahar are discriminated for their skin colour, religion, and traditions. url_title: Cry of a River. The trouble with India‚Äôs toilets and drinking water.
url_description: More films about India: https://rtd.rt.com/tags/india/ It‚Äôs surprising how long we can live without food, but without water, survival is impossible, that‚Äôs why it‚Äôs the most precious of our natural resources. Now though, only 1% of the world reserves are safely drinkable. Yet, we consistently fail to see or treat water as the life-giving treasure that it really is. Supplies are being contaminated with industrial and biological waste, aggravating a water crisis that is already crippling countries in every continent. Even India, which has tended to treat its waters with respect and awe, famously worshipping the River Ganges, has a cautionary tale to tell. Hindu people believe that if their sacred Ganges should ever be lost, the Universe would disappear too. Locals who have lived and worked on the river since childhood confirm that water quality has deteriorated dramatically over the years. For generations it has been the local custom to cremate the deceased and scatter their ashes on the river. However, many poor people can‚Äôt even afford firewood, they often resort to water burials in the river without burning, inevitably, this causes even more pollution. As serious as the health risks are, that is just a small part of the Ganges‚Äô wider pollution problems. Two other major factors are contributing to the river‚Äôs toxic decline; raw sewage flows directly into the once sacred water and factories dump huge quantities of chemical waste. The proper disposal of human waste is a pressing issue in India with proper toilets a rarity in rural areas. Many millions of villagers never even consider installing a regular toilet, held back either by poverty or blind acceptance of the status quo. Defecating in streets and fields is unsanitary and leads to the faecal contamination of ground water and so, waterborne diseases are commonplace. The government is attempting to address the problem with financial support and education initiatives for villagers. Progress is slow though; there are already places in India where local water reserves are now unfit for human consumption, or even for agriculture. Kolkata for example, on the Ganges Delta, has an abundance of water but the city has to depend on freshwater deliveries because its own supplies are so contaminated, they can‚Äôt even be used for laundry let alone drinking. Some new-agers may claim Loki ‚Äúexposes‚Äù the Gods; the language of the Edda says otherwise. Can you ask / turn to Odin for help? Often modern pagans, who are ill informed, think that the Gods, even Odin, are not to be turned to in times of need or to ask for help during a struggle. While we can argue that one should provide an offering out of thanks or when asking, just asking alone isn't something you are turned off from. These ill informed pagans think that such an act is Christianly or like Abrahamics whereby you petition or beg God for help or salvation. They paint the Pagan / Ethnic Gods as blind to the folk's plight or are heart hardened to only care about those who take care of themselves with no love for humanity. While it is true that the Gods respect and grant boons to those who work hard, make sacrifices, and are brave, the Gods are not deaf to our existence or struggle. "Just so I Find Odin invoked in Swedish popular songs: Hielp nu, Oden Asagrim! Svenska forns√•ngor 1, 11. hielp mig Othin! 1, 69. To this God first and foremost the people turned when in distress; I suppose he is called Asagrim, because among the Ases he bire the name of Gr√Æmnir? While other sacred animals such as the raven and wolf were demonized by the church, the stag and serpent remained prominent in religious art well into the Middle Ages. Here, the battle between the noble stag and the serpent appears on a Byzantine mosaic from Constantinople, 6th Century.

The northern portal of the Urnes Stave Church features the recurring motif of a stag and serpents; this was such a persistent motif of the afterlife, nobility, and ascension to Valhalla that perhaps the early church gave up on demonizing them, as they did with ravens and wolves, and adopted them into early Christian iconography. The portal has been dated to the 11th Century, while the rest of the church was built in the 12th Century; it may very well have been repurposed from another church-or a temple. Aldhelm‚Äôs 7th Century letter to Heahfrith mentions a snake and stag on pillars in Anglo Saxon temples, and according to Bede, pagan temples were not destroyed, but repurposed. ‚¥≤

A fragment of Andronovo pottery with a Swastika from the Akmola region, Kazakhstan, 2000BC-900BC. Many centuries later, the same variation of the Swastika was used on an Anglo Saxon burial urn at Spong Hill in the 6th Century.

Ren√© Gu√©non and Russian archaeologist Gennady Zdanovich proposed that the Swastika originated from the movement of the Big Dipper around Polaris, based on some of the oldest known examples from the Bronze Age. On many variations, the arms are curved where the bowl and handle of the dipper would be. On a common variation of the Hindu Swastika, the four circles mirror the seasonal position of the Little Dipper in relation to the Big Dipper. This symbol, reflected in the night sky, would have served as a visible testament to the cycles of time, life, death and renewal. ‡øò

Sagnama√∞r‚Äôs Guide to Amanita Muscaria If you should choose to use amanita muscaria for religious or medicinal purposes, be sure to prepare it right. The key to effectively utilizing this ancient entheogen is a process called decarboxylation; conversion of the mushroom‚Äôs harmful toxin, called ibotenic acid, into one called muscimol; this is the compound that allows one to enter altered states of consciousness. Start by removing the stems and thoroughly drying the caps, this begins the process of decarboxylation. A dehydrator is ideal, otherwise, an oven on the lowest possible setting will do. A traditional method is to string them up in a warm, well-ventilated place, and/or direct sunlight. Your mushrooms should be dry enough that you can‚Äôt bend them without them cracking. Amanita muscaria isn‚Äôt illegal in most countries, you may be able to easily buy dried mushrooms. Per dose/per person, think of 1-10g as a 1-10 scale of intensity of the psychotropic effects. Amanita muscaria‚Äôs effects on the central nervous system have been shown to be effective in treating various ailments such as insomnia, chronic stress, depression, addiction and even muscle pains; for medicinal use, only very small doses, usually under a gram, should be necessary. Now, here‚Äôs how you make Soma. To achieve total decarboxylation, add your dried caps to water along with half a lemon or 2-5tbsp of apple cider vinegar, bring to a boil, and simmer for three hours. Alternatively, wine can be used. The key here is the addition of an acid. You can also just make a tea from the dried caps, as drying will mitigate any side effects, but this extra step will produce more muscimol. *Disclaimer: for legal reasons, I‚Äôm not advocating for anything. Use amanita muscaria at your own risk. Never consume any wild mushroom you aren‚Äôt 100% certain of. Be safe. üçÑ

Since the conversation‚Äôs come up again‚Ä¶arguments for and against a monistic worldview in Germanic paganism can be made from the Poetic Edda. The most significant case against monism would be the stark dichotomy between the Gods and the J√∂tnar, with the Gods as benevolent agents of creation and order, pitted in an eternal battle against the destructive and chaotic forces of the J√∂tnar. The fact that a victory for the J√∂tnar in Ragnar√∂k would mean the destruction of the Nine Realms could be used to argue that the J√∂tnar are objectively, inherently evil, and thus, an underlying unity with the wholly benevolent Gods is not possible. However; a case could be made from the fact that J√∂tnar are individuals, some of which are benevolent and even accepted among the Gods, as is the case with √Ügir, R√°n and Ska√∞i, who aids the Gods in binding Loki. This upward mobility for the J√∂tnar could be used to argue that an underlying unity is possible. Ultimately, read the Eddas and make your own judgement.

The theory that the √Üsir-Vanir war was an allegory for a war between the invading Indo-Europeans and the Early European Farmers/Hunter Gatherers is deeply flawed. Most importantly, cognates to the Vanir gods are found in other Indo-European religions. The most obvious example is Freyja/ƒíostre, cognate to Greek Eos, Baltic Au≈°rinƒó, Roman Aurora and Vedic Ushas, the most-mentioned goddess in the Rig Veda. Myths of wars between gods exist in other Indo-European religions, such as the Titanomachy of Greek paganism, the wars between Devas and Asuras, and the battle between Shiva and Vishnu in the Puranas. It is not at all unique to Germanic paganism. Painting by Donn P. Crane, 1922.

Winterfylleth was the Old English name for the winter equinox. According to Bede, the Anglo Saxons called the beginning of winter «∑interfylle√æ, a term comprised of winter and full moon. The Germanic peoples only recognized summer (ON: Sumar) and winter (ON: Vetr), and the full moon of what would now be October marked the beginning of winter; the six months where the days were longer than the nights were counted as summer, and the other six as winter. From the Sagas, Haustbl√≥t was observed at this time. In the G√≠sla saga S√∫rssonar, a feast and a sacrifice to Freyr on the Winter-Nights (Vetrn√¶tr) is mentioned twice. ‚ÄúSummer drew to a close and the Winter Nights began. In those days it was the custom to celebrate the coming of winter by holding feasts and a Winter Nights‚Äô sacrifice. Gisli no longer sacrificed after he left Viborg, but he still held feasts and showed the same magnanimity as before.‚Äù ‚ÄúThorgrim decided to hold a feast at the end of autumn to celebrate the coming of the Winter Nights. There was to be a sacrifice to Frey, and he invited his brother, Bork, Eyjolf Thordarson and many other men of distinction.‚Äù The Saga of Saint Olaf attested this practice enduring in Norway, ‚ÄúAs long as heathenism prevailed, Sigurd usually had three sacrifices every year: one on winter-night's eve, one on mid-winter's eve, and the third in summer.‚Äù In the Ynglingasaga, Odin prescribed a sacrifice at the beginning of winter for a good year. ‚ÄúOn winter day there should be blood-sacrifice for a good year, and in the middle of winter for a good crop; and the third sacrifice should be on summer day, for victory in battle.‚Äù √Ålfabl√≥t followed, being held at home with one‚Äôs family. ‚ÄúSyncretism‚Äù is a term I‚Äôve seen thrown around a lot lately, usually as an insult, by people who don‚Äôt understand what it means. Combining beliefs and practices from more than one religion is syncretism. Comparatively studying other religions while only practicing one religion is not syncretism. If, for example, you were to study other Indo-European religions (and recognize them as related), but only practice Germanic paganism yourself, that‚Äôs not syncretism. Some friends of mine practice Buddhism alongside European polytheism, as did the ancient Greeks in Gandhara, which is syncretism. Religious syncretism did occur in the ancient world; for example, along the Roman frontiers. Romans, Celts and Germans shared worship of gods such as Hercules Magusanus, Nehalennia and Epona along the Rhine and Danube, and many Romans and Greeks adopted worship of Egyptian gods alongside their own. Hope this clears things up. Pics: a Roman-made shrine to Nehalennia, and a Roman mosaic depicting Hermes-Anubis.

url_title: A God in Disguise? Pagan Lessons in Hospitality
url_description: In traditions around the world we see the same mythological trope of a god disguised as a beggar so that he can test mortals. Very often this is based on a moral that one should uphold the ancient tradition of honouring the guest in one's home. The myths usually show the god, who can be Zeus, Shiva, or Odin, punishing the mortals who fail to show them proper hospitality when they visit. What lessons can pagans learn from these myths? cleaned_message: This is, without a doubt, the worst take I‚Äôve seen in a while. Indo-European reconstructionism is carefully based on the numerous linguistic, cultural, and genetic commonalities among IE peoples. Yes, the Greek myth of Baucis and Philemon is somewhat similar to the biblical myth of Sodom and Gomorrah. There are also several differences, such as Zeus and Hermes visiting in disguise as opposed to angels, and Tyana being flooded as opposed to being destroyed by fire and brimstone. Its slight similarity to the biblical myth does not invalidate its numerous similarities to other IE myths involving gods in disguise; such as the Gr√≠mnism√°l. Our ancestors didn‚Äôt come from atomized tribes who formed similar cultures, languages and religions out of pure coincidence, our Indo-European ancestors conquered half of the known world, founding great new cultures, before they‚Äôd even figured out iron. You‚Äôd think that would be a source of pride for these people. https://t.me/folkishworldview/313
url_title: Folkish Worldview
url_description: Proto-Indo-European reconstruction is a dangerous business. It's very easy to draw unsound conclusions from nothing more than wild leaps and rough guesswork. There are some in the right-wing pagan community who take this way too far. You'll see such wild generalizations as "Lugh = Odin = Zeus = Shiva" etc. It's easy to see things that aren't there. For example, there's a well known Greek myth of Baucis and Philemon where two gods in disguise visit a town of wicked folk who violate the sacred custom of xenia, refusing to welcome the strangers. Only the good Baucis and Philemon take the strangers in and later only they are spared in a divine flood that wipes out the town. This is very clearly paralleled by the biblical story of Sodom and Gomorrah where YHVH sends two angels to test the wicked people of Sodom and only Lot welcomes them into his home, after which Sodom is destroyed and Lot is spared. If you were to apply the Lugh = Odin = etc. approach, you could not ask for a more clear "reconstructed" myth between the "last common ancestor" of the Greeks and Jews, leading you to a putative "Proto-Helleno-Semitic" myth, which is clearly gibberish. Proto-Indo-European reconstruction is fraught with danger and pitfalls. It should not be bandied about lightly. Seeing people proceed recklessly here, and then claim to be authoritative, is a big red flag. @folkishworldview

Julian the Apostate made a few interesting cases for polytheism in Against the Galileans. He argued that so many peoples having such drastically differing moralities, laws, religions and physical differences as being the work of multiple different gods, as opposed to a common people with different languages, as described in the Tower of Babel story. He also questioned why if there was only one true god, and he was a jealous god as it says in Exodus, that for centuries, he only spoke to a tribe in the Near East, while allowing other peoples to worship false gods.

With Cicero‚Äôs proposal of divination as proof of the divine, it‚Äôs important to recognize that in turbulent times such as the Migration Period and the Viking Age, warfare was a constant and a bad harvest would be enough to destroy your family‚Äôs life. Divination wouldn‚Äôt have been so universally relied upon if it wasn‚Äôt reliably producing actionable results for people. It would be simply too many coincidences to not be. And when you consider the fact that divination and consulting a soothsayer were repeatedly banned in multiple early Christian law codes, it shows that it was important enough to people that they were willing to risk doing it regardless of legality, often truly risking their lives, and it was a persistent enough practice that they failed to ban it for hundreds of years. Divination wasn‚Äôt a game.

Cases for polytheism‚Ä¶ Oddly enough, before I ever read Cicero, I myself made similar arguments to those made in De Natura Deorum. That so many peoples, some related and some unrelated and with very little contact, had a deeply ingrained belief in gods. Many of these gods were similar to those known by other peoples, and many were completely unique to certain peoples. They came by these beliefs, and held to them for centuries, naturally; for argument‚Äôs sake I‚Äôve been looking for an example of a forced, coerced, or politically motivated conversion to paganism, but in the Germanic sphere, I couldn‚Äôt find one. Blasphemy was severely punished, but in pagan Europe, different religious groups coexisted. Many of these peoples, related and unrelated, often developed similar methods of contacting and worshipping these gods; such as fire rituals, worshipping at certain bodies of water, shamanic practices, and sacrifices of objects of value. And how does this prove that they‚Äôre not just archetypes ingrained into the human subconscious? Our ancestors, as the polytheists of today, clearly believed in metaphysical gods; they wouldn‚Äôt have had elaborate gifting rituals in which they offered valuable resources if they didn‚Äôt believe they‚Äôd ever get anything in return, and didn‚Äôt believe these gods were metaphysical and able to intercede in their lives. Something Cicero cites as an example of visible divine intercession is auguries and prophetic visions granted to priests and shamans by the Gods, which ended up being actionable or later proven true. Unlike individual blessings and UPGs today, this would be visible to multiple people. Today, an example of divine intercession that comes to mind is Kedarnath Temple; when Uttarakhand was struck by flash floods, 92 people took refuge in a temple of Shiva. As the floodwaters surged towards the temple, a boulder rolled down from the mountains, and came to a stop mere feet from the temple, diverting the floodwaters and saving everyone inside. Science can‚Äôt explain this one away; with the momentum the boulder was carrying, it should have crushed the temple. It wasn‚Äôt an archetype or a metaphor that stopped the boulder that day; it was a god, looking out for his devotees. ‚¥≤

A better picture of the Thor figure from Lund. It was carved from a piece of walrus ivory, and is believed to depict Thor raising winds with his beard, as described in the √ìl√°fs saga Tryggvasonar. Hallfre√∞r Vandr√¶√∞ask√°ld was described carrying a small figure of Thor made of a tusk; would‚Äôve been something like this.
An interesting amulet from Gnezdovo, with two quadrupeds back to back; possibly Freki and Geri. A similar example was found in the V√•rby hoard. ·ö¨

In the Gautreks Saga, when Starka√∞r sacrifices V√≠kar, he says ‚Äúnow I give you to Odin‚Äù, or in Old Norse, N√∫ gef ek √æik √ì√∞ni: this is something we could use in our own bl√≥ts to Odin. In Old English, this would be N≈´ gief ic √æƒì W≈çden. ‚¥≤ Painting by Konrad Wihelm Delitz, 1892.

The oft-overlooked First Merseburg Charm invokes Idisi (D√≠sir; probably Valkyries) to escape fetters. Charms to escape from fetters are mentioned twice in the Poetic Edda, which shows it was a well-known charm; the First Merseburg Charm being a surviving Old High German example. ‚ÄúOnce the Idisi set forth, to this place and that; Some fastened fetters; some hindered the horde, Some loosed the bonds from the brave: Leap forth from the fetters! Escape from the foes!‚Äù ~First Merseburg Charm ‚ÄúA fourth I know, if men shall fasten Bonds on my bended legs; So great is the charm that forth I may go, The fetters spring from my feet, Broken the bonds from my hands.‚Äù ~H√°vam√°l 149, Bellows ‚ÄúThen fifth I will chant thee, if fetters perchance Shall bind thy bending limbs: O'er thy thighs do I chant a loosening-charm, And the lock is burst from the limbs, And the fetters fall from the feet.‚Äù ~Svipdagsm√°l 10, Bellows Painting by William T. Maud, 1890.
Bronze Age fylfot amulets from Greece and Sweden.

Whether or not you believe Loki is objectively evil, he does teach an important, timeless lesson; the dangers of allowing a vanquished enemy to live among you. Although Odin was good to him, his loyalty to his own people, and resentment of his conquerors, would always outweigh the goodwill of the √Üsir. Painting: Balders D√∏d by Peter Cramer, 1779.
Lovely bracteate with a looped square symbol from Stora Tollby, Gotland.

Another interpretation of the Snaptun Stone‚Ä¶ While the stone clearly depicts Loki, it depicts him after his mouth had been sewn shut after he wouldn‚Äôt honour his wager, which Brokkr won despite Loki‚Äôs attempts to sabotage him in his smithy. Thus, the image of the conclusion of this story, with Loki defeated, on a smith‚Äôs hearth stone may have been intended to prevent any interference by evil spirits during the smithing process, and possibly to help the smith produce the finest possible work.

This popular Viking Age pendant design is very reminiscent of a few examples of Neolithic spiral art, including the kerbstones at Newgrange. The jury‚Äôs out on what they represent; pathways between worlds, traps for evil spirits, or altered states of consciousness are a few theories. These spirals have been compared to visuals produced by psychedelics, including psilocybin.

Vendemasker (reversible mask) pendants were popular across Scandinavia in the Viking Age. The intricate design forms a bearded face, whether viewed from above or below. It‚Äôs been proposed that these depict Odin; hanging upside down on Yggdrasil to gain esoteric insight. Some examples feature a beast head, which could depict D√°inn above or N√≠√∞√∏ggr beneath. Plus, one of Odin‚Äôs epithets is Tveggi; twofold. It could also be a shamanic motif, representing the reflection of the underworld and upper world; which Odin traverses between. ‚¥≤

In Finnish paganism, grass snakes are associated with the earth goddess Akka, and in Baltic paganism with the sun goddess Saulƒó, because they emerge from hibernation underground in spring, when they are often seen in masses known as mating balls. This could also be the inspiration behind the ever-present Germanic entwined snake motifs, which may also be a symbol of fertility. ‚¥≤

An unusual mask pendant found in √òster Lindet, Denmark, proposed to depict Loki with his mouth stitched shut by Brokkr as described in the Sk√°ldskaparm√°l. It‚Äôs worth noting that even if this does depict Loki, as with every other depiction we have of Loki, he‚Äôs depicted somehow bound; symbolizing the Gods subduing the forces of chaos and evil. For example, he‚Äôs also depicted with his mouth stitched on the Snaptun Stone, and he‚Äôs depicted bound on the Loki Stone from Kirkby.
One of the bed posts from the Oseberg Ship, with a Valknut visible. Could have been intended as a protective symbol for while the occupant slept.

I‚Äôve always found it interesting how while the Germanic peoples lived in relatively humble dwellings, they lavishly decorated every inch of the small things; weapons, tools, armour, etc. But, compared to civilizations such as Ancient Greece and Rome, who built massive feats of architecture, many of which still stand to this day, the Germanic peoples had very little peacetime. While IE peoples such as the Romans managed to periodically subdue their enemies, the Germanic peoples were surrounded by enemies on all sides; the Romans, the Nomads, the Carolingians, and of course, rival tribes. In the case of the Migration Era, many of these peoples would also frequently be on the move. And in these turbulent times, it would be these simple survival essentials; your knife, sword, shield, helmet, spear, axe, horse harness, wagon, tent, cloak pin, fire starter, etc. that would be your lifeline; and worthy of this adornment, as symbols of the resilience of your folk. ‚¥≤
This necklace was found in a 5-6th Century Scandinavian settlement in Such√°n, northern Poland, featuring a sun cross and two bracteates. ‚¥≤

Among the Germanic peoples, a partial shave appears to have been a symbol of nobility. A figure on the Oseberg Wagon appears to depict a man with an undercut, and razors were often found in high status burials throughout the Bronze Age and Iron Age. In Leo the Deacon‚Äôs account of Sviatoslav I, his head was shaved with with some of his hair falling down the side, ‚Äúwhich showed high status among his kin‚Äù. Sviatoslav was of Norse descent, but similar styles were also recorded among the Wends. A 12-14th Century fresco from a church in Westerwijwerd, Netherlands, depicts two Frisian warriors with significant undercuts, and only one lock of hair at the front. William of Malmesbury‚Äôs 11th Century Chronicle of the Kings of England mentioned the Anglo Saxons wearing their hair cropped, along with punctured designs (tattoos?) and gold arm rings; clearly high status warriors he was describing.
A silver brooch from √Ñspinge, Sweden, with the popular backwards-facing beast design depicted in the Ringerike art style, 10-11th Century. Looks like it could depict Fenrir bound.

This gullgubber from Bornholm appears to be a votive depiction of a sacrifice by hanging. Gullgubbers are frequently found at the sites of temples, often depicting people or animals such as boars, and are thought to have been made and offered by people who couldn‚Äôt afford to sacrifice the real thing.
A Vendel Era drinking horn terminal from H√∏rning, Denmark, with one eye filled in with a silver sun cross. Very Odinic. ‚¥≤

The sun cross may be one of the most prominent symbols of Germanic and European paganism as a whole. While the Swastika was used all over the world, the sun cross saw the most use in Europe, and was used throughout the Bronze Age and Iron Age. Depending on the variation, it encompasses the sun and even the Swastika and the cycle of life and time. Other symbols such as the Mjolnir were more specific to one particular period or culture. And, it was prominent enough that it was absorbed into Christian iconography across Europe. ‚Ä¶as a bonus, wearing or displaying a sun cross is a great way to scare brosatrus away. ‚¥≤
A Viking Age bronze mount, with two Ringerike-style wolf heads sprouting from a face, likely Odin with Freki and Geri.

In a recent ballistics test, the WWI French Adrian Helmet outperformed the modern Advanced Combat Helmet in protection from overhead blasts-due to the reinforced crest. The boar-crests on Migration Period helmets, mentioned throughout Beowulf, were more than decoration, they would have significantly reinforced the helmet. Pic: the helmet from Valsg√§rde grave 6.

Anglo Saxon pressblech die depicting a wolf warrior from Fen Drayton, Cambridgeshire, 6-7th Century. This one looks more like a man peering out through a specialized helmet, as described by Plutarch. ‚¥≤

Katharine Simms and Charles McQuarrie wrote that the Fianna warriors favoured the Cul√°n haircut, and would have ‚Äúdevilish markings‚Äù on their foreheads, possibly tattoos. This haircut has been found on bog bodies in Ireland and Denmark. Among the Iroquois, this haircut is known as the Wolf‚Äôs Tail, and was given to cultic wolf warriors. This haircut may very well have originated in the Stone Age with the Mal‚ÄôTa Buret‚Äô Culture, and may have been a mark of the Koryos.
A pressblech stamp with an Odinic horned figure from Vejleby, Lolland, Denmark. ‚¥≤

Jacob Grimm recorded a few very Odinic superstitions or ‚Äúunbeliefs‚Äù in parts of Germany. Some folks believed that encountering a wolf was good luck, as recounted in the Reginsm√°l. They also believed that a bird flying over your right was good luck and over your left was bad luck, and an eagle flying by your ‚Äúpocket side‚Äù was such an auspicious sign that people would shift their pocket to the side an eagle had flown by. ‚¥≤ Painting by Liliya Butenko.
A recently discovered Migration Period gold hoard from Spentrup, Denmark, containing a brooch, ring, and several zoomorphic lunulae, each with two bird heads. Very Odinic. ‚¥≤

When morning came, the Saxons placed an eagle before the eastern gate, and constructed an altar of victory following the error of their fathers.‚Äú ~Deeds of the Saxons, Widukind of Corvey ‚¥≤

Been thinking‚Ä¶another one of my takeaways from Exiles of the Golden Age was the kinds of people who showed up. Lots of amazing people, united by heritage, mission, and faith. There were none of these terminally online basement pagans who spend half of their time criticizing and complaining. One of the speakers, a fellow Germanic pagan, referenced the Rig Veda, Buddhism and Hellenism, and nobody screamed that he was an evil syncretist/monist/Platonist/etc. One speaker was Christian, and everyone was respectful, willing to engage in a respectful interfaith dialogue and agree to disagree on certain things because we shared a common heritage and mission. I talked with a lot of people there, even asked a few what they believed happened when the Yamnaya branched out and formed new cultures, whether they continued to worship the same Gods in their new languages; or, forgot about them and‚Ä¶made up new ones? They recognized Odin is known to multiple peoples under different names, as it says in the Gr√≠mnism√°l and Gylfaginning. A few of us even joked about certain content creators. The conflicts you‚Äôve seen on the pagan web over the past year were entirely started and parroted by a select vocal few, but it only exists among the terminally online. It doesn't exist in the real world. We also discussed one of the main issues facing paganism; the fact that too many pagans focus so much on what they oppose, to the point that they become solely defined by what they hate. While hate is a necessary part of the human experience, without love of all that‚Äôs good, you will never have any genuine belief. Our enemies are known; don‚Äôt give them any more power over you by allowing them to define your entire worldview. The way forward is known. Find your people and build your networks in the real world, and worship your Gods, Wights and ancestors with utmost piety. Ves heill! Wes √æ√∫ h√°l! ‚¥≤

Recorded by a lovely friend of mine, author of this article: Danish Folklore There was a bit of folk belief, or the "old faith" as my grandparents called it, on northwest Funen when I was a kid in the 70s, about, among other things, "the hunters" as they were called. My dad's parents were one of those households who used to put a mixed (fresh) sheaf over the front door, to maintain good relations with the hunters, besides the sheaf on the pole down in the garden, when we got into that part of autumn and winter when the wind picked up. Whether the hunters were good or the opposite, of course, depended a bit on who you asked, but for those who had good relations with Oens and so on, there was the fact that they chased trolls and evil beings away from house and field.

Geoffrey Keating‚Äôs Foras Feasa ar √âirinn, drawing upon multiple medieval Irish accounts, contains a detailed account of the Fianna warbands. To join the Fianna, one had to pass several tests; to parry multiple spears with a shield and staff, move through the forest without breaking a twig, being detected by other warriors or having a branch undo one of his braids, and would have to be able to jump over a tree as high as his forehead, stoop under a tree as low as his knee, and pull a thorn from his foot while running. Slander was dealt with quite severely in the Older Gula√æing Law. If one was found guilty of slander, the accuser was required to pay a fine to the accused, and the accused had the right to have him outlawed and kill him. Examples mentioned in the law code included; accusing a man of unlawful sexual intercourse (likely adultery and/or homosexuality), claiming a man gave birth to a child (reference to Loki?), or comparing him to a bitch or mare (which implied homosexuality), accusing another of being a troll, werewolf or sorcerer, and accusing a woman of adultery.

In the Fagrskinna, H√°kon the Good decreed that every freedman capable of fighting was to have a spear, shield and slashing weapon, be it an axe or sword. The 11th Century Older Gula√æing Law required all freedmen to own weapons, including a sword or axe, spear and shield, and each household was to have a bow and two dozen arrows. Inspections would be held, and any freedman missing these weapons would be subject to fines. At assemblies, men would show their approval of a decision by raising their weapons; this practice was known as v√°pntak (ON: weapon-touching). Our ancestors understood well that freedom derives solely from one‚Äôs preparedness and ability to defend it against all contestants. Thought I‚Äôd review an often overlooked translation of the Poetic Edda; the 2014 one by Jeramy Dodds. Dodds is a Canadian professional poet and academic, and his translation shows a focus on keeping it poetic, with a strong understanding of the Old Icelandic poetic form. Like Bellows, he meticulously maintains the original form, but with more modern English, making it easier to read than older translations. The only downside is that while he did include a comprehensive index, there‚Äôs no notes. Overall though, it‚Äôs a good translation and a straightforward and enjoyable read, and could especially be a good first Edda for newcomers. It gets my seal of approval. ‚¥≤

People have been asking me about Jackson Crawford‚Äôs translation of the Poetic Edda. Regardless of what you might think of the guy, I‚Äôve read the V√∂lusp√° in the Amazon free sample, and I was not at all impressed by what I saw. Here‚Äôs my review. First of all, in the V√∂lusp√°, he replaces Garm with Fenrir in stanza 49 and 58 ("Now Garm howls loud before Gnipahellir"), and omitted multiple stanzas, because he seems to think he knows better than the original poet. Unlike other translators, he offers no explanatory notes, neither on the text nor his decisions. Secondly, the beautiful, articulate language of the Edda, for example the kennings and epithets of the Gods, is highly simplified and literal. In addition, he didn‚Äôt translate it word for word, he translated each entire sentence. The result is an Edda that‚Äôs not poetic at all. As with Thorpe's translation, it's hard to say if he was going for verse or prose. It certainly won‚Äôt read at all like it was originally intended to, as poetry. Yes, it‚Äôs very easy to read, but even then, he‚Äôs changed and omitted several things from the original text. Bottom line, he offers nothing over other translations, I‚Äôd even say he lowered the bar. Bellows's translation is still my favourite, but if you want one that's going to be easier to read with less antiquated terms, I recommend Larrington's. Larrington‚Äôs also includes a few additional poems not found in the Codex Regius, or other translations. Hate to be so negative, but people need to know what they‚Äôre spending their money on, and putting into their heads. It does have one redeeming feature‚Ä¶after all, there could be another toilet paper shortage, and there‚Äôs 392 sheets altogether. ‚¥≤

Remember, in the Annals, Tacitus mentioned the Chatti and Hermunduri fighting over a salt producing river. Salt was much more scarce and valuable back then, and would absolutely make for a suitable food offering.

"The Thesaurus pauperum of 1468 condemned "the idolatrous superstition of those who left food and drink at night in open view for Abundia and Satia, or, as the people said, Fraw Percht and her retinue, hoping thereby to gain abundance and riches." The same practice of offering drink, salt, and food to Perchta, "alias domine Habundie," on certain days had been taken note of and subsequently condemned in 1439 by Thomas Ebendorfer von Haselbach in De decem praeceptis." The Thesaurus pauperum of 1468 speaks of a "growing cult to Perchta" found in Bavaria which was then actively condemned by the Church. After which the cult still continued to exist. It amazes me that the most historically catholic state in Germany had a growing cult to Perchta/Holle during the medieval period.

Up until recently, the Heiltsuk People of the Pacific Northwest maintained a wolf warrior initiation rite very similar to that of the Indo-European Koryos; the ‚Äúdog-eater‚Äù ritual. Long ago, the Heiltsuk domesticated dogs for hunting, by stealing wolf pups. They believed that the wolves might resent their packmates who left them, and that by eating a dog, and vicariously settling the score, the initiate ritually becomes a wolf. The survival of these rites show that they probably have a shared common origin with the various Eurasian Koryos rites in the Stone Age, with the Mal‚ÄôTa Buret‚Äô Culture.

Part of the H√°vam√°l I often see taken out of context these days is stanza 54-56, each of which begin with, ‚ÄúA measure of wisdom each man shall have, but never too much let him know;‚Äù (Bellows translation). Some people seem to take this to mean that one shouldn‚Äôt think too much, and even use it to tell people not to question their opinions and interpretations, as if to introduce Puritan-tier anti-intellectualism to paganism. But let‚Äôs look at the rest of the stanzas. 54. ‚Äú‚Ä¶The fairest lives do those men live Whose wisdom wide has grown. 55. ‚Äú‚Ä¶For the wise man‚Äôs heart is seldom happy, If wisdom too great he has won. 56. ‚Äú‚Ä¶Let no man the fate before him see, For so is he freest from sorrow.‚Äù At no point does the H√°vam√°l, the words of the wisest of the √Üsir, tell you not to think for yourself, Stanza 54 clearly illustrates this. All it takes to dispel these ridiculous arguments is to simply read the Edda. Stanza 55 is merely a warning; the greater your understanding of the complexities of the many issues facing our folk, the more tormented your mind will be. Follow the example of Odin, never stop seeking knowledge and wisdom. Read the Eddas and Sagas, revisit them, study them, debate them. It is only with a deep understanding of our holy texts, folklore, history and theology that you can propagate your ethnic faith, and defend it against all attackers, internal and external. And with a deeper understanding will come a deeper connection to the Gods. ‚¥≤

The Second Merseburg Charm, which recounts Odin healing Baldr‚Äôs horse, has multiple later 18-19th Century parallels in Scandinavia, Scotland and Saxony, wherein Jesus or St. Olaf take the place of Odin, which shows this particular healing charm was widely known. Jacob Grimm collected multiple examples from Norway, Sweden, Denmark, and the Shetland Islands. One example from Norway; ‚ÄúJesus himself rode to the heath, And as he rode, his horse's bone was broken. Jesus dismounted and healed that: Jesus laid marrow to marrow, Bone to bone, flesh to flesh. Jesus thereafter laid a leaf So that these should stay in their place.‚Äù Artur Hazelius recorded one from Sm√•land, Sweden, brazenly invoking Odin in the 19th Century. ‚ÄúOdin rides over rock and hill; He rides his horse out of dislocation and into realignment, Out of disorder and into order, bone to bone, joint to joint, As it was best, when it was whole.‚Äù Book 4, hymn 12 of the Atharvaveda contains a very similar healing charm for a broken bone; ‚ÄúThou art the healer, making whole, the healer of the broken bone: Make thou this whole, Arundhatƒ´! Whatever bone of thine within thy body hath been wrenched or cracked, May DhƒÅtar set it properly and join together limb by limb. With marrow be the marrow joined, thy limb united with the limb. Let what hath fallen of thy flesh, and the bone also grow again. Let marrow close with marrow, let skin grow united with the skin. Let blood and bone grow strong in thee, flesh grow together with the flesh. Join thou together hair with hair, join thou together skin with skin. Let blood and bone grow strong in thee. A persistent misconception you‚Äôll hear is that Tyr is somehow the ‚Äúoriginal‚Äù Sky Father/head of the Germanic pantheon. However, this argument is based solely on oversimplified linguistics. The name Tyr means simply ‚Äúthe/a God‚Äù, and many of Odin‚Äôs epithets contain -tyr; ex. Geirtyr (spear-god). In the Sk√°ldskaparm√°l, Thor is attested as Chariot-Tyr. Odin clearly is the Sky Father; he slays the primordial life form (Ymir) and shapes the cosmos from his body, fathers the Striker (Thor) and the Divine Twins, marries the Earth Mother (Frigg/Jor√∞), watches over the ancestral dead (Einherjar), tests his children‚Äôs hospitality in disguise as Shiva and Zeus are attested as doing, and his golden throne Hlidskjalf is the all-seeing sun eye. These roles are reflected by the Sky Father in other IE religions. According to Tacitus, the Germanic tribes worshipped Mercury (Wodan) the most, followed by Mars (Tyr) and Hercules (Thor). He does not liken any Germanic gods to Jupiter. In the Sk√°ldskaparm√°l, Tyr is attested as a son of Odin. In the Hymskvi√∞a he‚Äôs attested as the son of Hymir; who may have been Odin in disguise. The Hymskvi√∞a follows the H√°rbar√∞slj√≥√∞ in the Poetic Edda, and Hymir taunts Thor in a very similar manner to H√°rbar√∞, suggesting he‚Äôll freeze if he goes fishing. Odin‚Äôs titles containing Tyr include; Geirtyr (spear god), Hrafntyr (raven god), Farmatyr (burden god), Fimbultyr (mighty god), Gautatyr (god of the Geats), Sigtyr (victory god), Hertyr (host god), Hroptatyr (sage god) Runatyr (rune god), Hangetyr (hanged god), Valtyr (god of the slain), Veratyr (god of men) and Rei√∞atyr (god of riders). Several of Odin‚Äôs titles contain father; Aldafa√∞r (father of men), Alfa√∞r (Allfather), Herf√∏√∞r/Herjaf√∏√∞r (father of hosts), Galdraf√∏√∞r (father of galdr), J√≥lf√∏√∞r (Yule father) and Sigf√∏√∞r (father of victory). However, none of Tyr‚Äôs epithets suggest he is any kind of father figure. Tyr has a clear Vedic cognate; Kartikeya, commonly known as Murugan, and Shanmukha in the Vedas. He is a son of Shiva, and the commander of the army of the Devas. Like Tyr, Mars and Ares, Tuesday is Kartikeya‚Äôs holy day, and his weapon is a spear. Tyr‚Äôs Celtic cognate would be Nuada. Nuada was the first high king of the Tuatha D√© Danann, before losing his hand in battle. The Romans likened Nuada to Mars, who is second only to Jupiter as a commander of the Gods; just like Kartikeya‚Ä¶and Tyr. ·õè

Tom kindly gave me early access to this course so I could review it, and I can confidently say that I heartily endorse this course. What to do with your food offerings, as per various historical sources; Leaving them out; the Guta Lag bans leaving offerings of food and drink in sacred groves, and the Hyndluj√≥√∞ and Hervarar Saga ok Hei√∞reks mention leaving offerings at an outdoor shrine. In many Indo-European religions, an animal eating your offering was considered a good omen; the Gr√≠mnism√°l may attest to this belief, with Odin giving any food given to him to his wolves. Burning; the Penitential of Theodore, Confessional of Ecgbert, and Cnut‚Äôs laws banned burning offerings of grain and worshipping fire. Fire was so integral to Germanic pagan practices that Ahmad ibn Rustah referred to the Vikings as Al-Majus; fire worshippers. Placing in a body of water; countless offerings including animal bones, gold and weapons have been found in bogs, lakes and rivers across Germanic Europe. Alfred the Great‚Äôs laws banned making offerings at rivers, and Cnut‚Äôs laws banned worshipping at wells and waterfalls. Eating it; communal feasts of sacrificial animals are well attested in the Heimskringla, J√≥msv√≠kinga Saga and Hervarar Saga ok Hei√∞reks. The Penitential of Theodore bans eating food that had been offered in sacrifice, which shows this was acceptable. The Bhagavad Gita says similar. ‚¥≤

Like us today, our ancestors wouldn‚Äôt have been able to sacrifice valuable livestock (or prisoners) on a regular basis. While many Christian and Roman accounts focus on animal and human sacrifices in greater detail, on a daily basis, offerings of food and drink were far more common, such as alcohol and grain. The Life of St. Columban mentions Swabians making an offering of beer to Wodan, the Guta Saga mentions smaller assemblies making offerings of food and ale, and The History of the Normans by Dudo of Saint-Quentin mentions offerings of grain and wine. The Anglo Saxon Penitential of Theodore and the Confessional of Egbert both explicitly banned the burning of grain. The Indiculus superstitionum et paganiarum mentions the Old Saxons making idols of moistened flour; not unlike torma in Buddhism.

Here is a list I came up with. I know that others may disagree thinking there are other areas or text that should be mentioned. However, I intend this for general beginners. The V√∂lusp√°: shows a common Eurasian/ Indo-European creation myth that reflects similar things in the Greek tales as well as the Rig Veda Mandala 10. It also shows the cycle of life and rebirth, similar to other Indo-European groups and Samara. As well as the creation of man. R√≠gs√æula: shows the creation of the tripartite caste system. The H√°vam√°l: has proverbial wisdom for daily life and warriors. and Odin's path to Enlightenment / Runes. Gr√≠mnism√°l: 8-10, Helgakvi√∞a I-II, and V√∂lusp√° 32 stanza describe Valhalla. Helgakvi√∞a : Reincarnation Gr√≠mnism√°l and Gylfaginning describe Asgard in general, which can be compared to Elysium and Olympus / Svargaloka / Mt. Sumeru (Meru). Gylfaginning: (as long as someone can decipher the Euhemerism) shows the Order from Chaos, the organization of the Heavens, and the role of the Gods as well as Odin's position as God/Chieftain. Note: I think the V√∂lsunga saga in general presents a majority of the folklore and cultural setting that would represent all Germanic peoples. https://t.me/hammerandvajra

I‚Äôve been noticing a trend among pagan circles to vehemently reject, or attempt to disprove, our Indo-European ancestry, oddly enough just as it was proven that the Indo-Europeans originated in Europe with the Sredny Stog Culture. Attempting to denounce Indo-European heritage as non-native is pointless. It seems like a lot of them don‚Äôt like to admit any relation to Iranians or Indians. It should be a source of pride that our ancestors conquered half of the known world, before they‚Äôd even figured out how to work with iron.

The Saga of Hadding in the Gesta Danorum contains a lesser-known attestation of Hel. Hadding encounters an old woman (Hel) carrying herbs, and asks where she got them in winter. She takes him with her underground, through a dark path to a sunny region where the herbs grew. They encounter noblemen, and warriors in battle, and cross a bridge over a river filled with weapons (Gj√∂ll), until they come to a wall. She rips the head off a rooster and throws it over the wall, and it comes back to life, and they hear it crow over the wall. While the V√∂luspa and Gylfaginning describe the horrors of N√°str√∂nd in greater detail, the Saga of Hadding paints a far more benevolent picture of Hel; a home of the ancestors, with an opportunity for reincarnation.

The runic Forsaringen (Forsa Ring), made in the 9th Century, is the oldest surviving record of Old Norse Law. It appears to have been used to record a charge and/or order to restore a ritual site (v√©). The inscription reads; ‚ÄúOne ox and two aura (in fine) (to?) staf (or) aura staf (in fine) for the restoration of a cult site (v√©) in a valid state for the first time; two oxen and four aura for the second time; but for the third time four oxen and eight aura; and all property in suspension, if he doesn‚Äôt make right. That, the people are entitled to demand, according to the law of the people that was decreed and ratified before. But they made (the ring/statement), Anund from T√•sta, and Ofeg from Hjorsta. But Vibj√∂rn carved.‚Äù Translated by Stefan Brink. The projection in the middle resembles Thor‚Äôs hammer; likely a reference to Thor‚Äôs role of upholding justice and law, as attested in the Gylfaginning.

Following the Battle of Maserfield, Penda took his time killing Oswald, hacking off each of his limbs, and finally his head. A raven picked up one of Oswald‚Äôs severed arms, but dropped it into a large ash tree, where it was later recovered and made into a Christian relic. This made the tree and spring next to it both a pagan and Christian holy site, as the water from the spring was said to produce miracles, such as curing eye problems. However, well into the Middle Ages, people would be arrested for performing witchcraft (pagan bl√≥ts?) at Oswald‚Äôs tree. The location of the tree is no longer known, but the town of Oswestry, Shropshire, is named after it.

Another example of the Gravettian ‚ÄúFemme √† la Corne‚Äù (woman with the horn) motif. The image of a woman with a drinking horn is echoed in later Bronze Age and Germanic art.

This Gravettian limestone carving is known as the Venus of Laussel, carved around 25,000 years ago in Dordogne, France. The horn in her hand appears to be an early drinking horn, and the ritual use of drinking horns may stretch back further than we‚Äôd ever imagined.

·õü·õä·õè·ö®·ö±·ö® / ·õñ·ö©·õã·õè·ö±·õñ Ostara, spelled ƒíostre in Old English, is the Germanic goddess of the dawn, the shining one who revives the land after winter. The most well known source on her is Bede, who wrote that the pagan Anglo Saxons held feasts in her honour during ƒíosturm≈çna√æ (likely April), which was replaced by Paschal Month and later Easter after the Christian takeover. Jacob Grimm also wrote that Ostaram≈çna√æ was celebrated on the continent, with feasts, games and bonfires in April/May. Some modern playgans egregiously claim that ƒíostre was an invention of Bede, despite the fact that the dawn goddess appears in virtually every branch of Indo-European religion, and in the Rig Veda, Ushas is mentioned more than any other goddess. In Deutsche Mythologie, Jacob Grimm dug further into continental etymological evidence. He notes that in Old High German, the term √¥star (Old Norse/Gothic: austra/√°ustr) ‚Äúexpresses movement towards the rising sun.‚Äù He also noted the many similarities to the Slavic goddess Vesna, and a deity named Austri is mentioned in Gylfaginning, which Sturluson describes as a ‚Äúspirit of light‚Äù. Ostara has several direct cognates; Eos (Greek), Aurora (Roman), Vesna or Zarya (Slavic) and Ushas (Vedic). Her reconstructed Proto Indo European name would be Hausos. In Mahayana and Vajrayana Buddhism, She‚Äôs known as Marici. Ostara‚Äôs sacred animal is the hare. Both in England and Germany, imagery of hares and rabbits were always associated with the spring festivals, going as far back as the Stone Age. As hares are some of the first animals to come out of hibernation, an old German folk tradition said that their hopping is what awakens Ostara from her winter slumber. HƒÅl wes √æu ƒíostre! ·õâ

Regarding Icelandic stave magic. Icelandic magical staves have always been a controversial topic in modern Heathen circles. Many will argue until they‚Äôre blue in the face that they are ‚ÄúChristian‚Äù, as staves used in later Icelandic magic bear resemblance to the contents of the Key of Solomon. But first, let‚Äôs look at the Key of Solomon itself. The magical staves in the Key of Solomon are essentially reinterpretations of ancient Greek, Roman and Mesopotamian magical symbols, such as Roman Charakt√™res, collected and recorded in Hebrew by Jewish and Arab chroniclers in the Byzantine Empire. As well as Icelandic magic, the Key also heavily influenced Kabbalah, and later Islamic mysticism. Several rituals in the Lesser Key involve invoking demons, and the Greater Key deals with the proper format for making sacrifices of food and animals to these spirits and demons, as well as invoking the planets named after the Roman pantheon. (That‚Äôs not very Christian, I must say.) While the language changed, hiding its contents under a thin veneer of Abrahamism; Hebrew language, association with King Solomon, and a passage advising the reader to ask for God‚Äôs protection before summoning a demon; the roots of the Key of Solomon are very much pagan, making it an extremely controversial work for centuries. Now, let‚Äôs look at the √Ügishj√°lmur, the ‚ÄúHelm of Awe‚Äù. The term ‚ÄúHelm of Awe‚Äù was recorded around 200 years earlier in the F√°fnism√°l, denoting a helmet, or stave, worn by F√°fnir; ‚ÄúThe fear-helm I wore to afright mankind, While guarding my gold I lay; Mightier seemed I than any man, For a fiercer never I found.‚Äù ~F√°fnism√°l 16, Bellows In ancient India, a nearly identical stave appeared called the Asht√°nga Yantra, each arm representing Shiva‚Äôs Trishul. The Yantra ‚Äúdetains the word in the mouth of the enemy‚Äù, striking fear into opponents. The √Ügishj√°lmur is one stave which confirms that the roots of some of these staves are Indo-European. An important thing to remember about Iceland is, for centuries, it was one of the few places where folk magic was openly practiced. Iceland only officially accepted Christianity because of pressure from king Olaf II of Norway, and many ancient traditions persisted far out of the sight of puritanical continental Europe for generations. The witch hysteria that swept across Europe and the Colonies didn‚Äôt reach Iceland until the 17th Century. And until then, practice, research and development of these magical traditions continued. Due to the destruction of countless pagan records during the Middle Ages, the few surviving grimoires such as the Key of Solomon were used by Icelandic sorcerers to fill in the gaps. While staves like the Vegvis√≠r are in no way Viking Age symbols, they are the result of a continuation of much older magical traditions.

While vandalism of pagan shrines and temples often goes unpunished, I suspect this may be because a lot of people don‚Äôt know how to (legally) deal with it. Either we fight back against religious discrimination, or it will escalate. ·õ¶

cleaned_message: An interesting early Bronze Age axe from F√•rdrup, Denmark. It‚Äôs very similar in shape to earlier Stone Age axe-hammers, and being made from solid bronze, it was likely a prestige item. It was found buried along with other votive offerings in a field.

An incomplete Viking Age or Anglo Scandinavian scabbard chape, with two beast heads, perhaps Freki and Geri. The ‚Äúalmond-shaped‚Äù eyes are very characteristic of late Viking Age Ringerike and Urnes-style art. 10-11th Century.
More scenes from The Ring of the Nibelungs by Franz Stassen.

Freki is the name of one of Odin's wolves. Meaning 'greedy', Freki derived from the proto Germanic word *frekaz - whilst frek√¥ (deriving from *frekaz) could mean eager, bold warrior or a wolf. In OE we can find cognates in fr√¶c and frec (greedy or bold) - whilst the name freca, which is attested in Beowulf could mean wolf or warrior.
A raven-head terminal from a more detailed Anglo Saxon bucket mount. The curvature of the back indicates it was mounted on a vessel.

An Anglo Saxon bronze mount, likely from a stave-built bucket, with a depiction of Woden. The terminals form two raven heads, the rivet holes forming the eyes. In the middle is a moustached face, with the right eye much smaller than the left. Found in Rocklands, Norfolk, 6-7th Century. ·ö©

An X-ray of one of the swords from the Salme ship burial revealed this intricate design; two composite faces, with the beards morphing into jaws. This could depict Freki and Geri, and/or Odin as Tveggi.

Tveggi (double, twofold) most likely refers to Odin‚Äôs dual nature; for example, as a God governing both death and war, and creation and healing. Painting: Wodan heilt Balders Pferd by Carl Emil Doepler, 1905.

This reminds me; in Nj√°l‚Äôs Saga, Hjalti Skeggison writes a nasty poem in which he calls Odin a bitch, for which he‚Äôs sentenced to outlawry. Back then, comparing a man to a female animal such as a bitch (ON: bikkja/t√≠k) or mare (ON: m√©rr) implied passive homosexuality and effeminacy, that the man was ‚Äúbred‚Äù, and was a most grievous insult. Hjalti wouldn‚Äôt have been outlawed if it were true. ·ö¨

Certain people would have you believe that one of the names of Odin, ON "Tveggi" means ‚Äúhermaphrodite.‚Äù It is actually a poetic heiti which means ‚Äútwofold one‚Äùand is cognate with Sanskrit dvay√° 'twofold, double'. None of the uses of this word of which I am aware implies that Odin is a hermaphrodite or cross dresser. So why is it that people are pushing this?

Several amulets shaped like miniature fire steels have been found from the Viking Age, sometimes alongside Thor‚Äôs Hammers. Thinking about the folk tale from Sm√•land, connecting sheet lightning with Freyja‚Äôs fire steel, these amulets may very well have been a symbol of Freyja.

‚ÄúWhen as a boy I was visiting the old Proud-Katrina, I was afraid of lightning like all boys in those days. When the sheet lightning flared at the night, Katrina said: "Don't be afraid little child, it is only Freyja who is out making fire with steel and flintstone to see if the rye is ripe. She is kind to people and she is only doing it to be of service,‚Äù - A recount of Sm√•land Swedish folklore told by Johan Alfred G√∂th This bit of folklore explains certain graves that contain firesteel amulets. It is interesting how it mentions here that she checks on rye because in German folklore we see a figure known as the Rye Mother (Roggenmuhme). The Rye Mother shows a few christianized elements such as kidnapping children, being depicted as dark and witch-like, killing rye with her touch. However, German farmers would give sections of unharvested rye as an offering to appease her for a good harvest. She is also associated with rainfall. This is no doubt a post Christian conception of Freyja.

Celtic ‚Äúfobs‚Äù are a mysterious type of artifact, the original purpose of which remains unknown. They always consist of a large, decorated openwork face with a large suspension loop on the back. url_description: Forefather is an Viking/Anglo-Saxon Metal band from Surrey, England. The band was formed in September 1997 by two brothers, who adopted the stage names Athelstan and Wulfstan. They recorded their first album Deep Into Time at their home studio (known as The Croft) in August 1998 and eventually released it in March 1999 on their own label Angelisc Enterprises to reasonable critical acclaim. Their follow-up The Fighting Man was released in October 2000, and owing to improved equipment purchased in part from the sales of their first album was of markedly better sound quality, and was positively received by the underground metal press. At this time the band chose to release a collection of demo recordings entitled Legends Untold on the German Millennium Metal label. Engla Tocyme (The Coming of the English) was recorded in late 2001 and released in March 2002 along with a re-issue of their first album Deep Into Time, with improved artwork and a bonus track. Their latest album, Ours is the Kingdom was released in June 2004, marking the bands move to the respected Karmageddon Media label, and the subsequent improvement in the general quality of artwork and packaging this afforded. As of this time, the brothers are working on a fifth full-length album, after taking some time out to work with the Folk metal supergroup Folkearth. Forefather released the new album, Steadfaston the Seven Kingdoms label in 2008, and has recieved very good reviews in the metal media. Most of the bands songs are impossible to perform live with just two people. They use a drum-machine in the studio, and have revealed in interviews that they do not like the idea of guest musicians working on the project, preferring to keep it In the family, as it were

Is Loki a weaver? Well he is certainly a weaver of lies and deceit! The Faroese word Lokkanet (Lokke's web) meant cobweb, just as the Swedish word lokkan√§t (Loki‚Äôs net) is a spiders web. Lokka / Loka is believed to come from the PGmc *l≈´kanƒÖ which gives us our modern word ‚Äòlock‚Äô and means to bind or hold together. It seems only fitting then that Loki‚Äôs fate was to be bound to a rock as punishment.

cleaned_message: Speaking of comparative mythology, I‚Äôve found PDFs of several of Georges Dum√©zil‚Äôs books, I will share them momentarily. For those unfamiliar, Georges Dum√©zil was a religious studies scholar and mythologist who was a pioneer in the field of Indo-European studies. He was known for his ‚Äútrifunctional hypothesis‚Äù; that three core societal functions, such as priests/sorcerers, warriors and farmers/tradesmen, manifested themselves in Indo-European society as well as among the Gods. For example, Odin fulfills the role of the priest/sorcerer who governs cosmic and judicial order, Thor fulfills the role of the warrior who protects the Nine Realms through his physical might and prowess, and Freyr fulfills the role of the farmer/tradesman who governs wealth and fertility.
A Viking Age strap slide, found in Rocklands, Norfolk, 8-11th Century. Borre-style decoration, with two facing beasts. A similar example was found attached to a belt, behind the buckle.
An Iron Age rectangular brooch, found in Sandeg√•rd, Bornholm, Denmark. The design consists of two interlaced birds, whose bodies form a bearded face in the centre.

The purpose of any real comparative studies shouldn‚Äôt be to devalue or undermine our own traditions-they should reinforce them. One of the most common arguments you‚Äôll hear from e-Christians, Wiccatrus, and other pagan subverters is that you can‚Äôt know what our ancestors believed because the Eddas and Sagas were recorded by Christians. But, when you see so many parallels in our own lore which harmonize with the lore of related peoples, you‚Äôll see that‚Äôs not true at all. Even without going outside of Europe, you‚Äôll see very similar recurring themes in, for example, the Iliad and Mabinogion. The Germanic faith and worldview are quite thoroughly expressed in the Eddas and Sagas. There is absolutely enough in them to coherently reconstruct them, and even the beliefs that are more sparsely attested, for example, the immortality of the soul/ƒÄtman (which is attested in the Gylfaginning) are attested among related Indo-European peoples, such as the Celts and Dacians. ·õâ
More illustrations for Der Ring des Nibelungen by Franz Stassen.
An Anglo Saxon sleeve clasp set, found in Norfolk, 5-7th Century. The quatrefoil design is uncommon on sleeve clasps, and similar to finds from Nydam Mose.

The impressive Hillersj√∂ Runestone is the second longest runic inscription in Sweden. It was found on the Snotasta√∞ir/Snottsta Farm, recording a family‚Äôs lineage and inheritance rights to the farm. The inscription reads; ‚ÄúGeirmundr got Geirlaug in her maidenhood. Then they got a son, before he drowned. And then the son died. Then she got Gu√∞r√≠kr. Then they got children. And one maid lived; she was called Inga. Ragnfastr of Snutasta√∞ir got her. Then he died, and thereafter the son. And the mother came to inherit from her son. Then she got Eir√≠kr. Then she died. Then Geirlaug came to inherit from Inga, her daughter. √ûorbj√∏rn Skald carved the runes.‚Äù

Illustrations for Der Ring des Nibelungen by Franz Stassen, 1914. There are quite a few, I will post more in the weeks to come.

A bronze pendant from Kievan Rus, with the eight-armed variation of the Swastika which would later become known as the Kolovrat. Found in Chernihiv, 9-11th Century. *While the name ‚ÄúKolovrat‚Äù is relatively recent, the symbol was found throughout Kievan Rus, as well as Ancient Greek pottery. It was likely intended to be a doubled-up Swastika.

Mosaics in Felix Romuliana, a complex of an imperial palace and temples built by Galerius in 298AD in Gamzigrad, Serbia. The several mosaics feature a hexagonal variation of the Labyrinth, numerous swastikas and solar symbols, and an image of Dionysus. It was abandoned in the 7th Century with the invasion of the Slavic tribes, and was rediscovered in 1835.

A Viking Age Jellinge-style disc brooch, found in Thetford, Norfolk, 9-10th Century. Made of bronze, lots of gilding remaining. It‚Äôs got the popular Jellinge-style backwards facing animal; likely a wolf, with the pointed ears and long tongue hanging out. This is by far the nicest example of this type I‚Äôve seen.
A strange Viking Age bronze axe amulet, with a one-eyed face of Odin on the blade. Found in Norway, 9-10th Century. ·ö¨

A Bronze Age to Iron Age ‚Äúvotive wheel‚Äù, found in Lincolnshire. Several examples have been found in burials and at the sites of temples in Britain, France and Central Europe, and one in Norfolk was found alongside a figure of Jupiter. Votive wheels have been found in Greece, with inscriptions dedicating them to Zeus, Apollo and Hercules.

This is the only complete surviving Roman Draco standard, seen by a friend in the British Museum. The Roman Draco was likely based on the Dacian Draco. The Dacians (like virtually every Indo-European culture) worshipped wolves, and the Draco was designed to make a howling noise when the wind blew through it, or when it was carried by a charioteer or cavalryman at high speeds.

If you‚Äôre looking to set up a home altar, especially on a tighter budget, a great place to start is your local Indian market. Find one which sells puja supplies, and you‚Äôll find very similar ritual tools to what out ancestors are attested as having used, such as brass and copper bowls for offerings, altar bells, incense and holders, and oil lamps, often for a very reasonable price. The Sagas frequently mention a source of fire on altars, the Kjalnesinga Saga mentions a copper offering bowl, and the Gesta Danorum mentions ringing of bells; all things which continue to be used in Hindu and Buddhist worship today.

A beautiful Anglo Saxon saucer brooch, from the Cotswolds burial ground, 5-6th Century. This particular design appears to have been a locally produced variation, and appears to depict the Little Dipper revolving around the North Star. The hole in the middle would likely have originally held a precious stone, such as a garnet.

Another Anglo Saxon saucer brooch, from the Cotswolds burial ground, 5-6th Century. The plain design is quite unusual for a saucer brooch; I suspect it would have had a coating of silver or gold. The hole looks countersunk, and likely would have held a garnet.

A Migration Era brooch from Farsund, Norway. The head plate has a very Odinic motif; a bearded face, whose beard morphs into two wolf heads (note the pointed ears in the corners of the panel). The bow is adorned with several fylfots, and the entire outer edge is adorned with multiple Salin-I style beasts.
Dangerous Lands, by Alexander Groznov.

An early Anglo Saxon disc brooch from the Cotswolds burial ground, 5-6th Century. This pattern, with five ring-and-dot decorations forming a simple sun cross, was a very early one. The warrior buried here would have likely still had Celtic blood dripping from his sword. ‚®Å

A closer look at the sword pommel from the Cotswolds Anglo Saxon warrior‚Äôs burial. Classic cocked-hat form, with beautiful punched ring and dot decoration, and deep concave grooves adorning the edges. Made of bronze, with a tin coating. 5-6th Century.

*Those wondering: yes, the collection from the burial ground was offered to a museum, which recorded each item through the British Museum‚Äôs PAS, but both declined to keep them (fools). The finder tells me that Anglo Saxon specialist Matt Bunker is coming to help us record the site and finds, and the British Museum may survey the site in the spring.

This Anglo Saxon sword pommel, brooch and buckle were found within feet of each other in a burial ground containing a warrior and two noble women in the Cotswolds, near Ebrington, undoubtedly belonging to the same 5-6th Century warrior, holding his cloak and sword belt together. All three have the same white metal coating; likely tin. Disc brooches are one of the few types of brooches found in male Anglo Saxon burials.
Mega find just landed. Stay tuned‚Ä¶
An illustration for the Alv√≠ssm√°l by Franz Stassen.

I should reify my position for those unclear; Never once did I claim that ‚Äúall Gods are one‚Äù, what I did was express agreement with Cicero‚Äôs De Natura Deorum, and the Gylfaginning, that Gods may be known to multiple (related) peoples under different names in their respective languages. The n√≠√∞ings who continue to spread lies about me should thank whatever Gods they purport to believe in that they don‚Äôt live in a historical pagan society. In pagan Germanic societies, men being indirect in conflict, which included spreading slander behind someone‚Äôs back, was considered ergi and was grounds for duels, fines, even outlawry. ·õ¶
An embossed leather bag from a noble burial in Krefeld-Gellep, northwestern Germany, 6-7th Century.

‚ÄúWotan disappeared when his oaks fell and appeared again when the Christian God proved too weak to save Christendom from fratricidal slaughter‚Ä¶the one-eyed old hunter, on the edge of the German forest, laughed and saddled Sleipnir.‚Äù ~Carl Jung Painting: Die Wilde Jagd by Franz von Stuck, 1889. ·ö®

Along with the Storm Ring/Sun Halo, the refraction of light by cirrostratus clouds can give the sun the appearance of having six or more distinct rays around it. This phenomenon often precedes rainfall and storms, and undoubtedly would have inspired variations of the Sunwheel, the Wheel of Taranis, the Slavic Perunika, and perhaps even the Hagal rune. ·öº
Scythian variations of the zoomorphic fylfot.

The reality of Vikings in Africa‚Ä¶ A recurring Old Norse term for Africans was Bl√°menn; blue men (singular: bl√°ma√∞r). This would likely have been because they encountered the nomadic Tuareg tribe in North Africa, who have traded goods such as textiles, cosmetics and slaves between the Sahel and Mediterranean for centuries, and famously wear robes dyed with indigo. The Orkneyinga Saga mentions bl√°menn fighting Earl Rognvald alongside Saracens (Arabs) in Galicia. According to the Annals of Ulster, following the raid on Mauritania, Vikings brought back African slaves and sold them for an increased price in Dublin, alongside textiles. One Viking Age skeleton with African facial features has been unearthed in York; possibly a √ær√¶ll captured during this raid. In the Kjalnesinga Saga, King Harald has a bl√°ma√∞r slave which he makes B√∫i fight, after burning down the temple in Iceland. Descriptions of bl√°menn usually mention two key features; no understanding of the Old Norse language, and a large mouth. Later on, ‚Äúbl√°ma√∞r‚Äù was used to refer to more monstrous things, such as trolls and draugar, and later, demons. In the Eyrbyggja Saga, when they dug up Thorolf Half-foot following the hauntings, his body had become blue and bloated, but had not begun to decompose-which indicated he had risen as a draugr.
Petroglyphs in the Gegham Mountains, Armenia, 8-5th millennium BC.

An amazing find from Denmark; a brooch with a raven eating a fallen warrior. In the Saga of Egill Skallagrimsson, a kenning for a warrior was Hrafngrennir (raven feeder), along with Ulfgrennir (wolf feeder) and Arngrennir (eagle feeder). Each of these animals were heavily associated with Odin, and were known to follow warbands, and appear after a battle to eat the dead. In Celtic paganism, the Morrigan takes the form of a raven to carry the souls of the dead to the afterlife; and the raven on this brooch does look like it could be carrying the body off. Another kenning was Feitir Folkstara (fattener of the war-starling). Conversely, an Old Norse insult was Hrafnasueltir (raven starver), implying cowardice. ·õ¶

Happy Solm≈çna√æ! (Sol-Month) The name was recorded by the Christian Anglo-Saxon scholar Bede in his treatise De temporum ratione (The Reckoning of Time), saying that "Sol-Monath can be said to be the month of cakes, which were offered to their Gods" In Old English, ‚ÄúSol‚Äù is mostly used to refer to soil or mud. Implying that this month is sacred to the Earth-Mother Goddess. However, this could only be one of the meanings of the word in this context. ‚ÄúSol‚Äù is also believed to mean ‚Äúcake‚Äù and can perhaps be linked to the English custom known as souling. In this tradition one would go house to house and sing songs where the guests would be gifted ‚Äúsoul cakes‚Äù in exchange for prayers. This tradition is usually credited to be Christian, but as with most Christian traditions, this one may indeed be Pagan. So be sure to give an offering of cakes to the Earth-Mother.

In defense of the Prose Edda‚Ä¶ Much like S√¶mundr Fr√≥√∞i, Snorri Sturluson‚Äôs goal with his Edda was to preserve Old Icelandic alliterative verse poetry, which was vanishing along with Iceland‚Äôs pagan traditions, from which it was inseparable. The vast majority of surviving alliterative poetry was pagan, although the Sk√°ldskaparm√°l contains a few fragments of Christian alliterative poetry. The Gylfaginning, while written largely in prose, contains several fragments of poetry, as well as kennings and honourifics, a common theme in Norse poetry. And the H√°ttatal is essentially an instruction manual for writing Old Icelandic poetry. The euhemeristic references to the Trojan War in the Gylfaginning would have undoubtedly been added for Snorri‚Äôs own safety, and to prevent his work from being suppressed by the Church. These references really don‚Äôt flow with the rest of the writing. Pic: an illustration for the Gylfaginning from the Codex Upsaliensis, 14th Century.

Here's all three volumes of Alison Finlay and Anthony Faulkes's excellent translation of the Heimskringla. Volume I covers the Ynglinga Saga to Olaf Tryggvason's defeat at the Battle of Svolder, Volume II covers the reign of Olaf II, and Volume III covers from the reign of Magnus the Good to Magnus V.

Carrying a ‚Äúpocket God‚Äù is indeed a historical practice, as attested in the Hallfre√∞ar Saga. Hallfre√∞r Vandr√¶√∞ask√°ld was a court skald of H√°kon Sigur√∞arson, and later Olaf Tryggvason. He initially fled to Iceland to avoid being forced to convert to Christianity, but later agreed to convert in exchange for becoming Olaf‚Äôs court sk√°ld. Vandr√¶√∞ask√°ld, ‚Äútroublesome poet‚Äù, was a nickname Olaf gave him on account of his reluctance to commit to Christianity; an evident theme in his surviving poems. Later in the Saga, he‚Äôs accused of carrying a small carved figure of Thor, and performing rituals with it in secret. His poetry survives in the Hallfre√∞ar Saga, Heimskringla, and Sk√°ldskaparm√°l. ‚ÄúThe whole race of men to win Odin's grace has wrought poems (I recall the exquisite works of my forebears); but with sorrow, for well did Vi√∞rir's power please the poet, do I conceive hate for the first husband of Frigg, now I serve Christ.‚Äù ~Hallfre√∞r Vandr√¶√∞ask√°ld, Lausav√≠sur

The Goths of the Wielbark Culture built very similar stone ship burials to the examples found in southern Scandinavia, and built a series of wooden roads and bridges along the Amber Road.
PSA: these little brass incense holders can be had for around a dollar a piece on eBay or Amazon, or around $10 with an ashtray. These designs can hold an incense cone, or multiple incense sticks.

While we don‚Äôt have any concrete records of Germanic peoples using incense, it was widely used as an offering by pagan Romans and Greeks. So much so that the early Roman church initially suppressed its use, saying that it attracted demons (Gods?). It‚Äôs entirely possible that the Vikings would have acquired incense in their travels, and Germanic auxiliaries would have prayed at a Roman shrine to Nehalennia or Hercules Magusanus with incense at some point. If they had access to incense, they undoubtedly would‚Äôve used it. Incense remains highly popular in Hinduism and Buddhism, and the first known use of incense was in the Indus Valley. Interestingly enough, as incense was widely believed to purify and sacralize a space for worship, recent studies have shown that certain incenses, such as frankincense and dhoop, will kill airborne bacteria and fungi. Kedarnath Temple is an ancient temple dedicated to Shiva, built around one of the 12 Jyotrlingas. Some believe it was built in the 8th Century by Adi Shankara, others say it was built earlier by the Pandavas to atone for their actions in the Mahabharata War. From the 14-18th Century, the temple was buried under a glacier, and was unscathed despite the ice shifting. In 2013, flash floods struck Uttarakhand. As the floodwaters surged towards the temple, a large rock rolled down from the mountains, and came to a stop mere feet from the temple, diverting the floodwaters and protecting it-and everyone taking refuge inside. With the momentum the rock would have been carrying, it should have crushed the temple. What happened that day is widely considered to have been an act of divine intervention.

Most recently, a man named Marcos Pantoja spent 12 years living with a pack of wolves in the Sierra Morena mountains of Spain, after his foster father died when he was seven. Following his ‚Äúrescue‚Äù, he said he was quite disappointed with human society, and how cold and callous it was compared to his wolves. In India, a boy who was subsequently named Dina Sanichar was found living with a pack of wolves in 1867 in Uttar Pradesh, and after hearing his story in his travels, Rudyard Kipling created his character Mowgli.
