The Turkic Oghuz Epic contains a similar account to Lopichis‚Äôs journey with the wolf in the Historia Langobardorum. In the Oghuz Epic, in what is now northern China, a village was devastated in a raid, and only one boy survived. A female wolf, named Asena, finds the injured boy and nurses him back to health. He then impregnates this divine wolf Asena, who travels to the Qocho Mountains, inhabited by the Tocharians, and gives birth to ten hybrid boys. One, named Ashina, became the progenitor of the G√∂kt√ºrks. The name G√∂kt√ºrks means ‚ÄúCelestial Turks‚Äù. The first G√∂kt√ºrks settled in the Altai Mountains, and became known as expert iron workers, which is supported by the archeological record. Asena resurfaces later in the Ergenekon Legend. Following a defeat, the G√∂kt√ºrks take refuge in the Ergenekon Valley for four centuries, but Tengri has other plans for them. Asena returns, and leads them out-and they proceed to form what we now call the First Turkic Khaganate, which spawned many great nations. In multiple Turkic legends, wolves are divine messengers, appearing to guide their folk out of danger, and to glory. Chinggis Khaan was said to have a soul of a wolf, and the wolf remains the national animal of Turkey. The Bashkirs, a Kipchak-descended Turkic group living in Russia, believed a divine wolf descended from the sky to guide them, and the name Bashkirs means ‚Äúthose with a wolf on their heads‚Äù in reference to this.

Odin‚Äôs wolf as a divine messenger‚Ä¶ In the 5th century, the Langobards began their southward migration to Italia, and came into conflict with the Avars. In the Historia Langobardorum, a man named Leupchis had five sons who were abducted by the Avars in 610AD. One of them, Lopichis, managed to escape. On his way back, he met a wolf who guided him back to his family. This wolf, ‚Äúsibi divinitus datum esse‚Äù, may well have been a divine messenger from Odin. ‚ÄúWhen he had gone and escaped, carrying only a quiver and bow and a little food for the journey, and did not at all know where he was going, a wolf came to him and became the companion of his journey and his guide. Seeing that it proceeded before him, and often looked behind and stood with him when he stood, and went ahead when he advanced, he understood that it had been given to him from heaven to show to him the way.‚Äù ~History of the Langobards, Fouke translation ·ö®

The One-eyed God: Odin and the Indo-Germanic Mannerbunde, by Kris Kershaw. A detailed study into the worship of Odin, connections with worship of Rudra/Shiva, and wolf warrior cults among the Germanic tribes and other Indo-European peoples.

A possible insight into the berserkrgang phenomenon‚Ä¶ In the east of the Indo-European world, certain Shaiva Traditions encourage ascetic, monastic lifestyles. For example, on the hardcore end, the Aghori. Aghori Sadhus will go so far as to take only what they can carry, leave society altogether, and live in caves and mountains, like Shiva himself, believed to live an ascetic life atop Mount Kailash. In Germanic, Celtic and Slavic traditions, priests, shamans, and some elite warriors, were known to live on the fringes of society. The Slavic term for a pagan priest, Volkhv, is derived from the term for wolf. Certain followers of Rudra/Shiva, especially his aspect of Kala Bhairava, would live as metaphorical dogs and wolves, likely a continuation of the Vedic-era Vratya tradition. One thing is consistent in multiple period Roman accounts-elite Germanic, Celtic and Dacian warriors who fought fearlessly without armour, and in the case of the Gauls, even without clothing. With my studies into Shaivism, a theory I have is, these elite warriors‚Äô training may have been similar to the practices of the Aghori; a period away from all of the distractions and comforts of civilization. Only you and your vigorous pursuit of the Gods. The reason they may have chosen to go into battle without armour is, in addition to intimidating the enemy, this exposed, frenzied, feral state is when they may have been the absolute closest to Odin (or Lugus, Zalmoxis, or Rudra, depending on the culture), the God they wished to invoke, and channel, on the battlefield.

Divisive, strawman, and bias statements I have seen recently about syncretism I will clear up...yet again....in good faith. (Some may be just misunderstandings) 1.(Syncretism destroyed culture, biodiversity etc) No it actually creates culture. We wouldn't have the various forms of Paganism we have now if it weren't for Indo-European and other groups merging in a syncretic manner. Do you think our ancestors just gave up their Gods when they met another tribe? The IE spread out, each branch meeting with other Old European, Near Eastern, or Asiatic group and formed a merger and unique branch. Though having the same root origins on at core levels. Each should be respected, regardless of their commonalities, this is the true diversity I have been speaking of for years. Though their commonalities are important for understanding and certain reconstruction. Any so called Indo-European scholar, or syncretic practitioner saying otherwise is wrong, and I haven't met many who don't think this way. 2) ( Syncretics or those of Indo-European studies think lore, myth, origins, cosmology came into being on the spot with comparative agenda and allegory.) No, yet again this is the evolution of "myth". As people migrated and met with or merged with / absorbed or subjugated other tribes their founding myths and cosmology were adjusted by the environment they resided in and adapted to, the other tribes and their heritage as well, and the shared commonality of certain origins. These were all crafted overtime and yet again like I said above very unique in many ways. Though the reason they have so much basic and foundational Gods, cosmology, terms, metaphysics, allegory, metaphors, and values are due to certain direct common origins forming a core part. These "myths" were indeed crafted, and passed on orally at first as they developed / evolved. 3) ( all who practice syncretism are Platonist and think the Gods are metaphors for perennial truths) (apparently thinking STJ said this?) First off, Plato lives in these peoples head rent free. I know STJ had a good set of rebuttals regarding Plato, but I wouldn't consider him a Platonist, if he is then that is his stance to argue. Plato considered the Gods to be real so this point makes no sense to me. STJ thinks the Gods are real. I believe the Gods are real. Just because I practice syncretic faith to approach the Gods doesn't mean I'm saying others have to. The majority of Europeans are a merger of different forms of European (Old Europe + Indo-European √ó different European branches) are they supposed to go on a purity spiral and stop worshipping Gods that are IE or Old European if they have an admixture? Origins of the Christmas tree. The modern Christmas tree is an amalgamation of several possible ancient traditions, both Pagan and Christian. One likely origin is in Ancient Rome. Wreaths made of evergreen trees and plants were made during Saturnalia. Aurelian suggested that Saturnalia should be held alongside Christmas in order to compete with the growing Christian church, but this resulted in many Saturnalia traditions being adopted by the Christians. Similarly, in the Viking Age, H√°kon the Good decreed J√≥l was to be held alongside Christmas in the hopes of winning Pagans over to Christianity, which led to J√≥l traditions being absorbed into Christmas. In Ancient Egypt and the Near East, evergreens were associated with rebirth and reincarnation, which was easily absorbed into early Christianity, wherein it represents the rebirth of Christ. In parts of Europe, evergreen decorations were said to keep the Devil away in the Middle Ages. Of course, the Germanic and Baltic peoples practiced tree worship. Decorating trees during Wassailing and placing offerings in the branches are likely a carryover from Pagan times. Some claim the Christmas tree is in memory of St. Boniface cutting down √ûonar‚Äôs oak, but let us remember, that was an oak, and the Germanic peoples bashed St. Boniface‚Äôs head in and continued to resist Christian rule long after the oak fell. The inversion of a deciduous vs an evergreen tree may be a Christian thing. Some also claim it was originally a representation of Yggrdrasil; it‚Äôs impossible to say. The modern Christmas tree originated in Germany and Livonia in the 16th Century, and Martin Luther is credited with its invention. Which is curious, as the Bible forbids cutting and decorating a tree (Jeremiah 10:3-4). The Bremen Guild Chronicle mentions a tree being brought inside and decorated with foods, such as apples and nuts, and the guild members‚Äô children would eat them on Christmas Day. Afterwards, the tree was burned‚Ä¶perhaps a remnant of an ancient solar festival? There‚Äôs a similar practice in Poland; during the Koliada festival, an evergreen branch is suspended from the rafters and decorated. This originated in pagan times, to bring a good harvest in the new year. The Christmas tree itself is not an ancient tradition; it‚Äôs the result of a combination of both ancient Pagan folk traditions, and medieval Christian traditions. The mistletoe is very likely a Pagan remnant; celebrating the inevitable return of Baldr. In Ancient Rome, the mistletoe represented peace and reconciliation. ·õâ Go√∞an J√≥l! Gl√¶d Ge≈çl! Io Saturnalia! Merry Christmas!

M≈çdraniht, or Modranicht, ‚ÄúNight of the Mothers‚Äù, was a holy day observed by the pagan Anglo Saxons. According to Bede, it was celebrated ‚Äúthe year on the 8th calends of January, when we celebrate the birth of the Lord.‚Äù, which would have been the 25th of December. Bede suspected sacrifices were held on this night. One possibility is it may have been the Anglo Saxon equivalent of D√≠sabl√≥t, which was held before J√≥l in Scandinavia. It‚Äôs likely that it was connected to the worship of the Matres and Matronae (Mothers and Matrons). The Matres and Matronae are known from several altars across England, Germany and France, depicting three women; reminiscent of the Norns. Several altars depict them with headdresses characteristic of the Ubii, a Germanic tribe that lived along the Rhine, pointing to a Romano-Germanic origin. A few altars are inscribed with ‚ÄúMatronis Gabiabus‚Äù, the ‚Äúgiving mothers‚Äù. This also fits with Old Norse Gefn, an epithet of Freyja, meaning ‚ÄúShe who gives‚Äù, and Gefjon. A few of these altars appeared in Roman camps, and one near Hadrian‚Äôs Wall, possibly made by Germanic auxiliaries. Their placement around military sites suggests that the Mothers were not mere fertility deities, but also protectors, spinning the fates of the soldiers. Three goddesses ruling fate is recurring in Indo European religions; for example, the Norns, the Moirai, Parcae, Hekate, and the Sudiƒçka. The Slavic Sudiƒçka and Greek Moirai spin a thread as they foretell the child‚Äôs life, cutting it when the life will end. New parents would leave out offerings of food for the Sudiƒçka, hoping they would make favourable predictions. While M≈çdraniht is a more challenging one to recreate due to fragmentary knowledge, it can still be observed today. ·õâ

Log pulling, called Blukio Vilkimo in Lithuania and Bluka Vilk≈°ana in Latvia, is the Baltic equivalent of the Yule Log. On the winter solstice, a log or tree stump is dragged into the middle of a village, and burned to celebrate the return of the sun. It was believed that the stump could trap one‚Äôs misfortune, and even disease and evil spirits, and people would touch the log as it was dragged through the town, to transfer them to it before it was burned. Anything that they didn‚Äôt want to carry into the new year. The people who drag the log wear masks and costumes to scare away evil spirits, not unlike other winter processions across Europe. ·ö≤

S√≥narg√∂ltr: the Yule Boar. One historical Yule practice was, a boar would be led into the hall, and the people would lay their hands on it and publicly swear solemn oaths for the year ahead, known as heitstrenging, after which it was sacrificed and eaten. It was connected with the worship of Freyr, hence the boar. This practice is attested in the Hervarar Saga ok Hei√∞reks; every year, King Hei√∞rekr would sacrifice the largest boar he could find to Freyr on the eve of Yule. Beforehand, his men would lay their hands on its bristles and take oaths. Hei√∞rekr vowed to let any man go who could defeat him in a riddle contest; a vow he later breaks in the Saga when Odin defeats him and he strikes at him with his sword, and he dies shortly after. It is also attested in the Helgakvi√∞a Hj√∂rvar√∞ssonar, wherein King Hj√∂rvar√∞r‚Äôs men swear oaths on a sacred boar at the king‚Äôs Yule feast, and H√©√∞inn vows to marry Sv√°fa. We see a similar practice today in one form of Hindu Puja, where a coconut is used in place of a sacrificial animal. In the later Middle Ages, an enduring tradition was serving a boar‚Äôs head at Christmas feasts; Jacob Grimm believed this may have been a holdover from the ancient sacrifices, wherein the head would often be severed. While some of you may (understandably) not want to get and sacrifice a live boar, one day this winter, this could be observed with a ceremonial feast (maybe a ham?) and an offering to Freyr, and by making vows for the year ahead. ·õù

Another key difference between the Germanic pagan vs. Abrahamic worldview is that Germanic paganism is world-affirming vs. world-rejecting. Our ancestors did not see our world as inherently unjust, or something to be escaped from. While you may make it to the halls of the Gods after death, there was no way to guarantee this. Our ancestors also believed they may return to it before they earned their place in the higher realms. The Helgakvi√∞a Hundingsbana II and the √ûattr of Olaf Geirsta√∞-Alf both attest to not only the Germanic belief in reincarnation, but that they would reincarnate into their own bloodlines. Should they accrue honour and virtue in life, this would be passed down to their descendants, in the form of hamingja. And, should they live a dishonourable life, and tarnish their family name, they would find themselves sharing in their folks‚Äô misery. In 664AD, Wulfhere of Mercia inadvertently caused a pagan resurgence in East Anglia and Essex. As his missionaries worked to convert them, a plague swept through; and he explained to new converts that despite being ‚Äúsaved‚Äù, they would have to wait for their salvation until after they had died horribly. Led by Sighere, the East Saxons rejected Christianity and prayed to the Old Gods, choosing instead to fight for their lives and homeland, rather than banking on promises of a better afterlife.

An important thing to understand about the IE Pagan vs. Abrahamic worldview is, having your prayers answered doesn‚Äôt mean you‚Äôll be saved or exempt from hardships. In the Helgakvi√∞a Hundingsbana II, when Dagr prayed to Odin for revenge on his father‚Äôs killer, Odin gave him his spear. Across the IE world, when Parshuram wanted to rid the world of the corrupt Kshatriyas and prayed to Shiva, he gave him his axe. I understand a lot of pagans are ex-Christians, and coming into paganism without understanding this, and expecting the Gods to extricate you from life‚Äôs difficulties, may be part of what drives so many people to become bitter atheists, those who reduce the Gods to small, limited caricatures, or even to go back to another church. Our pagan ancestors did not pray to be saved from this life, and all of its beauties and horrors. Even if they were to make it to the halls of the Gods after death (which they had no guarantee of), they fought tooth and claw their entire lives to secure peace and prosperity for their folk, and for themselves, glory that would outlast death, and inspire their descendants to strive for higher things; and they prayed to their Gods to help them along the way. ·õâ

The Gyerim-ro Dagger is a dagger of likely Tocharian origin, found in a burial in Gyeongsang, South Korea. It bears a striking resemblance to daggers in Tocharian paintings in the Kizil Caves and Kumtura Caves, and was likely traded to Korea via the Silk Road.

In Scandinavia, St. Olaf gradually took the place of the cult of Thor. He was often depicted with an axe, and was invoked for many of the same roles as Thor; protection in battle, rain, harvests, and marriages.

Whenever you see something in pagan literature or folklore that resembles something you know from Christianity, there‚Äôs something that‚Äôs important to keep in mind. When you read through our primary sources, such as the Icelandic Sagas, you‚Äôll see a very common conversion tactic was that your king would come to your village with his personal warband and take hostages. A tactic the Carolingian Franks would use was to draw the men out of the villages, then send in more soldiers, and the men would return to find their loved ones at sword point. It‚Äôs easy to say you‚Äôd have been one of the ones who died at Verden, but if they had someone you cared about, well, that‚Äôs a completely different dynamic. What our ancestors did was convert, even superficially, but just enough to keep these tyrants happy enough that they‚Äôd let the hostages live, and they‚Äôd incorporate as much of their original culture as possible under a thin veneer of Christianity. Saints took the place of many Gods, St. Michael took the place of Thor, Mary took the place of Frigg, Ausa Vatni became baptism, and so on. When viewed through this lens, things make much more sense. And, it can help us extricate our own original practices.

‚Ä¶what‚Äôs really ironic is that I myself may have inadvertently started a lot of the theological infighting, drama and stupidity we‚Äôre seeing with pagans today a few months ago‚Ä¶by sharing a quote from this book. This is a period account from a living Roman pagan.

Nehalennia is a goddess presiding over the North Sea. Etymologically, her name means "She who is with the sea" from Proto-Germanic "nehwa" (close to) and "heli" (sea). This also fits with northern Celtic languages, combining the elements "ne-" (on/at) and "halen" (sea). The fact that her name retains its meaning in Germanic and Celtic languages suggests she was worshipped by both peoples. Several stone altars dating from the 2nd century BC to the 3rd century AD to Nehalennia have been discovered along the coast around Zeeland, Frisia, and England, and as far inland as Cologne. She‚Äôs depicted with ships, a dog at her feet, and baskets of bread and fruit, which indicates an association with fertility and/or commerce. One inscription in Cologne reads; ‚ÄúTo the goddess Nehalennia, on account of goods duly kept safe, Marcus Secundinus Silvanus, trader of pottery with Britain, fulfilled his vow willingly and deservedly.‚Äù This Latin inscription suggests she was worshipped by the Romans living in the region as well.

In this episode, I have a discussion with Sagnamadr Stark. We cover general faith, comparative religion, and worldview. The importance of artifacts, archeology, history, and how interpretations and interactions of these should meet our practice and understanding. url_description: In this episode I have a discussion with Sagnamadr Stark. We cover general faith, comparative religion, and world view. The importance of artifacts, and archeology, history, and how interpretations and interactions of these should meet our practice and understanding. How the Sagas and Eddas can be used for contemporary faith and practice. How to see through the negativity and in fighting amongst groups to have a proper outlook. cleaned_message: The latest instalment of the Hammer and Vajra podcast, featuring yours truly.
One of my favourite historical Thor‚Äôs hammer amulets. Found on Flekstad Farm, Steinkjer, central Norway.

‚ÄúBall √≠ Keilu kolli, Kjallandi brauzt √æ√∫ alla, √°√∞r draptu L√∫t ok Lei√∞a, l√©ztu dreyra B√∫seyru; heftir √æ√∫ Hengjankj√∂ftu, Hyrrokkin d√≥ fyrri; √æ√≥ var snemr in s√°ma Sv√≠v√∂r numin l√≠fi.‚Äù ‚ÄúThere was a clang on Keila's crown, you broke Kiallandi completely, before that you slew Lut and Leidi, you made Buseyra bleed, you halted Hengiankiapta, Hyrrokkin died previously, yet was the dusky Svivor's life taken earlier.‚Äù ~A fragment of a dr√°pa to Thor by 10th Century poet √ûorbj√∂rn d√≠sarsk√°ld, preserved in the Sk√°ldskaparm√°l, Faulkes translation. The Sk√°ldskaparm√°l is particularly valuable because it contains several contemporary 10th Century fragments of Old Norse poetry, and can be used as a reference for writing your own poetry, dr√°pas and prayers. Painting by Johannes Gehrts, 1901.

The Revsund Strip is the oldest surviving Scandinavian textile, dating to 780-980AD, making it older than the √ñverhogdal Tapestry. Made of a mix of wool and linen, adorned with several swastikas, looped squares, and two rider figures, possibly the Divine Twins.

The Skokloster Stone is very similar to the Reiterstein von Hornhausen, carved around 400-500 years later in Sweden in the 11th Century. The inscription tells us five men named Andv√©ttr, Gulleifr, Gunnarr, Horsi and Hr√≥dhleifr raised the stone in memory of their father √û√≥r√∞r.
And another‚Ä¶the coat of arms of Adenstedt, Lower Saxony.

Another German Coat of Arms which appears to be Woden is that of the B√∂rde district. A similar design appears on a few German Coat of Arms and even rune carvings from Sweden. However this figure is based on a carving from an ancient stone called the Reiterstein (the Rider Stone). The Rider wears a mask and carries a spear, both symbols of Woden. His white horse strides over a serpent, again both are Wodenic symbols. The Reiterstein is dated to the 7th century and was found in a field which contained over sixty graves. These are thought to be the burials of heathen Saxons who fought the christian Franks around 531. Perhaps this stone was raised in their honour?

This is the Coat of Arms of the Lower Saxony village of Woltershausen, Germany. The figure is clearly Woden and legend claims he haunted an ancient road between Winzenburg and Hildesheim called the Rennstieg which run just north of the village Woltershausen. Locals called him the Wodansreiter (Woden rider) and he was known to be able to change his form into a raven and a ghost who inhabited the nearby castle of H√∂decken.
A beautiful Anglo Saxon buckle, found on the Isle of Wight. This style, with the integral plate, appeared in the early 7th Century.

Vetrli√∞i Sumarli√∞ason was a staunch pagan, and wrote inflammatory poetry about √ûangbrandr, a Saxon missionary who was sent to Iceland, and was killed by him for it. Most of his work was destroyed, but this lausav√≠sa survived in the Sk√°ldskaparm√°l.

‚ÄúLeggi brauzt √æ√∫ Leiknar, lam√∞ir √ûr√≠valda, steyp√∞ir Starke√∞i, st√©ttu of Gjalp dau√∞a.‚Äù ‚ÄúYou broke Leikn's bones, you pounded Thrivaldi you cast down Starkad, you stood over the dead Gialp.‚Äù ~A 10th Century lausav√≠sa (single stanza poem) dedicated to Thor by Vetrli√∞i Sumarli√∞ason, recorded in the Sk√°ldskaparm√°l, Faulkes translation. Painting by Karl Erik Harr.
Parts of a sword hilt from Stora och Lilla Ihre, Gotland, 6-9th Century. The Broa-Style curled animal motifs are highly reminiscent of Scythian animal art.
A shrine dedicated to Svarog in Bitsevsky Park.
A unique Viking Age zoomorphic buckle, found in Swainby, North Yorkshire, 9-10th Century.

The possible origin of the popular ‚ÄúRing and Dot‚Äù motif, found on various artifacts across ancient Europe‚Ä¶ This weather phenomenon is known as a storm ring, or 22-degree halo. It‚Äôs caused by refraction of sunlight or moonlight by cirrus clouds in the atmosphere, which often precede rainfall and storm systems. An old saying goes, ‚Äúa ring around the sun or moon means rain or snow is coming soon.‚Äù Our ancestors would undoubtedly have seen this as an auspicious sign.
This Migration Period sword was found in the Kragehul bog, along with other sacrificed weapons. The pommel, with two stylized horse heads, could represent the Alcis Twins.
King Gylfi in Asgard, by Franz Stassen.

The Snartemo sword is a remarkable artifact, found in Norway, dated to the early 6th century. If you look closely at the gold foil on the handle, you can see a few tiermensch (beast-man) motifs. On the pommel, you‚Äôll notice an interesting motif; a tiermensch with the head of an eagle, similar to a sleeve clasp from Sutton Hoo. One of Odin‚Äôs many epithets was Arnh√∏f√∞i, ‚Äúeagle head‚Äù. These motifs could depict the interdependence and oneness of the natural world‚Ä¶or men becoming wolf warriors.
An outdoor temple in Bitsevsky Park, Russia.

The Ribe Skull Fragment is a bizarre runic amulet, carved on a fragment of a human cranium, invoking Odin for help against a mischievous dwarf. The inscription reads; ‚ÄúWolf and √ì√∞inn and High-Tyr. Help is borne against this pain. And the dwarf is overcome. Buur.‚Äù √ölfr and High-Tyr may be epithets of Odin, invoking him thrice. The ‚ÄúBuur‚Äù seemingly carved separately from the rest of the runes, may refer to B√∫ri, or be the name of the offending dwarf. The name B√∫ri means ‚Äúproducer‚Äù, and this could also have been an invocation, meant to bring the desired outcome into being. Hjalp buri es vi√∞r √æ√¶ima v√¶rki. Auk dverg unninn. Buur.‚Äù
A new silver Thor‚Äôs hammer amulet recently found in Markfield, Leicestershire.
The incredibly based coat of arms of J√§rva Parish, Estonia.

According to the Eyrbyggja Saga, Thorolf Mostrarskegg built his temple of Thor next to Helgafell. This rock is thought to be the sacrificial √û√≥rssteinn stone mentioned in the Saga, which would be reddened with blood.

Helgafell (ON: Holy Mountain) is a mountain on the Sn√¶fjellsnes Peninsula, western Iceland. The Eyrbyggja Saga and Landn√°mab√≥k attest it as being a home of the dead. Today, according to local folklore, if you hike to the top without looking back or saying a word, it will grant you three wishes.

All these reports of Christians vandalizing pagan shrines got me thinking‚Ä¶a tactic used by radical environmentalists to deter logging is tree spiking; driving spikes just under the surface of the wood, and if someone cuts into it, it can seriously damage their expensive tools-and depending on the tool, send the spikes flying like shrapnel. Now, if one were to place nails, or reginnaglar, in their outdoor godpoles, pillars, or shrines in a sacred grove, it could have a very similar effect... ·õâ

The Eyrbyggja Saga mentions reginnaglar, ‚Äúpower/God nails‚Äù, being driven into the high-seat pillars in the doorway of a temple. The Gl√¶lognskvi√∞a, a 10th Century skaldic poem, mentions performing prayers in front of reginnaglar. In Ancient Rome, ‚Äúmagic nails‚Äù with inscriptions and magical signs, often invoking Gods, were driven into doorways of houses, temples, shrines and tombs to protect those within. Norse reginnaglar would likely have been used in a similar manner. Pic: a few Roman magic nails from the British Museum, 3-4th Century. The one on the far left has an inscription invoking Artemis, and the one next to it has what looks like an image of Hermes-Anubis with a devotee or priest; this particular nail may have been for a tomb.

Neolithic rock art depicting a horned figure in Hossa V√§rikallio, Lake Somerj√§rvi, Finland. Painted with a mixture of ochre and blood by the people of the Pit-Comb Ware Culture, an R1a Y-DNA carrying predecessor of the Corded Ware Culture, 3,500-4,500 years ago.

‚ÄúFrith is the state of things which exists between friends. And it means, first and foremost, reciprocal inviolability. However individual wills may clash in a conflict of kin against kin, however stubbornly individual heads may seek their own way according to their quota of wisdom, there can never be question of conflict save in the sense of thoughts and feelings working their way toward an equipoise in unity. We need have no doubt but that good kinsmen could disagree with fervour, but however the matter might stand, there could-should, must inevitably-be but one ending to it all; a settlement peaceable and making for peace-frith.‚Äù ~Vilhelm Gr√∂nbech, Culture of the Teutons

Many of the folk in the pagan spheres are familiar with me. I've been in the community for a long time and am very proud of my contributions to the growth of our faith. If my words hold weight for you in this regard then please hear me. We have come a long way. I am so very proud of us. We are beginning to establish ourselves as real respectable advocates for a real living religious tradition. We are debating real theology. Real philosophy. Doing real research and understanding real sources in ways that can put scholarship back into pagan hands where it belongs. We still have a long way to go but our future is very bright. What MUST happen is in the many, many debates to come that we are holding ourselves to standard of conduct that is reflective of high-mindedness and nobility. Not the septic putridity of internet troll culture. We are here to serve the Gods. Our actions and conduct must please them or else we are doing it wrong. Those whom you are debating, who are real theistic devotional and right-handed pagans are not dogs to be beaten and abused. They are your kinfolk who you are trying to convince in an arena of ideas in order to distill the most authentic truths. Accusing an opponent of being secretly Christian is not an argument. Accusing an opponent of being secretly Jewish is not an argument. Accusing an opponent of being a fed or a glow or double agent is not an argument. Slandering an opponent's family or friends is absolutely not an argument. These are not noble or high-minded tactics. These are ergi. They are the exact tactics that aforementioned bad actors would use and have used. It makes the associated positions look clownish, amateur and contaminated with low IQ white trash behavior. This is unfortunately how we learn debate tactics on the internet. But we are ABOVE such conduct. So, many of us have behaved like this in the past. But we MUST purge this malignant behavior from both ourselves and our circles. It doesn't mean that there are never bad actors. There certainly are. But bad actors aren't championing that which they love. They are trying to destroy what they hate. They are DEgenerate. And we are generative. Battle forth with righteous fervor and determination. But do so with love for your ancestors and the high holy Gods in your heart. Show them and the world that we are as noble, good and true as we say we are with honor and sophistication. It is their will. Don't believe me? Read your Havamal again.

An illustration of the battle between the Vikings and Skr√¶lings in the Saga of Erik the Red, by Angus McBride. You can see Freydis Eiriksdottir reaching for a fallen kinsman‚Äôs sword. Skr√¶ling, the Old Norse term for Native Americans, means ‚Äúpeople who wear dried skins (skr√°).‚Äù
An interesting Gothic silver bow brooch, found in Ukraine. The design on the foot plate looks a lot like two vajra-style lighting bolts.

A medieval memory of Hel‚Ä¶ In the Old English Gospel of Nicodemus, written in the 11th century, we see a character named "Seo Helle" (Lady Hel). She engages in a flying match with Satan, and orders him to leave her realm, which he refuses to do. In the Norse saga of Saint Bartholomew, a demon hiding in a statue of a god is bound, and confesses that "Jesus made war on Hel, our queen." Rather than denying Hel altogether, it appears the missionaries would have had the Germanic peoples believe that when Satan was cast out of Heaven, he usurped Hel and became king of the underworld, turning it from the home of the ancestors to strictly a place of suffering and punishment. While some may claim Hel was an invention of the Icelandic poets, the lengths Christian missionaries went to to demonize her say otherwise; she was clearly widely known-and respected. Art: Hel and Garm, by Maria Pechenkina.
A 7th century bronze zierscheibe from Ingersheim, near Stuttgart, Germany. The design is very reminiscent of the Gotland snake-witch stone, as well as the Pashupati seals from Mohenjo Daro.

The Undley Bracteate also features a Roman-style wolf and twins motif. My personal theory is, with the √Üngles and Saxons having had greater contact with Rome while working as auxiliaries, that they may have seen Romulus and Remus as an incarnation of the Divine Twins.

The Undley Bracteate bears an inscription with both Gyfu (gift) and ≈ås (God) bindrunes and Gyfu and √Üsc (ash) bindrunes, and ‚Äúm√¶g√¶ medu‚Äù, which translates to ‚Äúreward for the kinsman‚Ä¶potentially for offering this gold bracteate in sacrifice.

The Gebo-Ansuz bindrune appears on several artifacts, notably the Undley Bracteate, and the Kragehul spear shaft. Some have suggested it's a shortening of "gibu auja" (I give luck), because one bracteate from Zealand had gibu auja inscribed on it-but not the bindrune. What it likely is a shortening of is gift+√Üsir, meant to sacralize an object for sacrifice. Looking at the Kragehul Spear, the inscription reads ek erilaz ƒÅsugƒ´salas muha haitƒì, "I, the erilaz of ƒÄsugƒ´salaz, am called Muha (bind runes)". The other side reads "(bind runes) the mighty roarer, hail, I dedicate to the spear." ƒÄsugƒ´salaz is a compounding of "God (√Ås)" and "pledge/hostage". Spears and weapons were often sacrificed, and it's also possible that such an inscribed spear could have been ceremonially thrown over the heads of the enemy, recreating Odin throwing Gungnir in the √Üsir-Vanir War, promising the enemy to Odin as a sacrifice. This is a symbol that is appropriate to put on something that you wish to offer to the Gods.

This Thor‚Äôs hammer from Harrogate, North Yorkshire, closely resembles several surviving Stone Age axe-hammers.

A few historical examples of Ukko‚Äôs axe amulets, from the national museum of Finland. The Ukonvasara was the Finnish equivalent of Thor‚Äôs hammer, and was modelled after Stone Age axe-hammers, which were often unearthed by heavy rains during storms. It could be called the Ukonvasara (Ukko‚Äôs hammer), or Ukonkirves (Ukko‚Äôs axe). In Estonia, Ukko was called Uku, Taara, and according to Mikael Agricola, Turisas; very similar to the reconstructed Proto-Germanic Thurisaz. One of Thor‚Äôs epithets in the Gylfaginning was √ñku-Thor, a possible reference to Ukko.

A Neolithic staff found in Finland, around 4,400 years old. Due to the association of snakes with shamanism in Uralic and Indo European religions, it‚Äôs thought that it may have belonged to a shaman of sorts. The snake is a common symbol of the shaman along with the wolf, but specifically, a shaman who can travel to and from the underworld. Odin, Veles and Shiva are often depicted with snakes. In Finnish paganism, snakes are associated with the earth goddess Akka, the wife of Ukko, because snakes emerge from the soil after the snow thaws.
Wieland the forger and the Princess, by Moritz von Schwind, 1850.

A Frisian gold solidus coin from 575-625AD, bearing the name ‚ÄúWeladu‚Äù, the Frisian spelling of Wayland. This coin is the earliest known attestation of Wayland the Smith. The staves in the figure‚Äôs hands could be the wings of of his flying machine. ·öπ·õñ·õö·ö™·õû·ö¢

The winged man of Uppakra, likely depicting Wayland the Smith in his bird suit. The earliest attestation to Wayland was on a Frisian coin from the 6-7th century, and the first ‚Äúofficial‚Äù human flight was achieved by Abbas in Firnas in the 9th Century, followed by Eilmer of Malmesbury, aka the flying monk, in the 11th Century. Wayland's story is entirely believable.
Two Anglo Saxon zoomorphic fylfot brooches from Mildenhall, Suffolk, 6th Century.

This cache of Roman gladii was recently found in a cave in Ein Gedi, Israel, with their original wood and leather hilts still intact. They were likely stashed here by Jewish rebels during the Bar Kokhba Revolt in the 2nd Century.

‚ÄúHe who offers to Me with devotion and a pure heart A leaf, a flower, a fruit, or water, that offering of devotion I accept from him.‚Äù ~Bhagavad Gita, 9:26, Sargent translation Very reminiscent of Julian‚Äôs quote about an offering only being worth as much as the piety with which it is offered.

Brinno as leader of the Canninefates raised on a shield, by Barend Wijnveld, 1835-1897. The practice of raising a new king on a shield was also documented among the Goths and Franks, and Julian‚Äôs Germanic guard raised him on a shield when he was proclaimed emperor.
Bledsian «∑interfylle√æ! G√≥√∞an Vetrn√¶tr!

Looks like there‚Äôs going to be a partial lunar eclipse for Winterfylleth tonight! It‚Äôll only be visible in Europe and Asia, so if you‚Äôre there, keep an eye on the sky. The peak should be; 9:14pm in London, 10:14pm in Berlin, 11:14pm in Moscow, 1:14am in Mumbai, and 4:14am in Hong Kong. A similar partial eclipse, seen from Regensburg, Germany, 2017:

‚ÄúOne god there is, in no way like mortal creatures either in bodily form or in the thought of his mind. The whole of him sees, the whole of him thinks, the whole of him hears. He stays always motionless in the same place; it is not fitting that he should move about now this way, now that.‚Äù ~Xenophanes, a Greek philosopher who held actual monistic beliefs, despite writing about how different peoples depicted the Gods/God in their own likeness. This n√≠√∞ingr knows so little of what he speaks.

‚ÄúAre you not aware that all offerings whether great or small that are brought to the gods with piety have equal value, whereas without piety, I will not say hecatombs, but, by the gods, even the Olympian sacrifice of a thousand oxen is merely empty expenditure and nothing else?‚Äù ~Julian the Apostate, from To the Cynic Heracleios. ·õâ Painting: Proclamation of Julian by Radu Oltean.
Various scenes from the V√∂lusp√° by Franz Stassen.
On today‚Äôs episode of ‚Äúthings I get tired of explaining to people‚Äù‚Ä¶
Illustrations for the √ûrymskvi√∞a by Franz Stassen.

I was going through some older photos, when I noticed this‚Ä¶ I see the outline of a chariot in the smoke from the incense sticks. I was performing a bl√≥t to Thor, hence the replica Eyrarland statue. Even when it may seem like the Gods aren‚Äôt listening, they are.

In addition to the evidence connecting Freyr to the barrow, he is associated with elves in Gr√≠mnism√°l where it says √Ålfheimr (the land of elves) was given by the gods as a gift to Freyr. It is clear from Ynglinga saga, Beowulf and the Ing rune of the Old English rune poem that Ingvifreyr was associated with noble lineages. Elves are also associated with the noble dead. √ûorsteins saga V√≠kingssonar recounts a line of local kings who ruled over √Ålfheim, and who, since they had elven blood, were said to be more beautiful than most men. There is also the story of a man named Olaf who becomes an elf after he died and was buried in a barrow. Thenceforth he was known as √ìlafr Geirsta√∞a √Ålfr - Olaf the elf of Geirstad. In Korm√°ks Saga elves are clearly associated with barrows. A witch directs a man to a barrow who needs to heal a serious wound. There he must sacrifice a bull to the elves who will feast on the flesh and he must redden the barrow with blood.
A closer look at the Odin figure from Lindby, Sweden. Upon closer inspection, the right eye is clearly squinted shut.
Illustrations from the H√°vam√°l, Vaf√ær√∫√∞nism√°l and Gr√≠mnism√°l from my antique German Edda. Artist is Franz Stassen.

Some elfish place names in England include Alvescot in Oxfordshire, from √Ülfegescota meaning √Ülf hƒìah's cot or Elf‚Äôs Cottage. Elvendon, also in Oxfordshire comes from Elvesdenegrof meaning Elves Wood Grove. Aluehou near Tetney in Lincolnshire comes from √°lfr haugr or the mound haunting by elves ‚Äì somewhere to give blot on the next full moon as Frƒìa (Frey) and the √¶lfe will be invoked in many upcoming rites! Another mound haunted by elves is Elvinhowe in Gosforth in Newcastle, whilst Elveden is a valley near Thetford which is home to the elves.

D√≠sabl√≥t was another bl√≥t held during Winter Nights in honour of the D√≠sir, female v√¶ttir who watched over the entire tribe; Valkyries, the Norns, and possibly ancestral spirits as well. The Old Saxon cognate is Idisi/Ides; in Beowulf, the Ides of the Scyldings and Helmings are attested. English philologist Gabriel Turville-Petre likened it to M≈çdraniht, which was held at the end of December in England, according to Bede. D√≠sabl√≥t was celebrated publicly, as opposed to at home like √Ålfabl√≥t, and according to V√≠ga-Gl√∫m‚Äôs Saga, it was held at the beginning of winter. In the Hervarar Saga, Starka√∞r kidnaps Alfhildr during D√≠sabl√≥t as she is reddening a h√∂rgr with blood at a dedicated D√≠sir shrine called the d√≠sarsalr. This suggests the bl√≥t could be performed by women. In the Ynglinga Saga, it was performed by the king of Sweden, who was also a high priest. In Egil‚Äôs Saga, it was hosted by King Eirikr. G√≥√∞an D√≠sabl√≥t! Art: The D√≠sabl√≥t, by August Malmstr√∂m.
√Ålfaborg, Iceland.

In Ireland and Scotland, Neolithic barrows are sometimes called ‚Äúelf-hills‚Äù. In Iceland, Britain and Scandinavia, multiple mountains are referred to as homes of elves; for example, √Ålfaborg (fortress of the elves) in eastern Iceland. The bulk of the Korm√°ks Saga takes place in Ireland and Scotland. The hill he sacrifices to the √Ålfar at could have been one of these barrows, or a hill, like unto √Ålfaborg. Belief in both √Ålfar and the dead inhabiting hills appears in multiple Sagas, for example, Helgafjell in the Landn√°mab√≥k and Eyrbyggja Saga. It‚Äôs been proposed that the D√∂kk√°lfar, attested as being subterranean in the Prose Edda, are ancestral spirits, while Lj√≥s√°lfar are something else entirely. In the Orkneys and Shetlands, burial mounds were also with another spirit; trows. A few things connect trows to ancestral spirits; in the Orkneyinga Saga, it‚Äôs said that Einar gives Kalf and Thorir ‚Äúto the trolls‚Äù when he kills them. In the Orkneys and Shetlands, a Yule tradition was to unlock every door so the trows could visit. In either case, hills, barrows and burial mounds were clearly believed to be liminal spaces, where the ancestors, and other entities, could pass into this world.

Another early Germanic scabbard mount, similar to the example in the Stark Collection, from Nydam, southern Denmark. This points towards an earlier, continental origin for this type of sword pyramid. The arches may have been based on a variation of the sundog phenomenon, wherein a crescent appears above the sun.

√Ålfabl√≥t was a bl√≥t held during Vetrnatr, at the beginning of winter. While our historical knowledge of Alfabl√≥t is limited, we have a few key details; it was a celebration in honour of the √Ålfar (elves), held at the end of the harvest season, and it was held at home with one's family as opposed to a public place of worship. √Ålfar were believed to hold power over health and fertility-and could cause illness, and destroy the crops of those who offended them. The Korm√°ks Saga describes a sacrifice to the √Ålfar to heal a battle wound. At a hill believed to be inhabited by the √Ålfar (a burial mound?), a bull is sacrificed, the hill reddened with its blood, and its flesh made into a feast for the √Ålfar. The V√∂lundarkvi√∞a describes V√∂lundr as having √Ålf ancestry, and this along with the Korm√°ks Saga links the √Ålfar with ancestral spirits. The reason √Ålfabl√≥t was held at home was likely because families would honour the ancestors of their particular family. Due to this aspect, less is known about Alfabl√≥t than other Germanic pagan holidays. Bees also carry a lesser-known association with the Sky Father across Indo European cultures. In Greek religion, it was believed that Kronos imprisoned Zeus in a cave, which also contained a beehive. Zeus survived on their honey, and grew strong enough to overthrow Kronos, and in turn, fed Dionysus honey. Dionysus retained his association with beekeeping long after wine overtook mead in Ancient Greece. And of course, in the Sk√°ldskaparm√°l, we see Odin‚Äôs gift of the mead of poetry, and according to the Gr√≠mnism√°l, he himself subsists on mead, and gives any food given to him to his wolves-which could refer to the belief that if you made an offering of food and an animal ate it, the Gods accepted your offering. Bees and Valkyries An Anglo Saxon metrical charm refers to bees as sƒ´gewƒ´f; ‚Äúvictory-women‚Äù, thought by folklorists Jacob Grimm and John Mitchell Kemble to refer to Valkyries. A tradition that survived across the British Isles and Western Europe was ‚Äútelling the bees‚Äù. People who kept bees would inform them of significant events in their families, such as births, marriages and deaths, and would offer a piece of wedding cake or funeral biscuit to their hives. The Frankish king Childeric was buried with hundreds of gold and garnet bee amulets. Of all the possible animal totems, he chose bees to accompany him on his final journey. In Celtic religion, bees were believed to be able to carry messages between the Otherworld and ours. In Greek religion, bees were heavily associated with Persephone, who was referred to as Melitodes (honeyed one), and believed to carry souls to and from the afterlife. But I remember it went like this‚Ä¶ In the forests of Thorenwald, a young woman had fallen in love with a man from a nearby village. Her father wanted her to marry another man, a warrior from a noble family, with whom he sought to align. But his daughter and her lover had made up their minds, and announced that they would marry. Unbeknownst to her, her father arranged to have the warrior kidnap her from her wedding, in order to bait her lover into a duel in which he would be gravely outmatched. The two families met to a tense wedding in the sacred oak grove. As they were taking their vows, the warrior came riding on a mighty Saxon horse, and snatched the woman. Her fianc√© drew his sword and demanded he get down and fight him. Before the duel could commence, she threw herself between them and called to Thor for help. And he heard her. A bolt of lightning struck an oak tree near where her father stood. He interpreted this as a warning from Thor himself, and didn‚Äôt interfere any further. When the wedding rituals were complete, and his daughter and her husband were officially married, the clouds parted. The people of the surrounding villages made offerings to Thor at the charred oak, a symbol of Thor‚Äôs love for his people.

It was said that if you were being followed by a malevolent entity, such as a troll or sm√•gubber, a way to get rid of it was to walk into the centre of a labyrinth, and then run out of it. The spirit would become confused in the folds of the labyrinth, and wouldn‚Äôt be able to get out in time to find you again and cause trouble. Stone labyrinths in Iceland, Finland, Russia and the Isles of Scilly. From the Middle Ages to the 18-19th Century, fishermen in Scandinavia, the British Isles, and around the Baltic Sea would build these labyrinths at their fishing camps as they waited for favourable winds. Fishermen would walk them for good luck at sea, and hunters and farmers would walk them to avoid unwanted encounters with predators.

Was discussing animism with a friend earlier. His TL;DR of animism is; the worldview in which there are many persons, only some of which are human. These ‚Äúpersons‚Äù encompass visible biological beings - humans, plants, animals, etc. and Gods and spirits. A collection of Gullgubbers from Sorte Muld, Denmark. These are often found at the sites of temples, and may have been used to decorate the walls. As statues of the Gods would be at the forefront of the temple, these could depict the Ancestors, and/or marriage rites held at the temple. Gullgubbers were also likely used as votive offerings, offered in the place of a sacrificial animal or prisoner. These would have been very easy to produce en masse, with gold foil and a die stamp, to be sold and used as offerings.

A question I hear a lot is, why did I, as a European pagan, visit Africa? Simple; Africa provides a unique opportunity to interact with some of the last living tribal cultures on earth, including some of the last pastoralists, such as the Maasai, and hunter-gatherers, such as the Hadza. Even if we‚Äôre not closely related, they maintain a lifestyle strikingly similar to that of our Bronze Age ancestors. And, if you really want to experience this, they‚Äôve been known to let us wazungu (foreigners) try living with them for a few days. There are a few surviving pastoralist tribes in India, such as the Dhangar, Bhutia, and Gandhila peoples‚Ä¶maybe I need to go there next.

This gold Anglo Saxon ring was found in northwest Essex, late 6-7th Century. It shows a clear combination of pagan and Christian imagery, with a figure holding a cross staff, and two ravens circling overhead. In some instances, pagan Anglo Saxons were willing to worship Jesus as *another* deity, for the sake of securing peace and alliances, including King R√¶dwald himself. Missionaries told them that Jesus would protect them in combat, and he may have initially been seen as another war god, like unto Tiw. In Teutonic Mythology, Jacob Grimm discussed how in medieval Germany, Woden was likened to the Christian God (likely as a conversion tactic). It was said that God created wolves, and chose wolves as his hounds; very Wodenic. A similar belief may have emerged in late Anglo Saxon England. ·ö©
Bingo. While I wouldn't say "most." The impact that Anglo-Saxon and Scandinavian had on the Scots made a nominally and culturally Celto-Norse but genetically rather Germanic group.

Especially on the West Coast and Northern Isles. When I did my DNA test, I found that my Scottish half, from Bearsden, had a large percentage of Norwegian. There was even a regional dialect of Norwegian in the Orkneys and Hebrides called Norn, up until 1850.

The Zierscheibe design appeared among the Alemanni, Franks and Langobards, along with the Etruscans and Iberian tribes. There‚Äôs several variations, always with a central point connected within a larger circle. With the most well-known design, you see several arms which resemble Ursa Major and/or Minor revolving around the North Star, with an extra curve where the ‚Äúhandle‚Äù of the dipper is. Many surviving Zierscheiben also incorporate a Fylfot. Therefore, this design likely represents the Big Dipper revolving around the North Star. The Big Dipper was known as √ì√∞ins Vagn/Woden‚Äôs Wagon among the Germanic peoples, and several of Odin‚Äôs titles link him to wagons; Vagna Verr (guardian of the wagon), Vagna Runni (mover of the wagon), and Valdr vagnbrautar (ruler of the wagon-road; the sky). By extension, the symbol likely represents Odin, and the path to higher consciousness, and the higher realms.

My stance on ‚Äúreclaiming‚Äù sacred symbols has always been this; regardless of where you stand politically, if someone took a symbol you held sacred, politicized it, even defiled it, do you think the correct course of action is to just‚Ä¶let them have it? Hindus, Buddhists, and the Navajo didn‚Äôt back away from the Fylfot/Svastika because the Third Reich used it, and European pagans could learn a thing or two from them. Besides, there are variations which look little like the Third Reich‚Äôs Hakenkreuz. And believe me, our opponents won‚Äôt stop with the Fylfot. ‚ÄúBerchtoldstag is an Alemannic holiday, known in Switzerland and Liechtenstein. It is near New Year's Day, during the Rauhn√§chte, in Switzerland nearly always on 2 January, with the status of a public holiday in a number of cantons. Its observation is attested since the 14th century, although celebrations were limited after the Protestant Reformation. Berchtold Day is a light-hearted, sociable event. People meet in pubs and restaurants to exchange good wishes for the New Year. In Hallwil in the canton of Aargau one can still witness the B√§rzeli, a parade of dressed up and masked figures symbolizing concepts like fertility, age, ugliness, wisdom, and vice. The name may be related to the Perchta, a female of myth and folklore, guardian of the animals, and sometimes leader of the Wild Hunt, Perchta shows dual faces at this time. To the faithful, she appears as a beautiful goddess of light who blesses humans with health and prosperity. To the evil hearted, deceitful and wicked, she appears as a ferocious demon with horns and fangs.‚Äù
Another survival of the Indo-European winter procession‚Ä¶

I do wonder if the horned headdresses in Germanic art were made from an actual bull skull. They often have what appears to be bovine ears, and the curves on the forehead of the image from Torslunda could be eye sockets. This could also explain why we‚Äôve never found a complete example, as the organic material would decay. Note that the figure on the Torslunda Plates, upon closer inspection, only has one eye.

The Mesopotamian chief God, Hadad/I≈°kur, was often depicted similarly to Odin, with a bull-horned headdress, often holding a stylized thunderbolt; it‚Äôs possible that with the figure of Odin from Upplands-Bro, the crossed sticks in his hand are a stylized vajra. After all, in the H√°vam√°l and Gr√≠mnism√°l, one of Odin‚Äôs titles is √ûundr; Thunderer.

Fascinating thread by Grandson of Finn on X-potential evidence of Celtic influence in Beowulf. For those of you not on X: There's too much evidence to deny that Beowulf occurred historically, but his legend is also an incarnation of an older Indo-European tale which has parallels in other branches. Most notably in the T√°in B√≥ Fr√°ich, which I'll do a thread on some day. Both Beowulf and Fr√°ich appear from afar, are served by a queen out of a jeweled goblet, dive into a lake to wrestle a sea monster at the bottom, initially overcome until a sword is found, later struggling with a dragon/serpent aided by a single companion, etc. Aurochs has shown pretty well that Arthur is a historical person (or people) whose life became mythologized, and Beowulf appears to be the opposite, a historical person whose life became overshadowed by a myth which was applied to him. https://x.com/ogmios/status/1699604760003846562?s=46

The Stenkvista runestone is located near the church at Stenkvista, two kilometers east of Skogstorp, S√∂dermanland County, Sweden. It features a depiction of Thor's hammer, Mj√∂llnir. The biggest argument against monism that I see circling the internet these days is that it served to erode tribal loyalties, and paved the way for monotheism. While this may be true in some cases, there are many monistic religions which have survived the test of time, for example, Pashupata Shaivism. And, multiple Buddhist sects, such as Tibetan Buddhism and Shugendo, retained multiple cultural and religious aspects of B√∂n (Tibetan shamanism) and Shint≈ç. Doesn‚Äôt mean I agree with all of their theology, but I don‚Äôt believe monism is the culture destroying plague some make it out to be.

The two main reasons why I lean towards polytheism vs. monism are, firstly, while there are many deities in related pantheons which closely resemble each other, you see countless regional deities which were only worshipped by certain cultures, or in certain regions. For example, from Germanic cultures; Zisa and Nehalennia. The other reason being, in every Indo European religion, the Gods marry and sire new Gods. Art: Yggdrasil by Friedrich Wilhelm Heine, 1886.

A modern-day example of frith would be penny auctions in the Great Depression. When banks seized farms when the farmers were unable to pay their mortgages, their neighbours would show up to the subsequent auction with their guns. The original owner of the farm would bid one penny, and nobody else would dare to bid more.

The way I‚Äôve always described Frith to newcomers to Germanic religion is as the social contract through which peace is kept; the mutual understanding that if someone wishes to harm your kin, action will be taken.

‚ÄúA word such as the Latin pax suggests first and foremost a laying down of arms, a state of equipoise due to the absence of disturbing elements; frith, on the other hand, indicates something armed, protection, defense - or else a power for peace which keeps men amicably inclined.‚Äù ~Vilhelm Gr√∂nbech, Culture of the Teutons Art: Germaanse Volksvergadering by Charles Rochussen, 1878-1881.

While modern pagans face multiple challenges, such as subversives and the sea of false information around our faith, in my opinion one of the most understated threats to modern paganism is the lack of professionalism in the online pagan community. For us pagans, we‚Äôre a significant religious minority in every single Western country. We often live far away from each other, so unfortunately, the online community is important. And it seems to me that every second pagan circle that I‚Äôve been in (and out of) is full of arrogant, obnoxious know-it-alls who think they know everything and are quick to start arguments, and run the risk of pushing away people who are new to paganism. From my own experience, I‚Äôve had a few friends coming from atheist and Catholic backgrounds who I was trying to sell on paganism, but they ultimately joined the Orthodox Church. I know why; it‚Äôs because the Church was able to offer them the respectful, coherent, cohesive community of like-minded individuals that they sought. For now, the churches have us beat on that front. As we build our communities, both online and in the real world, we need to cultivate cultures of professionalism, mutual respect and frith, but we also need to be approachable. If we want our kindreds to last more than a generation, that is. ·õâ

The design of the Latvian flag goes back to the Northern Crusades. According to the Livonian Rhymed Chronicle, a wounded Latgalian chieftain was laid on a white sheet. The patch he lay on remained white, and his blood stained the rest of it. The next time the Teutonic Knights saw the Latgalians in battle, they carried the bloodstained sheet as their new war banner.

The Snake-Witch Stone from Gotland may depict the legendary origins of the Gutnish people. In the 13th century, the Gutasaga was written, chronicling the early history of Gotland. In the beginning, the island was discovered by a man named √ûieluar, and his son Haf√æi moved to the island, along with his wife, Vitastjerna. One night, Vitastjerna dreamt that she was pregnant with three entwined snakes. Haf√æi interpreted this as a sign that they would have three sons, and everything was connected. She gave birth to three sons, Graip, Gute and Gunfjaun, the legendary progenitors of the Gutnish people. They ruled Gotland together and divided it into three √æri√∞jungar (ridings). Even after the church took over, Gotland remains divided into three deaneries. While the triskele was found across the Indo European world, and snakes were widely associated with shamanism, this particular example may depict the progenitors of the people of Gotland.

In Baltic paganism, wolves were known as Dievas Sunƒ´≈°i (dogs of God), and it was believed harming one could invoke his wrath, in the form of misfortune or plagues. I always thought there could be more to Freki and Geri, and Huginn and Muninn. Wolves and ravens have a very unique relationship in nature. Wolves will follow ravens to food, and ravens will alert the wolves to danger while they eat, and the wolves will tear open larger carcasses and crack open bones so the ravens can eat. Wolves won't eat ravens, and are often seen playing with them. It‚Äôs believed that individual wolves and ravens form lifelong friendships. Perhaps, as well as serving as his guards and companions, Odin's wolves and ravens are an embodiment of the interdependence of both our natural world and the N√≠u Heimar, and the gifting cycles between the Gods and mortals.

The Dove Book, a medieval Russian manuscript, relates a story in which the world and humanity were created from Adam‚Äôs body, strikingly similar to the V√∂luspa. This points towards an earlier Slavic Pagan belief in the cosmos being fashioned from the body of a primordial life form; like Ymir and Purusha.

Obviously not everyone is going to agree on various aspects of pagan theology, but if Shaivas, Shaktas and Vaisnavas could learn to coexist, pagans can too. Living and practicing the faith is the most important thing. ·õâ

Most creation myths across IE cultures share multiple aspects; always the growth of a World Tree (or pillar), sometimes from a cosmic egg, and often the sacrifice of a primordial life form (Ymir/Purusha), after which the world is fashioned from his body. In these creation myths, the chief of the Gods always appears alongside the world tree; ex. Odin‚Äôs family is roused from the primordial ice, Svarog emerges from the cosmic egg, and Shiva from the cosmic pillar (Lingodbhava). Now, did multiple Creators emerge alongside the World Tree, or would a deity this powerful, and his immediate family, be known to multiple cultures under other names in their respective languages? The fact that so many cultures, including non-IE cultures, came to the conclusion that there are certain deities; a Sky Father, Earth Mother, Striker, Dawn Goddess, Divine Twins, etc. leads me to believe the latter.

Returning to my previous post about the Oseberg beast posts and chains/ropes demarcating a ritual area, we also see in Egil‚Äôs saga reference to something called a v√©b√∂nd. The prefix v√©, cognate with Old English weoh, refers to a sacred area, while b√∂nd, like band, refers to a cord. In the saga heslistengur ‚Äúhazle poles‚Äù are used to demarcate a v√©b√∂nd not for a bl√≥t, but for a legal dispute. Poles from the supple hazle tree (hasla) were used to demarcate a fighting area or for a court to assemble within. Mark Puryear of the The Noroena Society has concluded, based on the inherently sacred meaning of v√©, that the sacred area for a bl√≥t ought also to be marked out with hazle poles, and I am inclined to agree with him. Evidently more elaborate and impressive alternatives were accepted, such as the beast posts of Oseberg and the golden chain around the Uppsala hof described by Adam of Bremen - but surely the simplest demarcation for a v√©b√∂nd is four hazle poles and a piece of a string.

url_description: Returning to the subject of rangles (read more), the Oseberg ship burial gives us a clue as to how they were used. It contained 5 ornately carved wooden beast heads, each of which held rope in its mouth and was associated with a unique rangle rattle, some with ornate gold work on them. Each of the rattles was attached by a rope to its metal hook. In addition the rattle-rope passed through the mouth of the associated animal head post. As far back as 1905 Shetelig and Gustafson proposed that the beasts and rangles were used during the funeral rite as a kind of fence for the sacred area (known as a Gard) which was inside the ship that was later buried beneath a barrow. It seems the rangles and beasts protected the ritual area from evil supernatural forces.

url_description: Vocals and arrangement by Farya Faraji, many thanks to Anet Gharibian for providing the pronunciation. The melody isn't mine, they're melodic motifs native to the region of the Armenian Highlands and often found in many folk songs of the region. Vahagn was an ancient Armenian deity associated with fire, war and thunder in the native Armenian polytheistic faith. He is often called ’é’´’∑’°’∫’°÷Ñ’°’≤ (Vishabakagh), which means Dragon-Slayer. Vahagn has an Indo-Iranian equivalent called Verethragna. The lyrics are in Classical Armenian or Old Armenian, the oldest attested form of the language which begins in the 5th century A.D. They are some of the only remnants of pre-Christian Armenian language and religious belief, preserved thanks to the efforts of Movses Khorenatsi, an Armenian historian from Late Antiquity. Khorenatsi is regarded as the father of Armenian history and the Armenian equivalent to Herodotus, and he claimed to be a disciple of Mesrop Mashtots, the creator of the Armenian alphabet. This song was collected by Movses Khorenatsi in his book "History of the Armenians," but the paganistic nature of it must date it to at least a century before his own time‚Äîthis song is a window into the forgotten world of pre-Christian Armenia. I consulted this academic lecture when researching the subject: https://av.tib.eu/media/48944 as well as this site: https://hayeren.hayastan.com/st/st19eng.html I used the pronunciation of Iranian Armenians, therefore my pronunciation might not reflect all the diverse accents of the Armenian diaspora of today. The music is typical of that of Armenia: it uses a duduk and a large frame drum, both being ancient instruments that stretch back to Late Antiquity, with the duduk being accepted as being at least the fifth century, which places it exactly at Movses Khorenatsi's time‚Äîwhich makes it possible that this piece would have been recognisable to some degree to him. Some Armenian scholars claim the existence of the duduk can be traced back to far before before the fith century, but mainstream academia has not conclusively confirmed those claims. As is typical of Armenian music, two duduks are used: one provides the base drone and the other plays the melody. The Labyrinth is one of Mankind‚Äôs oldest symbols, and it appears across Eurasia and the Americas. There are many variations, but always with a single ‚Äúentrance‚Äù, and a twisting path ending in the centre. The fact that it appeared in many Native American cultures indicates that it goes back to at least the Mesolithic period. In India, the labyrinth is called the Chakravy≈´ha after a complex battle formation mentioned in the Mahabharata, intended to draw enemies in and surround them. The symbol may have had an apotropaic purpose; it may have served to draw in and trap evil spirits. It‚Äôs also been proposed that it represents the journey of the soul. In multiple Native American cultures, it represented the path to the home of the ancestors. The labyrinth continued to be used in medieval Christianity, said to represent the journey to God; this could hint at an earlier belief in the symbol representing the journey to the ultimate destination.

A structure resembling a stone ship, a stone wall, glass beads, and several bones of domestic animals were found inside, indicating it was used as a ritual site.

The Kwakwaka‚Äôwakw natives of British Columbia had a similar tradition to our European winter processions; if they suspected a person was under the influence of an evil spirit, they would perform a ceremonial dance wearing large masks depicting wolves, ravens, and ogres, with the intent of scaring the spirit off. More notes on Germanic priesthood‚Ä¶ Being a Go√∞i was a far more popular choice for men, while being a V√∂lva was a far more popular choice for women. The reason being a Vitki/Sei√∞ma√∞r was considered ergi for men likely was because it could presumably allow him to indirectly harm an opponent. Men were expected to be direct in conflict, but sei√∞r could be seen as an acceptable weapon for women, who were at a physical disadvantage. It has also been suggested that entering an altered state in which you allow an entity to enter your body was considered more womanly. In the √ñgmundar √æ√°ttr dytts, a priestess of Freyr ritually marries him. She may very well have intended to let Freyr use her as a vessel. Painting by Valentina Mustajarvi.

In Germanic culture, there were two classes of priest, which weren‚Äôt always mutually exclusive: Go√∞i/Gy√∞ja: religious teacher, temple keeper, ritual specialist; basically a Guru. V√∂lva/Vitki: seeks direct possession by Gods and spirits. Seer/shaman.

Soft vs Hard Polytheism‚Ä¶ Soft Polytheism is the belief that there are multiple Gods, but the majority of parallel deities in related pantheons are cognates. While there are certainly deities with regional cults that were only worshipped by certain cultures, the fact that so many cultures agree there are certain deities; ex. a Sky Father, Earth Mother and Striker, which share multiple key characteristics, points towards one ultimate Indo-European pantheon, the deities of which may be understood and depicted differently among different cultures, but retain their characteristic features that originate with the religion of the Proto Indo-Europeans. Hard Polytheism is the belief that every god ever recorded exists, as a unique deity. I‚Äôm not trying to ridicule you, but to those who actually believe this, I have a few questions for you‚Ä¶ Do you believe there‚Äôs 10+ Sky Fathers, Earth Mothers, Strikers, etc. governing this world? How do you reconcile the fact that there are multiple creation myths among other Indo-European cultures, which often share several aspects, most importantly the sacrifice of the primordial life form, Ymir/Purusha? What happened when the Proto Indo-Europeans left the steppe, did each God in their pantheon splinter into new ones? Do you even believe that there are Gods at all, or do you believe that they are all simply metaphors and archetypes, and if so, why did our ancestors worship and sacrifice to them? Some things to ponder.

TL;DR for people who are new to my channel; I am a Germanic Pagan first, foremost and finally. But, yes, I believe there is value in studying other Indo-European religions to make sense of our more fragmentary lore. Call it syncretism or whatever you want; I don‚Äôt care. One of my key takeaways is, there are myths and legends that echo our own lore across all related Indo-European cultures.
One of the European-style longhouses on Pamiok Island, Nunavut.

‚Ä¶for those who aren‚Äôt familiar with him: Farley Mowat was a based Canadian ecologist, historian and writer. He spent decades in the Arctic studying wolves, and dispelling the harmful myths about them. His book Never Cry Wolf was instrumental in educating people and changing the public‚Äôs attitudes towards wolves around the world, and singlehandedly saved the lives of countless wolves. He also strongly suspected that there was a greater European presence in the Canadian Arctic, during the Viking Age and before. While in the Arctic, he studied mysterious stone longhouse foundations in northern Quebec and Nunavut, which are unlike anything the Inuit built, as they were nomadic for centuries. He noted they were similar to Viking Age and even earlier Iron Age longhouses, and in his book The Farfarers, he proposed that the original inhabitants of Scotland, whom he called the Albans, may have fled to the Orkneys and Iceland following the invasions of the Celts and the Anglo Saxons, and then fled to the New World following the Viking invasion. Just like with Patricia Sutherland, government funding for his studies ended because the Inuit complained; but there may have been more to this complaint than just his wolf study.

A memorial to Farley Mowat in Toronto. Farley Mowat suspected that peoples from the British Isles may have reached North America before the Vikings, and wrote a speculative fiction book about this; The Farfarers. Since then, the foundations of an Irish-style roundhouse has been found near Reykjavik, and further north, a man-made cave with crosses carved on the walls has been found near Seljaland, both of which predate the recorded arrival of the Vikings in Iceland by a century. Farley may have been correct. Pics by my friend Clayton Elmy.

A 15th century Dutch word to refer to the Big Dipper is ‚ÄúWoenswagen‚Äù, or in English, ‚ÄúWoden‚Äôs Wagon‚Äù. This of course implies a connection between the Allfather and the constellation. The Little Dipper in Norse tradition is sometimes referenced as ‚ÄúKvennavagn‚Äù (Woman‚Äôs Wagon) and is seen to be driven by Freyja. (Who I and many experts conflate to √ì√∞inn‚Äôs Wife Frigg). Both of these constellations revolve around the North Star in our night sky. When they complete a full rotation, they make the patter of a swastika, which is an odinic symbol connected to death and passing on to the next world. Check my pins if you would like to read the post I‚Äôve made on it for context. In many other traditions around the world, the North Star (Polaris) is seen as the gateway to Heaven. In Gr√≠mnism√°l, it explains that √ì√∞inn chooses half the dead while Freyja chooses the other half.

Here is the pattern that is made when they complete a rotation around the North Star (in red). The closest dipper is of course kvennavagn (Freyja‚Äôs Wagon) while the one farthest from the star is Woenswagen (√ì√∞inn‚Äôs Wagon).

cleaned_message: How very mature of you. If you actually read the thread Odynets is referencing, not once did I deny that the many branches of Indo-European religion are indeed ethnic, but, they are related. I do not believe our Gods are so small and weak as to be limited to only one branch of Indo-European culture each. I can no longer in good faith endorse this channel. Shame, I liked his content, and the work he‚Äôs done translating lesser known works.

Alright, someone posed the very valid question of how I reconcile being a Folkish Pagan with the fact that multiple Indo-European cultures venerate Gods which clearly have cognates in other IE pantheons. First of all, every Indo-European religion has an aspect of ancestor worship, which inseparably binds a faith to its people. Secondly, Y-DNA Haplogroup I1. This haplogroup appeared in southern Scandinavia in the Bronze Age, and has yet to be found among over a hundred continental European samples from the same period. Southern Scandinavia is where the Irminones originated, and according to Snorri‚Äôs euhemerized account, where Odin sired the first of our Folk. You‚Äôll find many IE religions have myths about Gods siring bloodlines on Earth. You can accept that your culture is part of a larger mosaic without sacrificing your unique cultural identity. At least I hope you can; our enemies would love for us to stay divided.

‚ÄúCome now: Do we really think that the gods are everywhere called by the same names by which they are addressed by us? But the gods have as many names as there are languages among humans. For it is not with the gods as with you: you are Velleius wherever you go, but Vulcan is not Vulcan in Italy and in Africa and in Spain.‚Äù ·õâ ~Marcus Tullius Cicero

Before I even knew who Cicero was, one of the things that made me have faith in paganism over Christianity is, countless cultures, many with little to no contact, always seemed to organically come to the conclusion that there were certain deities; a Sky Father, Earth Mother, Thunderer/Striker, Divine Son, etc., most of which share multiple characteristics.

‚ÄúThis seems to be advanced as the surest basis for our belief in the existence of gods, that there is no race so uncivilized, no one in the world so barbarous that his mind has no inkling of a belief in gods.‚Äù ~Marcus Tullius Cicero

Here‚Äôs Bald‚Äôs second Leechbook, with the original Old English text; https://www.repository.cam.ac.uk/bitstream/handle/1810/268228/Doyle-2017-PhD_appendix.pdf?sequence=2&isAllowed=y

This book talks about the Anglo Saxon traditions of herbal medicines and healing, through surviving medical manuscripts, Christo-pagan magic, and there‚Äôs a section on the use of amulets. It includes a few original Anglo Saxon medical texts; the Old English Herbarium, the Lacnunga, and part of Bald‚Äôs Leechbook, with the original facing Old English text. Recently, a salve for an eye infection from Bald‚Äôs Leechbook (L√¶ce was an Old English term for doctor), made with onion, garlic, wine and cow bile, was found to be able to treat MRSA; an antibiotic resistant bacteria which has baffled the best scientists. Many of these texts were suppressed for centuries after the Norman invasion, considered to be witchcraft. This book would be great for those who are interested in our history, and traditional medicine. Many of the plants mentioned in these books have been examined by modern scientists, and confirmed to have legitimate medicinal uses. Depending on where you live, I‚Äôd recommend supplementing it with a book on Native ethnobotany in your area. Learning about traditional medicine is never a bad idea. The past few years have shown how feeble and unreliable the global medicine supply chains can be. This book can help you become the L√¶ce your √ûƒìod needs.

As far as religion, while many Maasai have become Christians and Muslims, they traditionally worship a single god, Engai. A volcano called Ol Doinyo Lengai is believed to be his home (very Landv√¶ttir-like), and the white lava it emits is said to be his beard. His benevolent aspect is called Black Engai, his wrathful aspect, Red Engai. I wonder if this is in reference to dried lava, and molten lava.

For the Maasai and other Nilotic peoples, the weapon of choice is an iconic throwing spear not unlike the Roman pilum, with a long, thin iron shaft, and a leaf-shaped head. In the related Nilotic Turkana tribe, boys become men when they can make a clean kill with one of these spears.

When I visited the Maasai People, I was surprised to learn that they had maintained a coming of age ritual, strikingly similar to the Indo-European Koryos. When a boy comes of age, 15-17, he undergoes a ritual death and rebirth. He trades his brightly coloured shuka (cloak) for a black one, shaves his head, paints his face with white clay, and leaves his tribe. For the next several months, these initiates survive on their own in the wilderness. In days gone by, they may have scouted new lands to raid-or been sent to hunt a lion. Upon returning to their tribe, the boys are recognized as men, and Moran (warriors). They are given their red shuka and their own spear and shield, and are permitted to marry. Having completed their initiation, they grow their hair long and elaborately braid it.

This is a fascinating read‚Ä¶genetic evidence of an R1b invasion into Central Africa in the Bronze Age. Oddly enough, several Nilotic peoples of Central and Eastern Africa who carry this gene have staunchly maintained a nomadic pastoralist lifestyle not unlike that of the early Indo-Europeans, subsisting largely on red meat and milk. I‚Äôve met Maasai and Kurya people who I thought had strangely European facial features. I suppose this is why. https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5142112/
