Norse Paganism in the Middle Ages Have you heard of Erik Klasson and Ragvald Odenskarl? Both men were 15th century Swedes executed for openly declaring themselves Pagans, but their stories are even more interesting. In 1492 Erik was executed for "sorcery", theft and heresy. He was originally a servant of Hans Persson on the island of V√§rmd√∂. When Erik was put before the court in Stockholm he had declared that he had sworn himself to Odin to escape poverty, and that he stole from his master a few times. In Erik's case he was being judged for his Paganism but officially judged for sorcery making it ambiguous to determine whether it was a witch trial or trial of heresy. In the eyes of the Church, native European Gods were demons and even though Erik himself meant Odin when he said "Oden", the Church translated this as "Satan" and thus Erik was judged as a devil-worshipper. The second case was that of Ragvald Odenskarl ("Odin's Man", "Odin's Jarl"). Ragvald was put on trial on the 27th October 1484 for having stolen from Skepptuna Church twice, Markims Church, Orkesta Church and Vallentuna Church. Ragvald himself declared that he had served Odin for seven years and was not a Christian but a follower of the old way.

In Germania, Tacitus wrote that ‚ÄúThe Germans do not think it in keeping with the divine majesty to confine gods within walls or to portray them in the likeness of any human countenance. Their holy places are woods and groves, and they apply the names of deities to that hidden presence which is seen only by the eye of reverence.‚Äù Makes one wonder if the early Germanic tribes even used images. I‚Äôve noticed that following the Nordic Bronze Age, pre-Roman contact Germanic idols were very abstract, often without so much as a face. But, more highly detailed images of Gods, including small bronze figurines, began to reappear from the 6-7th Century onwards. My theory is that these may have been influenced by portable Roman military shrines. When you look at the level of sophistication with other Germanic Iron Age art, I tend to think the abstract designs were intentional. As if to say, I do not claim to know the true faces of the Gods.

This 7th century Indian idol was found in Staraya Maina, Volga River Basin, Russia. Thought to depict either Vishnu or Kali. It‚Äôs been proposed that the Volga could be one of the unidentifiable rivers mentioned in the Rig Veda. Much of the garnet used in early medieval Europe can be traced back to India, especially Rajasthan, and Sri Lanka; it could have been brought to Europe by way of the Volga. Aside from a pocket in Bavaria, garnet is not found in Europe. Pic 2: an Anglo Saxon ‚Äúkeystone‚Äù brooch, with an intact garnet.
Haakon Jarl commands the clergymen to return ashore, by Christian Krohg, 1899. It was an illustration for the 1899 edition of the Heimskringla.

On the √ñverhogdal tapestries that I have posted about before, there is a tree depicted with a bird, possibly an eagle on the top of it, that is likely a depiction of the axis mundi in Germanic tradition, Yggdrasil. If you look at the bottom and to the left of the tree, there is a horse shown with 8 legs. Very likely a depiction of √ì√∞inn‚Äôs horse, Sleipnir. This would make sense because he uses Sleipnir to travel through all of the 9 realms that exist within the great tree.

Should you find your pages are attracting playgans and brosatrus, you can scare them off with three simple sentences‚Ä¶ I‚Äôm not spiritual, I‚Äôm religious. They‚Äôre not ‚Äúenergies‚Äù, they‚Äôre Gods. I don‚Äôt ‚Äúwork with‚Äù, I worship them.

An early Anglo Saxon wrist clasp, Hines type C1, 5-7th Century. This was a very popular design in the early Anglo Saxon period, with two Salin I-style birds. The fact that the double-bird motif disappeared from Anglo Saxon art following the 8th Century suggests it was an overtly pagan motif; potentially Woden‚Äôs ravens.

Anglo Saxon and Langobardic glass drinking horns, 6-7th Century. Glass was far more labour intensive and expensive in the Iron Age, and we‚Äôve found several glass drinking horns in noble burials across Germanic Europe. The horn shape may have been kept due to its use in rituals.

Finds from the wealthy middle aged woman‚Äôs grave in Himling√∏je, Denmark dated to 3rd c AD. Glass, amber, gold and bronze jewellery, a bronze spindle whorl and a glass drinking horn. The fibula in the grave had a runic inscription of a man's name "widuhudaR" who may have been her husband and the owner of some of these items. In her mouth was a gold coin with which she could pay a ferryman in Hel.

Fun fact from Teutonic Mythology‚Ä¶an Old Icelandic kenning for foxes was Holta√æ√≥rr; Thor of the holt (den), in reference to Thor‚Äôs red beard. It was used as late as the 19th Century. There are no red foxes in Iceland, so I suspect this goes back to the Viking Age. ·öº

The √û√≥rsdr√°pa is one of the oldest Eddic poems, first recorded in the 10th Century by Eil√≠fr Go√∞r√∫narson, a court skald of H√°kon Sigur√∞arson. It recounts how Thor got his hammer and gauntlets, and Thor‚Äôs battle with the J√∂tunn Geirro√∞, whom he defeats by throwing a molten lump of iron with his gauntlets. Two other versions are preserved in the Sk√°ldskaparm√°l, recorded by Eysteinn Valdason, and another by √ûorbj√∂rn d√≠sarsk√°ld, which include Thor‚Äôs fishing trip with Hymir a list of J√∂tnar slain by Thor. It was later echoed in the Gesta Danorum. Art by Gillian McClure.
Another example, found in East Anglia. With this mask-and-birds motif, the eyes are often asymmetrical. Very Wodenic.
An Anglo Saxon cruciform brooch terminal, found on the Isle of Wight, 5-7th Century. Notice how one eye is slightly obscured.

Reading volume 2 of Grimm‚Äôs Teutonic Mythology, found an interesting detail‚Ä¶in medieval German folklore, Thor was twisted into a demonic figure because of his association with goats, while Odin was likened to the Christian God. It was even said that the Devil created goats, but God created wolves, and chose wolves as his hounds. ·ö¨ Art: Odin, der G√∂ttervater by Carl Emil Doepler, 1880.
A small Anglo Saxon gilded mount with a knotwork design, possibly from a belt. Found in East Anglia, likely 5-7th Century.

An awesome painting of Lord Parshuram, artist unknown to me. Parshuram is by far my favourite avatar of Vishnu. We would be wise to remember how Parshuram dealt with tyrants; he didn‚Äôt compromise with them, debate with them, tolerate them, point out their hypocrisy, sign online petitions against them, or try to vote them away‚Ä¶He hacked them to pieces with an axe.

An Anglo Saxon or Anglo Scandinavian silver garment hook, or ‚Äúhooked tag‚Äù. This is the only example I‚Äôve seen with the looped fylfot design. Found near York, 7-11th Century. These were likely used for winningas or woollen hose, and have also been found in burials at waist height, which suggests they may have been used as fasteners for belt pouches.

The Wildberg Man is a potential image of a Germanic priest. This statue was found near Stuttgart, and was made at some point during the Iron Age. The outfit, with the long robe and belt, resembles that of the priest statues at the Acropolis, which led to the theory that this statue depicts a priest. Long hair and beards may have been a mark of priesthood. The Chatti weren‚Äôt permitted to cut their hair or beards until they‚Äôd killed an enemy. Centuries later, Harald Fairhair vowed not to cut his hair until he‚Äôd united all of Norway. A priest‚Äôs uncut hair could have been a mark of a lifelong oath to serve the Gods as a priest.
A small silver vessel from Lejre, Denmark. It wouldn‚Äôt have held much liquid; perhaps it was used for an Ausa Vatni ritual.

Insight into Ausa Vatni, the Germanic naming ceremony. There‚Äôs a few accounts of this practice in the Poetic Edda and the Sagas. The consistent aspect is sprinkling water over the baby, Ausa Vatni means ‚Äúto pour over water‚Äù in Old Norse. From the Poetic Edda: H√°vam√°l: ‚ÄúA thirteenth I know, if a thane full young With water I sprinkle well; He shall not fall, though he fares mid the host, Nor sink beneath the swords.‚Äù (H√°vam√°l 158, Bellows) R√≠gs√æula: ‚ÄúA son had Mothir, in silk they wrapped him, With water they sprinkled him, Jarl he was; Blond was his hair, and bright his cheeks, Grim as a snake's were his glowing eyes.‚Äù (R√≠gs√æula 34, Bellows) From the Eyrbyggja Saga: ‚ÄúThen in the summer when √û√≥rsteinn was twenty-five years old, √û√≥ra gave birth to another son, who was sprinkled with water and given the name Grim. √û√≥rsteinn dedicated this boy to √û√≥rr, calling him √û√≥rgrimr, and said he should become temple priest.‚Äù In the Saga of Harald Fairhair in the Heimskringla, Halfdan the Black pours water from a silver bowl over Harald before giving him his name, along with ten pounds of gold. In the Saga of the Jomsvikings, Cnut is sprinkled with water when he‚Äôs given his name. By the account in the Eyrbyggja Saga, Thor was invoked to protect the child. As water was used to give offerings to Gods, Ausa Vatni would also serve to bond the child to the deity. In the case of √û√≥rgrimr, -Grimr means ‚Äúmask‚Äù; Thor‚Äôs mask/vessel, and he becomes a priest. Ausa Vatni is a prime example of why we mustn‚Äôt be too quick to disregard anything that sound too Christian on the surface. This is absolutely a traditional Germanic practice, and a practice that modern pagans can reclaim and revive. ·õö

cleaned_message: This is another excellent read. It breaks down the various Germanic aspects that were absorbed into Christianity in the Middle Ages. Jacob Grimm wrote about this quite a bit in Teutonic Mythology too. While in their purest forms, Germanic paganism and Christianity are fundamentally incompatible, in order to be palatable enough for the Germanic warlords who ended up spreading it, Christianity had to absorb certain aspects of Germanic culture and paganism. Chances are, there are things that you currently associate with Christianity that are of Germanic origin. For example, Ausa Vatni and baptism. Too many modern pagans are too quick to knee-jerk and reject anything that remotely resembles Christianity; this book can help us recover what was ours in the first place.

Regardless of which religion you may follow, when you read a holy text, be it the Eddas, the Sagas, the Vedas, the Sutras, the Gita, you‚Äôre inevitably going to find something that challenges and contradicts your existing worldview, values and desires. At this point, you‚Äôll have a transformative choice to make; you can put in the work to interpret and understand it, or, cherry pick a few out-of-context verses, lie to yourself, and make yourself comfortable at the cost of stunting your spiritual growth. Unfortunately, most seem to choose the second option these days. ·õâ Pic: The Codex Regius, with the title of the H√°vam√°l visible in red.

Heard someone claim that the Gods wouldn‚Äôt reward their followers, because they do not punish. Oh, they do. From the Poetic Edda alone, off the top of my head; V√∂luspa: oathbreakers, kinslayers and adulterers are sent to N√°strond, where they are shredded by N√≠√∞√∏ggr and a wolf (Garmr?). Gr√≠mnism√°l: Odin causes Geirr√∏√∞ to fall on his sword, expediting his trip to Hel. Lokasenna: Odin guts Loki‚Äôs son and binds him with his own entrails. Alvissmal: Thor causes Alviss to turn to stone. Sigdr√≠fum√°l: Odin casts Brunhild down to Midgard. Helgakvi√∞a Hundingsbana II: Odin gives Dagr a spear to exact revenge. And see also; the Hervarar Saga ok Hei√∞reks, wherein Thor strikes down Starka√∞r Aludreng, and King Hei√∞rekr is killed after striking at Odin in the form of a falcon, and the entire Gautreks Saga, wherein Thor lays multiple curses on Starka√∞r. Thank you all for reading my posts‚Ä¶now go read the lore!

Why do I spend time debating with brosatrus, whose minds I‚Äôm never going to change? Because one of the best ways to counter the rampant disinformation about our faith, wherever we see it, is by spreading information. Bystanders might see your comments and do some real research.

Don‚Äôt know what hole they keep crawling out of, but I continue to see self-purported Pagans claiming that things like the Gods giving their followers tangible rewards, or our ancestors having clear conceptions of good and evil, is ‚ÄúChristian.‚Äù If your religious baggage is keeping you from having a clear understanding of your own faith, work through that first, before you try to study any of our sacred texts. ·õá

Immediately there came ill-weather against the king so strong, that he might not hold out at sea.‚Äù ‚Ä¶I like how the Saga about the big bad king who converted everyone doesn‚Äôt outright deny the existence of Thor. How Paganism Has Changed My Life Since having come to the Native European traditions I have come to a greater connection with my ancestors and the traditions which are purely European in nature. I have come to a better understanding and connection of my identity and I have come to have a more fulfilled sense of self, purpose, meaning, and origin. I have a solid understanding and grasp of where I come from, why I am here, who I am, and where I am going in life. I have also gained a great degree of separation from what is described as "the modern world", or what can be described as the cesspit of societal rot, multiculturalism, degeneration of culture, and the overall disconnection from tribe that our people experience in The West. The Native European traditions and mythos has given me a sense of belonging and resolve that Christianity could never give me. Algiz Vidarsson

Photo of Silbury hill, taken by a friend who recently visited the area. Legend tells that king Sil is buried inside. The suffix ~bury comes from the OE byrƒ°an, hill or fort. Berg (mountain) and burh (fort) have the same root. So is ‚ÄòSil‚Äô OE as well? The common suggestion is Sil comes from the Romano-British goddess Sul but there was an OE word Syl, which was a pillar ‚Äì cognate with the German Sul (as in Irminsul). Syl survives in modern English Sile ‚Äì a large beam or timber. Whilst Silbury hill was constructed some 4500 years ago, author Jim Leary suggests that the Anglo-Saxons used the hill as a defensive site, with archaeological finds supporting the idea. Archaeology surveys also reveal a massive post hole found on the top of the hill. Older legends connect the hill with Ursa Major or ‚Äòthe plough‚Äô. It is believed that if you had been standing, looking up at the hill some 4500 years ago, the constellation Ursa Major appeared to plough the top of the flattened hill as it rotated round in the night sky.
An Anglo Saxon mount with two bird heads, found in Kelling, East Anglia, 5-7th Century. It has a suspension loop at one end, and may have been part of a sword suspension or a horse harness.

Hr√≥lfs Saga Gautrekssonar is an interesting one, with a potential Indo-Iranic connection. Queen √ûorbj√∂rg likes to fight, dislikes being called womanly, much to the disdain of her father, who calls her King √û√≥rbergr. Actual gender bending‚Ä¶wondering why the woke mob hasn‚Äôt gobbled it up yet. ‚Ä¶maybe it‚Äôs because when she‚Äôs eventually bested in combat by Hr√≥lfr and falls in love with him, she embraces her femininity, marries him, gives away her weapons and takes up weaving? It‚Äôs very similar to what Herodotus wrote about the Sarmatians, wherein women weren‚Äôt permitted to marry until they‚Äôd slain at least one man. The Sarmatians formed alliances with Germanic tribes on several occasions; first with the Alemanni to stop the eastern expansion of the Roman Empire, and later on, with the Goths against the Huns. It‚Äôs entirely possible some of their cultural practices were passed on to their Germanic allies.

‚ÄúA measure of wisdom each man shall have, But never too much let him know; For the wise man's heart is seldom happy, If wisdom too great he has won.‚Äù ~H√°vam√°l 55, Bellows Painting by Lorenz Fr√∏lich, 1844.
An early Anglo Saxon mount (or pendant?) with what appears to be a wolf, facing backwards with its jaws clasped around its body.
The Sutton Hoo buckle even has a few examples of this motif.

A recurring motif in Germanic Iron Age art was a beast with its jaws clasped around its own body. A good friend of mine suggested that it may be the Germanic equivalent of the ouroboros; symbolizing the eternal cycle of destruction and rebirth.
An early Anglo Saxon East Anglian style equal armed brooch, 5-6th Century.
The first Viking artifact found in L‚ÄôAnse aux Meadows was a spindle whorl. Several strands of Scandinavian-style spun yarn were found further north in Nunguvik, northern Baffin Island.

An offer to Sleipnir described in 1593 Spegel des antchristlichen pawesdomes by preacher N Gryse ‚ÄúF√ºr Wodes Pferd‚Äù (for Odin‚Äôs horse) ‚ÄúWode, hale dynem rosse nu voder, nu distel vnde dorn, thom andren jar beter korn.‚Äù = ‚ÄúWodan, haal uw ros voor, nu distel van de doorn, dan ander jaar beter koren‚Äù = ‚ÄúOdin, bring forth your horse, now thistle of the thorn, then next year better korn‚Äù Heathenry didn‚Äôt just stop at Christianity #germanicheathenry #belgianheathenheritage #heathenry #heathen #norsepagan #heidendom #paganism

The infamous Aarhus ‚Äúmask stone‚Äù, raised in memory of a warrior who died fighting against Olaf Tryggvason in the Battle of Svolder. The inscription reads; ‚ÄúGunnulfr and Au√∞gautr and √Åslakr and Hr√≥lfr raised this stone in memory of F√∫l, their partner, who died when kings fought.‚Äù ‚ÄúGunnulfr ok «æ√∞gotr ok √Åsl√°kr ok R√≥lfr r√©s√æu st√©n √æannsi √¶ftir F√∫l, f√©laga sinn, er var√∞ ... d«ø√∞r, √æ√° kunungar bar√∞usk.‚Äù
The Norse balance scale arm from Baffin Island, formerly Helluland, 11-14th Century.

A Viking Age folding balance scale arm, found in York, 9-11th Century. Even when the Vikings largely switched to coinage over bullion, balance scales were still used to test the purity of silver coins. A similar balance scale was found on Baffin Island, Nunavut.

The ‚ÄúBishop of Baffin‚Äù is a 13th to 14th Century Thule Inuit driftwood carving from Baffin Island, Nunavut, believed to depict a Norse Greenlander. The outfit resembles a bishop‚Äôs cassock, or even a warrior‚Äôs surcoat, with a cross on the chest.
A few near-complete examples, likely from the same workshop.
Another Anglo Saxon hanging bowl mount, found in east Hertfordshire, 7-8th Century. Beautiful knotwork decoration, with a few patches of yellow enamel still visible.

Viking Age artifacts from archaeological sites in Arctic Canada and Northwestern Greenland; a whetstone (a), a fragment of chainmail (b), a bronze vessel leg (c), two fragments of a bronze vessel (d,e), a wooden figurine of a person in European dress (f), and an arm of a bronze folding balance scale (g).
Smashan Kala Bhairava, by Vrindavan Art. üê∫üî±üôè

Widher is an attested name in Old Swedish which comes from the root *wƒ´daz meaning ‚Äòwide‚Äô. From this same root we get the name Vidar who is a son of Odin. Today I saw a reconstructed OE name *Wƒ´dhere in a poem dedicated to Vidar, very similar name to the Swedish Widher. The names Vidar and *Wƒ´dhere come from the root v√≠√∞r/wƒ´d (wide) and herr/here (army). The root *wƒ´daz is interesting because it means ‚Äòset apart or separate into two‚Äô as well as being cognate with *widuz meaning wood (Vidar is a woodland god). Vidar (or Wƒ´dhere) is known for his role of splitting or separating the jaws of Fenris apart.
Sacred grove by Arnold B√∂cklin
A Yamnaya necklace with dog teeth, and bone beads and dress pins.

An insight into the Koryos phenomenon, from the Russian Steppe. A Srubnaya Culture settlement in Krasnosamarskoe contained the bones of over 64 dogs. Recent carbon analysis shows these dogs lived comfortable lives with few injuries, and were quite old at time of death. These weren‚Äôt wild wolves‚Ä¶these were their pets. The bones also show signs of cooking, and carbon analysis also reveals that they died in the dead of winter-aligning with the VrƒÅtyastoma ritual mentioned in Rig Veda. It would appear that these dogs lived a full and complete life alongside their masters, until they were eventually eaten, whether they died of old age, or were sacrificed. The skulls were also broken open; in some Siberian cultures, this is done with shamans to release the soul. Many Bronze Age burials contain pendants made of dog teeth, including Kivik, Sweden; souvenirs of departed friends-or a mark of having completed this rite of passage. This ritual of eating one‚Äôs own pet dog could have been to destroy the last of one‚Äôs innocence, to harden these youthful warriors into stone cold killers, and/or to complete their initiation into a VrƒÅtya warrior cult.

"When earth is called the wife of Odin, the mother of Thor, when wind is styled the son of Fornj√≥t and the sea is conceived as Ran, the wife of √Ügir, the myths are not anthropomorphism or personification in the modern and Alexandrian sense. Human-likeness is joined to the other qualities of natural phenomena or, more truly expressed, human appearance enters as a quality among other qualities into the soul of earth, wind and sea, but it does not in the least interfere with the impersonal workings of the forces of nature." ~Vilhelm Gr√∏nbech, The Culture of the Teutons.

This is another excellent read; The Culture of the Teutons by Vilhelm Gr√∂nbech. Originally published in 1909, this book offers an extensive insight into the culture, religion and worldview of the Germanic peoples.
Grave goods from Sutton Hoo mound 17. Clearly belonged to an important person‚Ä¶could have been one of R√¶dwald‚Äôs √æegns, or another king.

I‚Äôm frequently asked about which books I‚Äôd recommend for people getting started in Germanic Paganism. Regardless of your experience level, two I consider essential along with the Poetic Edda and Rig Veda are; -Teutonic Mythology (Deutsche Mythologie)-Jacob Grimm One of the most intensive studies of the Germanic religion as a whole, drawing from Scandinavian, Anglo Saxon and continental Germanic sources; archaeology, literature, folklore and mythology. -The Road to Hel-Hilda Roderick Ellis (Davidson) One of the most intensive studies on the Germanic worldview surrounding the soul, death, the afterlife, reincarnation, and ancestor worship. Spoiler; you‚Äôre probably not going to Valhalla.

Insight into Anglo Saxon ancestor worship and offerings, from period accounts of Christian monks: Penitential of Theodore, 7th Century: ‚ÄúHe who causes grains to be burned where a man has died, for the health of the living and of the house, shall do penance for five years‚Äù. Confessional of Egbert, 8th Century: ‚ÄúAnyone who burns grain in the place where a dead man lay, for the health of living men and of his house (shall do one year of fasting)‚Äù. The 10th Century Writings of Alfric told priests not to ‚Äúeat or drink in the place where the corpse lies, lest you are imitators of the heathenism which they practice there‚Äù.
Last Halloween‚Ä¶fireworks going off outside, listening to the Kala Bhairava Ashtakam. üê∫üôèüî±

For those of you with dogs‚Ä¶wherever you may be, chances are there‚Äôs going to be fireworks soon. I found a the Kala Bhairava Ashtakam and the Hanuman Chalisa are great for helping a dog relax during fireworks. https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=BsEqI1NZA-E

cleaned_message: My wife and son are not able to attend the Summer blot to Thor tomorrow so they baked these dough idols for me to take as an offering on their behalf. The 8th century manuscript Indiculus superstitionum et paganiarum lists 30 kinds of cult practices among the Saxon pagans of the day. Number 26 is De simulacro de consparsa farina. "On the idol (made) from moistened flour.‚Äú This likely refers to a seasonal custom at high festivals in which perishable idols of the gods themselves, made from dough, were offered to the gods. Here we have Thor and one of his goats which will accompany our other offerings of libations and of goat meat.
And remember, the Anglo Saxon Penitential of Theodore and Confessional of Egbert both explicitly banned the burning of grain.
A 10th Century textile fragment from the Lendbreen ice patch, Norway, with the original blue colour still visible.
Thank you all for 800!

An ‚ÄúIbex-headed‚Äù pin. A casting mould for these was recently found in South Ronaldsey, Orkneys, dating to the 1st Century; possibly a Pictish design. Mine was found in East Anglia, and a few were found in Anglo Saxon burials; potentially souvenirs from battles with the Picts. One can easily see how this design evolved into the popular Hiberno Norse ringed pin, which was spread around the world by the Vikings.

A whalebone figure found in a 10th Century burial in Baldursheimur, northern Iceland. Very similar to the Thor figures from Eyrarland and Lund, with Thor gripping his beard. It was found alongside several gaming pieces, and may have served as a king piece, and/or a pocket god.
A rare sketch of Odin by Hans Thoma, 1839-1924.

The hilt of the Snartemo Sword, Norway, 6th Century. If you look closely, you can see several ‚Äútiermensch‚Äù (beast-man) motifs. This was a recurring theme in early Germanic art, with a mix of animal and human elements; likely cultic wolf warriors in the process of transformation.

‚ÄúThe lame rides a horse, the handless is herdsman, The deaf in battle is bold; The blind man is better than one that is burned, No good can come of a corpse.‚Äù ~H√°vam√°l 71, Bellows Don‚Äôt let your injuries, illnesses, obstacles or past defeats define you-overcome them. ·õè Art by Mary Evans.
Fun fact‚Ä¶the original Codex Regius is tiny. Whichever version of the Poetic Edda you have, chances are good that it‚Äôs much bigger than the original.
Ravnkel Freysgode by Andreas Bloch, 1895.

From the Eyrbyggja Saga, we know that becoming a go√∞i involved offering yourself to a deity‚Ä¶but what would happen if a deity rejected a go√∞i? Hrafnkels Saga gives us an idea. Hrafnkell becomes a go√∞i and builds a temple dedicated to Freyr, where he hosted bl√≥ts and feasts in his honour. However, he continues to get into duels, and refuses to pay weregild, and even kills one of his subordinates when he rides a horse he dedicated to Freyr. Go√∞ar were exempt from taxes, but him expecting to be exempt from paying weregild as well could be seen as him abusing his priestly title. After this, he loses everything; S√°mr seizes his estate, his temple is burned down, and his sacred horse thrown off a cliff. It‚Äôs as if he lost the favour of Freyr himself. I‚Äôve heard it proposed this Saga was a Christian subversion, but Hrafnkell doesn‚Äôt convert to Christianity after his defeat; he just becomes a bitter atheist. I see it more as a cautionary tale against abusing a priestly title, even the favour of the Gods. Anyone can claim to be a go√∞i, but ultimately, the Gods will have the final word.

It was also a most astonishing feat when you wrestled with Elle, for none has ever been, and none shall ever be, that Elle (eld, old age) will not get the better of him, though he gets to be old enough to abide her coming. Art by Dmitriy Galkin

Another Vendel S-shaped brooch. The S-shaped serpent was a recurring motif in the Germanic Iron Age, most popular in Scandinavia and France. One possible interpretation is that it was a ward against unseen threats, as there was a beast facing in each direction. Another possibility is it was an Odinic symbol; as serpents were heavily associated with the underworld and the cult of Odin. The two heads could signify his role as a psychopomp, travelling between the worlds of the living and the dead.
Viking Dragon soapstone casting mould, 8th - 13th century, Bj√∂rk√∂, Adels√∂, Uppland, Sweden. It reminds me a lot of vendel era dragon designs such as this one on the right from Sutton Hoo, England

"To be happy in the language of slaves is to sleep soundly and to be gluttonous. To be happy?! I am slain by your idea of happiness as a liquid and tasteless porridge! How foolish and disgusting is everything for which you exchange your laurel wreaths, your immortality. Oh! Blessed luminary, you who move tirelessly up there, in your inaccessible and great kingdom, give me particles of your soul and send rays that pierce my body and mind! How I want to be happy artificially and not like these slaves! Children of the Sun are nourished by their heroic deeds. They live in victory, drinking greatness in their souls and joy in their might." ~Johann Christian Friedrich H√∂lderlin, "Hyperion"
An S-shaped serpent brooch, found in western Zealand, Denmark, 7th Century.

Scored a beautiful classic print of the Poetic Edda, Henry Bellows‚Äôs translation. Seems to be a rare edition, I‚Äôm not finding much information on it. Keep an eye on those used book stores, even eBay. You never know what you might find.
A Germanic (Langobard?) brooch, found in Schwanbeck, northeastern Germany, not far from where the Langobards began their southward journey. Very Kolovrat-like.

This Gallo-Roman statue of an unknown goddess called "the good woman" has been worshipped by Gauls and Bretons for nearly 2000 years. People call it a Venus, but it isn't. The church had it thrown in the river in 1661 and again in 1670, but locals retrieved it both times and resumed worshipping her. There were widespread pagan practices in Brittany in the 17th century such that great efforts were made to christianise several Megalithic monuments where worship occurred. The statue was altered in 1700 and put on display in some gardens with a huge granite bath which was also associated with her cult. I went there and offered her some flowers today
The Eyrbyggja Saga is a gold mine for any serious Germanic pagan. The 1892 translation by William Morris & Eirikr Magnusson is available here: https://sagadb.org/eyrbyggja_saga.en

The Eyrbyggja Saga offers insight into what a go√∞i‚Äôs initiation rite may have looked like... ‚Äú√û√≥ra gave birth to another son, who was sprinkled with water and given the name Grim. √û√≥rsteinn dedicated this boy to √û√≥rr, calling him √û√≥rgrim, and said he should become a Hofgo√∞i.‚Äù First of all, Ausa Vatni; ritual cleansing. Ausa Vatni marked the beginning of a new chapter in life, and, offered the person to a deity, as water was used as a medium to commune with the otherworld. It was usually done nine days after birth. When the Teutonic Order set up in Riga, Latvia, the Baltic pagans would submit to baptism suspiciously quickly, but would always jump in the sacred Daugava River afterwards. They believed that this would wash off the foreign religion, and wash it all the way back to Germany. Secondly, giving a holy title, something that‚Äôs also survived in Hindu and Buddhist traditions. In √û√≥rgrim‚Äôs case, -Grim means ‚Äúmask‚Äù; implying he was offered as a vessel to Thor. Most of this would have been done at birth, if a go√∞i planned on passing on the position to his children. Yet, if someone became a go√∞i later in life, it‚Äôs plausible that they‚Äôd follow a similar process. Germanic names consisted of two elements; often containing a holy element, such as a sacred animal or the name of a God. For example, Thorolf=Thor+wolf; wolf of Thor. Ingvarr=Ingvi+warrior; warrior of Ing. Arnvi√∞r=eagle+tree; tree of the eagle (Yggdrasil?). This will be why the Catholic Church was so intent on baptizing pagan leaders; by the Germanic worldview, baptism would effectively take you away from your Gods and give you to another. ·õö
Norsemen Landing in Iceland by Oscar Arnold Wergeland, 1877.

‚ÄúA son is better, though late he be born, And his father to death have fared; Memory-stones seldom stand by the road Save when kinsman honors his kin.‚Äù ·õü ~Havamal 72, Bellows ‚ÄúSonr er betri, √æ√≥tt s√© s√≠√∞ of alinn eftir genginn guma; sjaldan bautarsteinar standa brautu n√¶r, nema reisi ni√∞r at ni√∞.‚Äù Pic: the Aarhus ‚ÄúMask Stone‚Äù, raised in memory of a warrior who died fighting Olaf Tryggvason in the Battle of Svolder.
A stunning Viking Age zoomorphic strap end, found in Dale Abbey, Derbyshire, 10-11th Century. The face is very sturgeon-like, as with many Viking Age depictions of serpents.
The Wolves Pursuing S√≥l and M√°ni by John Charles Dollman, 1909.

A prayer to S√≥l for Midsommar, based on a Rigvedic Surya hymn. Her bright rays bear her up aloft, the Goddess who knoweth all that lives, S√≥l, that all may look on her. The stars pass away before the all-beholding Sun. Her herald rays are seen afar refulgent over Midgard, like flames of fire that burn and blaze, Swift and all beautiful art thou, O S√≥l, maker of the light, illuming all of Midgard. Thou goest to the hosts of Gods, thou comest hither to mankind, hither all light to be beholden. Traversing sky and wide mid-air, thou metest with thy beams our days, S√≥l, seeing all things that have birth. Seven Bay Steeds harnessed to thy chariot bear thee, O thou farseeing One, S√≥l, with the radiant hair. S√≥l hath yoked the pure bright Seven, the daughters of the chariot, she goeth forth. Looking upon the loftier light above the darkness we have come to S√≥l, Goddess among the Gods, the light that is most excellent. Rising this day, ascending to Asgard, S√≥l, With all her conquering vigour the Sun hath gone up on high, giving my foe into mine hand: let me not be my foeman's prey. G√≥√∞an Midsommar!

A beautiful Anglo Saxon saucer brooch, found in Temple Grafton, Warwickshire, 6-7th Century. The design is very reminiscent of later Viking Age Terslev-style brooches, with the design consisting of a long tendril wrapping around a squarish frame.
Wodan Sacrifice, by Milek Jakubiec.

The most complete Roman lorica segmentata ever found was unearthed at Kalkriese, in the Teutoburg Forest, dating to 9AD. Because it was seemingly discarded, many suspect the soldier who it belonged to may have survived the initial battle, and been sacrificed afterwards.

Pendants made of rock crystal shaped into a ball were popular across the Germanic world. Pictured are Anglo Saxon, Frankish and Viking Age examples. ‚Ä¶I do wonder, if in the V√∂lundarkvi√∞a, the pendants V√∂lundr set the eyes of N√≠√∞u√∞r‚Äôs sons into were this style of pendant.
An early Anglo Saxon bracteate found in Norfolk, with a possible early depiction of Fenrir eating Tiw‚Äôs hand. ·õè

S√¶mundr fr√≥√∞i was born 56 years after Iceland‚Äôs formal acceptance of Christianity, and paganism wasn‚Äôt outlawed in Iceland until 1121AD, due only to pressure from the Kingdom of Norway. Iceland would still have been full of pagans when S√¶mundr was alive, and he would have known and consulted many of them while he was compiling the Poetic Edda.

‚ÄúS√¶mund, son of Sigfus, the reputed collector of the poems bearing his name, which is sometimes also called the Elder, and the Poetic, Edda, was born at Oddi, his paternal dwelling in the south of Iceland, between the years 1054 and 1057, or about 50 years after the establishment by law of the Christian religion in that island; hence it is easy to imagine that many heathens, or baptized favourers of the old mythic songs of heathenism, may have lived in his days and imparted to him the lays of the times of old, which his unfettered mind induced him to hand down to posterity.‚Äù ~Benjamin Thorpe‚Äôs introduction to the Poetic Edda, 1866.
Have you ever wondered what the Eyrarland Thor Idol looked like gilt in 22 karat gold? Wonder no more.
Lovely. The Saga of Olaf Tryggvason mentions a statue of Thor made of silver with a beard of gold, so this is quite fitting.

I‚Äôve shared this idea in recent years that the sun is representative of his all seeing eye and the moon being his wavering one. I wonder if the sacrificing of his eye is tied to the blood moon at all. Maybe when the Germanic peoples looked to the skies on the night of the blood moon, they would recount the myth where the Allfather gave his eye to Mimir in return for a drink from the Well of Memory.

The Sun and Moon have lore of their own, but there is the idea that the sun and moon are also the seeing and blind eyes of Woden himself. Woden‚Äôs bynames include B√°leygr or Flaming Eye (B√°l meaing fire) and the similar name Bileygr, Flashing Eye or Wavering Eye. The picture above is a copy of the Nebenstedt bracteate and the runes (written backwards and anti clockwise) spell gl√ØaugiR u√Øu rnR which are meant to mean ‚Äòglowing eye consecrates the runes‚Äô. ‚ÄòGlowing Eye‚Äô is of course Woden and it‚Äôs easily to imagine his seeing eye as the all seeing sun above.

‚ÄúIf haply a fool should find for himself wealth or a woman's love, pride waxes in him but wisdom never and onward he fares in his folly.‚Äù ~H√°vam√°l 78, Olive Bray translation Art: Wotan als Wanderer by Arpad Schmidhammer, 1903.
A stunning Viking Age sword guard recently found in Denmark.

How the Snaptun hearth stone would have been used back in the Viking Age. The hole would hold the bellows, and the stone would keep it from burning. My thinking is the carving of Loki would serve to remind the smith not to turn his back on the fire. Another theory I‚Äôve heard (thanks Cole) is because in the Gylfaginning, Loki faces off against the fire j√∂tunn H√°logi, it could have been a ward to help keep the fire under control. Fighting chaos with chaos, fire with fire, if you will.
Another Viking Age solar compass found in Wolin, Poland, 11th Century.
The Uunartoq Disc was found in an 11th Century Norse settlement near the Uunartoq Hot Springs, Greenland. It was likely used as a solar compass and latitude reader.

From Mr. Tom on Twitter‚Ä¶ "We are losing a connection with our ancestral ways. We have, like the Native Americans and Aborigines, a fantastic native tradition; folk stories, myths, and a spiritual connection with nature, with the soil and the stone. It's time we reclaim that." -Ray Mears

I visited Brittish Museum in London so I m sharing some of the things that intriged me. This one was found in the river Schelde (Scaldis) in Flanders, Belgium. My absolute favorite ship figure head. Allthough the description of the museum alludes to a possible Roman influence, other historians pointed out this is likely of Germanic making. Saxons and Frisians and Frankish tribes were well established in late Roman era in these parts.
The Landn√°mab√≥k said to remove a ship‚Äôs dragon-prow when coming in to land, as not to offend the Landv√¶ttir. It would appear this belief went back further.
An interesting Roman Mithras military shrine, depicting Mithras directing his devotees to what appears to be a Lingam.

A Vendel-era bow brooch, found in Kaliningrad, Russia, 5-8th Century. Kaliningrad was once the site of Kaup, a significant amber trading post along the Amber Road. A casting mould for these brooches was recently found in Helg√∂, Sweden, and similar brooches have been found in Germany and Latvia.

A Frankish (or Alemannic?) fibula found in Neudingen, Germany. The longer you look at it, the more the design reveals itself. You can see two large Salin I-style animal heads on the head plate and a bearded face on the foot plate, flanked by a two more larger animals. Quite possibly Wodan.
Worship in the Sacred Grove by Reinier Vinkeles, 1788 - 1790.

cleaned_message: The golden Finnestorp Odin buckle from V√§sterg√∂tland in central Sweden is dated to the Migration period, around the 5th or 6th century and is believed to depict Odin, with one of his eye's altered, presumably during a ritual, gazing down into Mimir's well in which we see the reflection of his two ravens "thought" and "memory". There is also a small stick supporting a hemisphere in the well, which has been interpreted as representing the sacrificed eye of Odin, who, at the time the buckle was made, would have been known as "Wodinz" in Sweden.
You can also see two raven heads in front of Odin‚Äôs face, flanked by two wolves on the frame of the buckle.

The ash tent poles from the Gokstad Ship burial, and a reconstruction of the tent. The main body of the tent would likely have been made of tightly woven wool, like ship sails. Traces of black and yellow paint were found on the heads. ‚Ä¶clearly, I need to step up my camping game.

A fragment of an Olaf Guthfrithson (or rather, √ìl√°fr Gu√∞r√∏√∞sson) penny with the iconic raven, struck in York, 939-941AD. It would appear that the moneyer struck this one a bit too eagerly, and punched out the middle. It would have been usable as silver bullion.

Several tiny sheet gold figures were found during the excavation of the Uppakra Temple. Over 120 have been found, dating from 400AD to 900AD. Each one was around 1-1.5cm tall. Possibly votive offerings, or ornaments for the temple walls. In the beginning of The Northman, you may have noticed the temple pillars were decorated with these gold figures.

What the Uppakra Temple may have looked like in its glory days. The excavation of the foundation revealed four large pillars around a central fire pit, not unlike the Ranheim Temple in central Norway. The doors were on the sidewalls, like the temple described in the Eyrbyggja Saga. The layout is similar to a few surviving stave churches; many of which may have originally been pagan temples that were repurposed into churches. According to Bede‚Äôs Ecclesiastical History, most pagan temples weren‚Äôt destroyed, but rather were repurposed. Before the 5th century, most Germanic peoples worshipped in sacred groves and outdoor weohs; these temples were likely influenced by contact with the Roman Empire. As Hilda Ellis Davidson pointed out, the small Roman temples unearthed in England follow a similar construction pattern. The Uppakra Temple is the most complete Germanic temple we‚Äôve found yet, and can serve as a reference for building new ones. Art by V√§nehem Illustration.

Viking Age and later Anglo Saxon depictions of ‚Äúdragons‚Äù often have barbels and sloping heads; like unto sturgeons. Early Medieval depictions of dragons and sea serpents may not have been so otherworldly, but rather, inspired by fleeting glimpses of the dryhten of the deep.

Anglo Saxon fish totems... Several fish-shaped shield mounts have been found in early Anglo Saxon sites, including the Sutton Hoo Burial. Many appear to depict the Northern Pike, a fierce, predatory fish that the Anglo Saxons described as ‚Äúwolfish‚Äù, known to hunt in packs, and occasionally bite swimmers and fishermen. English rivers were once home to sturgeons, which can grow to upwards of three thousand pounds in the Volga Delta. In Russia, the Kaluga Sturgeon is known for dragging fishermen out of their boats. In medieval England, eating sturgeon was restricted to the king. The sturgeon may have been a symbol of royalty further back, as the largest living fish in Europe‚Äôs waterways. The early Anglo Saxons left offerings in rivers, where sturgeons dwelt. It is entirely likely that these massive fish were also considered the patrons of these sacred waterways.

The Maine Penny is possible evidence of Viking exploration further south in North America. This Norse penny was found at the Goddard Site in Brooklin, Maine, along with other fragments of worked copper alloy. It looks to be a penny of Olaf Kyrre, who ruled Norway from 1067-1093. Some recent evidence suggests that the site known in the Vinland Sagas as H√≥p was in New Brunswick, where the Vikings went for lumber. Emerging evidence suggests they may have been trading lumber with the Inuit further north in Nunavut.

A noble Anglo Saxon lady‚Äôs personal effects, from a burial in Gloucestershire, 6-7th Century. Couple of gilded brooches, glass and amber beads, silver (hair?) rings, a comb, and more peculiarly, a pendant made of a beaver‚Äôs tooth.

I find it awfully amusing how while several Sagas (including one of my favourites, the Eyrbyggja Saga) end on a note of ‚ÄúThor bad, Christianity good‚Äù, they describe in detail pagan temples and practices. Despite the fact that we have rock carvings depicting Thor‚Äôs fishing trip with Hymir, and Sigur√∞r‚Äôs battle with Fafnir and Regin, and the similarities between the H√°konarm√°l and the H√°vam√°l, and several poems sharing similarities with other Indo European texts such as the Puranas, I still see people insisting that the Poetic Edda and Sagas are somehow Christian. To which I say, then what exactly are you going off of? Vikings? Marvel? UPG? Imagination? It‚Äôs always the same kinds of people, hippies and playgans trying to deconstruct and reshape the Old Ways into a postmodern, new age perversion where they‚Äôre in charge and their existing beliefs are validated. There‚Äôs no reasoning with them. For example, one striking parallel between the Edda and the Puranas is Odin‚Äôs introduction in the Gr√≠mnism√°l, and Shiva‚Äôs introduction in the Ishwara Gita, contained within the Kurma Purana.

My personal favourite translations of the Poetic Edda‚Ä¶ Henry Bellows‚Äôs translation is probably my number one, and favoured by many scholars. It‚Äôs concise and complete, and kept the original poetic form, with lots of good notes. Even if the English is a bit antiquated, it‚Äôs clear and readable. I‚Äôve heard some people complain that the English in his translation sounds like the KJV Bible; frankly I fail to see how that‚Äôs a bad thing, as lots of people are familiar with it. The version Imperium Press came out with last year is phenomenal, and includes the original Old Norse text, new introductions, and an extensive glossary. In my opinion, it‚Äôs the one to beat. I personally think Olive Bray‚Äôs translation is underrated. It reads beautifully, and she kept the poetic form, and also included the original Old Norse text and another version of the V√∂luspa. Her version was also illustrated by W.C. Collingwood. The downside is, hers only includes the poems in the Codex Regius; about half of the Edda. It is a piece of history though, as it was one of the first English translations that was widely available back in 1908. Plus, the Bray and Bellows translations are public domain, and easy to find for free. I also quite like Carolyne Larrington‚Äôs translation. Very clear, complete and straightforward to read, and as a bonus, there‚Äôs a beautiful cloth back version. Only downside is the notes are in the back of the book. Bonus: Jeramy Dodds, a professional poet, recently translated the Poetic Edda. No notes, but it reads clearly and beautifully. Would be a great first introduction to the Edda.

A small Anglo Saxon bow brooch, found in Norfolk, 5-7th Century. This style of brooch originated around the Baltic Sea, and was popular among the √Üngles and in southern Scandinavia. Rant time‚Ä¶ I continue to hear people arguing that the Poetic Edda can‚Äôt be trusted, that it‚Äôs somehow tainted because it was recorded by a Christian scribe. To which I say; have you actually read the Edda? The H√°vam√°l tells us to keep our weapons close, and stanza 127 clearly states; ‚ÄúWhen you know of evil, call it evil, and give no truce to your enemies.‚Äù (Larrington translation). In the Gr√≠mnism√°l, Odin doesn‚Äôt forgive Geirr√∂√∞, he causes him to fall on his sword. In the √ûrymskvi√∞a, Thor slays √ûrymr and his entire family. In the V√∂lundarkvi√∞a, for his capture and humiliation at the hands of N√≠√∞u√∞r, V√∂lundr carries out a most elaborate revenge. And that‚Äôs not even touching on the Heroic Poems not contained in the Codex Reguis. At what point in the Poetic Edda does it suggest to turn the other cheek, love and forgive thine enemies? Or not to take revenge, because the Gods will do it for you? I don‚Äôt care if a Christian scribe recorded the Poetic Edda, the values it conveys are very much pagan; the values that the Church hated because they made people difficult to control. Don‚Äôt love, forgive, or make peace with evil; destroy it. If someone tells you the Poetic Edda is garbage, they very likely have an agenda‚Ä¶and quite possibly have never even touched the Edda.

I‚Äôm having a thought about the Celtic votive axes. In Scandinavia and Finland, Neolithic axe heads, known as ‚Äúthunderstones‚Äù, were often uncovered during heavy rain, and would be kept in peoples‚Äô houses to protect against lightning strikes and evil spirits. Bronze Age and Stone Age axe heads have also been found in Germanic burials. In Finland, because Corded Ware-era axes were often found after storms, they became associated with the worship of Ukko. The runic Kvinneby Amulet attests Thor‚Äôs hammer as having came from the sea-perhaps washed up after a storm. It‚Äôs plausible that for the Celts, socketed axes from the British Bronze Age would have turned up after heavy rains, and may have carried a similar significance; as a symbol of Taranis. The votive axes could have been a miniaturized version of the holy ‚Äúthunder axes‚Äù, made easier to carry. Many examples were found at holy sites, where they may have been given out, or left as votive offerings.

Hengist replied: ‚ÄúWe worship the gods of our country, including Saturn, Jupiter, and all the others who govern this world. But the greatest god of all is Mercury, whom we call Woden in our tongue. To him our forefathers dedicated the fourth day of the week, which today we know by the name of Wednesday. After him we venerate the most powerful of the goddesses. Her name is Frƒìa and to her we have dedicated the sixth day of the week, which we call Friday in honour of her.‚Äù Even though the Historia is a heavily fictionalized account, it still tells us that the Anglo Saxons revered Woden as the highest of the Gods. ·ö© Art by Amalie Schoppe, 1832.

Hausmarken (house marks) were a system of emblems used in medieval Germany and Scandinavia to identify a family‚Äôs property. The first known use of house marks was in the 14th Century, and it‚Äôs likely they originated in earlier times from the runes. Many hausmarken resemble bindrunes, often containing a few non-runic symbols. In the 90s, the jeweller Kari Erlands introduced the Trollkors, and claimed it was based on a symbol she saw on her grandparents‚Äô farm. What she likely saw was a house mark, based on the Othala rune. The name ‚Äútrollkors‚Äù likely derives from the medieval Swedish practice of carving crosses above doorways and windows to keep trolls and other malevolent spirits from entering. ·õü

A Roman-era cultic Hand of Sabazios from Pompeii. Sabazios is the Thracian and Phrygian understanding of the Sky Father, and his worship persisted in the Roman Empire with Thracian auxiliaries. Sabazios‚Äôs iconography is very Shiva-like, with the crescent moon in his hair and the bull‚Äôs head at his feet. The gesture of the hand closely resembles the Prana Mudra.

An early Anglo Saxon quoit brooch, 5-6th Century. Still has lots of silvering in the punched decoration. This style, named after the game of quoits, was most popular in the Midlands. It was a derivative of the earlier annular brooches, with a simpler fastening mechanism.

An often overlooked Germanic goddess is Zisa. She was first attested in the 11th century Excerptum ex Gallia Historia, wherein she aids the Suebi in a battle against the Romans on September 28th, when they held feasts in her honour. According to the manuscript, Augsburg Germany was once named Cisaris/Zisaria after her, and a nearby hill was dedicated to her, called Zisenberg. The Codex of St. Emmeran and the Nuremberg Chronicle records a Suebian victory over an invading Roman force in the 1st Century. ‚ÄúAnd they chose for themselves the goddess Ziza, whom they believed to be Ceres. After the same goddess the city was named Zizaria.‚Äù A 12th Century church in Augsburg bears an interesting inscription‚Ä¶ ‚ÄúImpious worship long ago defiled the Gallusberg, and then offered it you, Ziza.‚Äù Post-Christianity, she was likened to Mary, who was called Maria Knotenl√∂serin (Mary, undoer of knots) in Augsburg-and her feast day is September 28th. Jacob Grimm proposed that due to the etymological similarity to Ziu, Tyr‚Äôs name in Old High German, and her being invoked for aid in battle, Zisa may be Tyr‚Äôs unnamed wife mentioned in the Lokasenna. Zisa may also be the ‚ÄúIsis‚Äù worshipped by the Suebi in Germania. The coat of arms of Augusburg bears a pinecone and a female figure with a mural crown; thought by many to be Zisa, the protector of Augsburg. The pinecone was used on Roman military standards; the figure on the Augsburg coat of arms is unique. Some have argued that Zisa is a modern invention, but as with Ostara, it makes zero sense as to why a Christian scribe would fabricate a pagan goddess, in the age when the Church was actively working to stamp out paganism. ·õè

The Runic alphabets have a few unique features; Half of the characters in the Elder Futhark and Anglo Saxon Futhorc have no parallels in any of the Old Italic alphabets, the Greek alphabet, or the Phoenician alphabet. One particularly unique feature is the Elder Futhark and Anglo Saxon Futhorc were the only alphabets in the world at the time which contained a letter for the -ing sound; Ingwaz ·õú and Inguz ·õù. Which brings us to another unique feature of the runic alphabets; each one had characters which represented deities; Ingwaz/Inguz, Tiwaz/Tyr/Tir, and Ansuz/√ìss/≈ås. In the Phoenician alphabet, while each character represents a things as well as a sound, none represent deities. ·õù·õè·ö©. Many academics will argue that the Runes came from the Old Latin, Greek or Phoenician Script, but it‚Äôs more likely that both share a common root; the Vinƒça Symbols. The Neolithic Vinƒça Symbols, or Danube Script, was a system of proto-writing that emerged in Central Europe in the 5-4th Millennia BC, and is the oldest known system of writing. The symbols are often found inscribed on pendants, vessels and figures, and are thought to have served as religious symbols, pictograms, and/or property markers. It‚Äôs quite easy to see how they influenced the development of the Germanic runic alphabets, and the old Etruscan, Greek and Phoenician scripts. Yet, with over half of the Runes having clearly evolved in Northern Europe, independently from the Mediterranean alphabets, the Runic Futharks are quite uniquely Germanic.

√ì√∞inn and the swastika. For many years, and in the modern day, it‚Äôs been thought that the swastika is a symbol that represents √û√≥rr. Usually people who‚Äôve adopted this viewpoint defend it to the death without looking into the claims, history, or looking into what clues we have from archaeology. First let‚Äôs discuss where and when the connection between √û√≥rr first came about. Hilda Ellis Davidson was a respected folklorist, and won the Kathrine Briggs Folklorist Award in 1988. She proposed that the swastika was connected √û√≥rr‚Äôs hammer based on the appearance of an Icelandic folk magic symbol (see below) known as a Galdrstafir in the book, Icelandic Folk and Fairy Tales by J√≥n √Årnason from 1862, the Galdrstafir itself was labeled ‚ÄúThor‚Äôs hammer‚Äù, It was very common to reference these sources in the 19th century by those taking a more educated stance on the culture of antiquity. Hilda Davidson did suggest a connection that I see as correct. Such as linking the swastika to death. This makes a lot of sense when we look at odinic bracteate finds, it usually depicts the Allfather himself on his steed Sleipnir (also see below). On who he travels between the different realms, especially the underworld or realm of the dead. We have many Anglo-Saxon cremation urns with swastikas featured on them. And that will lead me to my next point about what we can actually see from our finds. On the bracteates I‚Äôve posted below they all possess swastikas next to an odinic figure. It‚Äôs also very common to see on these bracteates the ALU rune formula. One of the interesting runic examples we have from Anglo-Saxon England is a cremation urn, not only with the ALU rune formula, but also possessing the swastika along with another solar symbol, known as a solar cross. In a discussion between myself and Sagnama√∞r Stark, he enlightened me on the fact that in ancient Chinese religion, the swastika is known to be the gateway to heaven, because of the patter that the constellations of the Big and Little Dipper rotating around the North Star in 4 celestial phases makes the pattern of a swastika. Anyone familiar with Germanic Paganism will know that death and the God √ì√∞inn are extremely connected. √ì√∞inn himself being a psychopomp, a Greek word for a guide of the souls of the dead. The Roman‚Äôs themselves identify him in Germania with their own God Mercury, who is also a psychopomp. In Gr√≠mnism√°l, √ì√∞inn disguised as Grimnir mentions to Agnarr Geirr√∂√∞sson that he chooses half the dead, Freyja being the one who receives the other half. The swastika is also well known to be a solar symbol, along with the well known solar cross. In the Nordic Bronze Age, there was a much bigger emphasis on sun worship. We can tell based on the stone carvings and the burials that we have from that time period. In their art, the sun crosses were very common, interestingly, these crosses were also depicted on the wheels of chariots. In ancient Vedic literature, the chariot itself is a symbol of the sun. The famous artifact known as the Trundholm sun chariot also features these characteristics. √ì√∞inn holding the role of the Sky-Father in Germanic religion also shares associations with different aspects of the sun. One of his kennings being B√°leygr, or bright eyed. The sun across different Indo-European religions is connected to an aspect of the sight of the Sky Father. Similar to Native American beliefs where they believed everything that was under sunlight was in sight of the Great Spirit. The sun itself could also represent Hli√∞skjalf. The throne of √ì√∞inn in √Åsgar√∞r. So there you have it, my personal analysis on the swastika. I believe it to be connected with death, the sun, and √ì√∞inn based on the archeological and comparative evidence we have. Thank you all for reading! Notes on Germanic priesthood; One could become a go√∞i by inheritance, or by maintaining a go√∞or√∞ (go√∞i‚Äôs estate); which would involve maintaining a temple or sanctuary, and carrying out priestly duties such as arranging feasts and bl√≥ts. One Old English term for pagan priests was heargweard; guardian/ward of a hearg (altar). From the Eyrbyggja Saga: ‚Äú√û√≥ra gave birth to another son, who was sprinkled with water and given the name Grim. √û√≥rsteinn dedicated this boy to √û√≥rr, calling him √û√≥rgrim, and said he should become a Hofgo√∞i (temple-priest).‚Äù One‚Äôs initiation into priesthood would likely involve Ausa Vatni; effectively offering yourself to a deity. According to the Kjalnesinga Saga and Eyrbyggja Saga, each go√∞i was to keep a silver ring and wear it at every public ceremony. Oaths were sworn on a go√∞i‚Äôs ring, and this role as a keeper of oaths remained until the annexation of Iceland in the 13th Century. In Bede‚Äôs Ecclesiastical History, when a priest named C≈ìfi converts, the king gives him a sword, spear and stallion. According to Bede and Tacitus, Germanic priests never owned weapons or rode a stallion, which hints at a similar system as with Roman priests of Jupiter, who were not permitted to engage in any kind of violence. In Germanic culture, this would make go√∞ar a protected class; it would be seen as cowardly to attack them. However, in the Hrafnkels Saga, a go√∞i in Iceland owns weapons and a stallion, yet never brings them inside a temple. Rules around priests owning weapons likely would‚Äôve changed after witnessing the murderous rampages of the likes of Charlemagne and Olaf Tryggvason, in which unarmed go√∞ar were often put to the sword. In the Landn√°mab√≥k, a go√∞i named √û√≥rhaddur Gamli (Thorhadd the Old) moves his temple to Iceland from Norway. He takes the pillars and a handful of soil from the temple with him. The Eyrbyggja Saga also mentions two high-seat pillars (√∂ndvegiss√∫lur) placed inside the temple door, with ‚Äúholy nails‚Äù (reginnagalar) driven into them.

The Hildebrandslied contains an interesting epithet; Irmingot. In Old High German and Old Saxon, irmin- is a term for ‚Äúgreat/mighty‚Äù, cognate to Old English eormen- and Old Norse j√∂rmun-. Yet, it was Zeus who split the first humans into male and female; and Ymir was hermaphroditic until he was slain by Odin. Rudolf Simek argues that in the R√≠gs√æula, R√≠gr is actually Odin, despite the original poem clearly introducing R√≠gr as Heimdallr, and the first few lines of the V√∂luspa clearly says ‚ÄúHeimdallr‚Äôs sons, both high and low‚Äù. On this day in 686, the last pagan Anglo Saxon kingdom, Wihtwara, fell. Wihtwara was invaded by Wulfhere of Mercia in 661, yet paganism endured, until C√¶dwalla of Wessex invaded in 686. With his last breath, he dedicated his death to Woden. Undoubtedly burdened by his abominable actions, C√¶dwalla made a pilgrimage to Rome to be formally baptized, where he died of his injuries sustained during the invasion. May he rot in Wyrmsele. What‚Äôs really funny is because he hadn‚Äôt yet been baptized when he invaded Wihtwara, many claimed he was a Pagan to further emphasize Saint Arwald‚Äôs canonization. On ‚ÄúSaint‚Äù Arwald‚Äôs Feastday, I instead remember the conviction of our ancestors, choosing a dignified death over dishonour.

The Stark coat of arms. In medieval heraldry, the oak and acorns retained their significance, representing strength and virility. Pliny the Elder described the Druids in Gaul using mistletoe picked from a sacred oak and a bull sacrifice to cure various ailments, including infertility. Sacrificial bull feasts continued in Ireland and Scotland during Lughnasadh as late as the 18th Century, where a bull was sacrificed and eaten in honour of Crom Dubh, and later, Saint M√°el Ruba. A tarbfeis (bull feast) is mentioned in several medieval Irish texts; a ritual in which a bull was sacrificed and eaten, and a Druid would sleep inside the hide, and have a vision of the next king.

Origins of the name Stark (Scotland). During the Wars of the Roses, the Duchess of Burgundy sent a company of German soldiers to aid the House of York in their attempt to overthrow Henry VII. They were defeated at the Battle of Stoke Plain, and the survivors fled to Scotland, where King James IV granted them asylum. This is likely how the German surname Stark was first introduced to Scotland. According to the Aaron Stark Family Chronicle, James IV was hunting with Sir John Muirhead in Cumbernauld, near Glasgow, and they were charged by a bull which had gotten loose. John held off the bull with his bare hands, gripping it by the horns, giving the king enough time to escape unharmed. When John escaped and regrouped with the king, he said it looked like he could have torn the bull‚Äôs head off if he wanted to. For his bravery, Sir John Muirhead was dubbed Sir John Stark. He was given a new coat of arms, with some classic Indo-European iconography; a bull‚Äôs head and three acorns. It‚Äôs often topped with a hand holding a severed bull head, and a banner reading ‚ÄúFortiorum Fortia Facta‚Äù, brave deeds of brave men.

·ö¢ The Uruz rune is an interesting one. The name of the Elder Futhark rune Uruz comes from Proto-Germanic ≈´ruz (auroch) and ≈´ra (water). The Anglo Saxon Futhorc kept the name Auroch, and in the Younger Futhark it became Rain. Aurochs often lived in moorland, as attested in the Anglo Saxon Rune Poem. Bovines require a lot of water to survive, and the ancient Germanic peoples may have followed them to find water. Auroch horns were prized for making drinking horns, because of how difficult it was to hunt an auroch, and due to their large size an auroch horn could hold a very large volume of water. In the Poetic Edda, Ymir survives on the milk of Au√∞umbla, and when he‚Äôs slain by Odin, his blood becomes the ocean. And, the Icelandic Rune Poem refers to rain as ‚Äúlamentation of the clouds‚Äù, possibly referring to Ymir‚Äôs mind, and attesting to water as a medium to acquire esoteric knowledge.

Rune Rant part 2: certain ‚Äúacademics‚Äù still think there‚Äôs no esoteric or spiritual element to the runes. Clearly, they‚Äôve forgotten; The very word rune, from Proto-Germanic r≈´n≈ç, means secret. The part in the Sigdr√≠fum√°l where Sigdr√≠fa instructs Sigurd on how to use runes to attain victory, protect himself, help deliver a child, become a healer, become wiser, and protect a ship at sea. In the R√≠gs√æula, Heimdallr teaches the runes to his son. His son then uses the runes to speak to birds, quench flame, and heal minds. Over half of the runes in the Elder Futhark have no parallels in the Old Latin, Greek, or Phoenician alphabets. Multiple runes represent deities, which does not occur in any other alphabet. ·õù·õè·ö©·ö¨ The Catholic Church tried to ban the use of runes for centuries, and charged people with witchcraft for using them. The argument about this I hear the most is that the Anglo Saxon Futhorc and Younger Futhark diverged. An interesting detail on the Kingmoor and Bramham Moor rune rings is they contain both Anglo Saxon and Younger Futhark runes. This suggests that, while the Anglo Saxons weren‚Äôt using Younger Futhark runes for their linguistic needs, they understood them. And, even if the names of some runes changed, they retained a similar underlying meaning. For example, while √ör ·ö¢ is called Auroch in the Anglo Saxon Futhorc and Rain in the Younger Futhark, both represent an unrelenting force of nature which can be helpful or harmful. The name √ör comes from Proto-Germanic ≈´ruz (auroch), and ≈´ra (water). A possible connection is that auroch horns were used to make drinking horns. An interesting one is, in the Icelandic Rune Poem, Hagal ·öº is called Hail, and a ‚Äúsickness of serpents‚Äù. In the Anglo Saxon Rune Poem, two variations appear; Gƒìar (year/harvest) and ƒ™or (serpent). In each case, it could serve as a ward against bad weather and serpents; and by extension, forces of chaos. A protective stave called the Donderbezem, which often resembles the Hagal rune, is used on buildings in the Netherlands and northern Germany to this day.

A unique Viking Age strap distributor, likely from a sword belt. It follows the overall form of Carolingian sword belt distributors, which also inspired the trefoil brooches, but the interlocking geometric decoration looks far more Scandinavian. A likely Langobardic image of Godan (Odin): This lavish bow brooch has a hidden face on the back of its foot. Notice how one eye is significantly larger than the other. With the face hidden on the back, the brooch allowed its wearer to discreetly carry an image of Odin in a time where Christianity was gaining a greater foothold in the Kingdom of the Langobards.

A fragment of an Old Saxon (or West Slavic?) spur, with a cup bearer motif. Being a cup bearer was an extremely prestigious title in many Indo European cultures. It would have to be someone that a king or noble trusted with his life, as the cup bearer would be ever-present in his court, overhearing every secret and serving drinks to him and his most trusted warriors; and in some cases, watching for poison. Pendants and mounts depicting cup bearers, usually women, appeared across Scandinavia and Germania. Many believe they could depict the Valkyries pouring mead in Valhalla; my theory is they could have served as wards against unseen threats, such as poison and treachery.

An Abbasid dirham, drilled to be worn as a pendant by a Viking. The Vikings and Anglo Saxons often made foreign coins into jewelry, likely souvenirs from their travels. This one looks like an Al-Mahdi dirham, and would have been struck in Baghdad in the 8th Century. It was found in North Yorkshire. In The Northman, you might notice Amleth‚Äôs pendant is also made from an Islamic coin.

William of Malmesbury‚Äôs 11th Century Chronicle of the Kings of England mentioned that the Anglo Saxons favoured cropped hair, and shaved their beards. Moustaches were favoured across the Germanic and Celtic world. In most Viking Age art, beards are relatively short and neat. In the Gautreks Saga, Starka√∞r‚Äôs beard is long enough that he can bite on to it when his jaw is injured. A few figurines depict men with a longer, braided beard. A popular style that appears in a few Viking Age and Anglo Saxon sources was a forked beard. Women‚Äôs hairstyles appear to have been more uniform across the Germanic world; worn long, and drawn into braids or knots at the back of the head. Veils were popular, even before the coming of Christianity. Shaving was a punishment for adultery; this is why Loki cutting Sif‚Äôs hair is such a serious offence. A completely shaven head was a mark of slavery, or punishment. A surviving law from the Kingdom of Burgundy outlaws giving a slave a wig, and prescribes shaving for certain offences. In Sweden‚Äôs Viking Age Bjarkey Laws, shaving was a punishment for theft. According to Anglo Saxon and medieval Irish laws, cutting someone‚Äôs hair without permission was a very serious offence, treated as mutilation. The combination of an undercut and moustache was also popular with other Indo-European peoples; the West Slavs favoured it well into the Middle Ages, while the East Slavs preferred a full head of hair and beard. A mummified Scythian head from the Tashtyk Culture was found with an undercut and a long moustache. While these unique tribal hairstyles served as symbols of one‚Äôs culture and social status, they also served the very utilitarian purpose of helping warriors identify fellow kinsmen in battle.

On Germanic and Celtic hairstyles. This is something that seems to come up a lot. After a few months of research, here‚Äôs what I‚Äôve found... In Germania, along with the legendary Suebian Knot, Tacitus recounts that the Chatti wouldn‚Äôt cut their hair and beards until they‚Äôd slain an enemy warrior. Hair was used as a visible symbol of oaths in other Germanic cultures; Harald Fairhair was so-called because he vowed not to cut his hair until he‚Äôd united all of Norway, and in the Poetic Edda, V√°li doesn‚Äôt so much as comb his hair until Baldr is avenged. Uncut hair could indicate an unfinished or ongoing task. Merovingian kings famously never cut their hair-which could have been a show of their lifelong commitment to serve their tribe. In many Germanic cultures, a partial shave was favoured. While uncut hair could indicate an unfulfilled oath, neatly styled hair and beards could be an indicator of a distinguished individual. Combs, tweezers and razors are commonly found in burials across the Germanic world. According to Sidonius, the Franks drew their hair forward, in a top knot and/or braids at the temples, and shaved the nape of the neck, not unlike later Norman knights. They also shaved their chins, but kept a moustache. In the History of the Langobards, Paul the Deacon wrote that the Langobard men shaved ‚Äúfrom the nape of the neck to the back of the skull‚Äù, but on top, parted the hair down the middle and let it grow to mouth-length. Leo the Deacon described Prince Sviatoslav as having ‚Äúshaved his head completely, except for a long lock that hung down the side(s?) of his head‚Äù. He also wore a short beard and a long moustache. In √Ülfric‚Äôs letter to Brother Edward, he lamented him adopting a Danish style of ‚Äúbald neck and blinded eyes‚Äù; this could be it. A figure carved on the Oseberg Wagon appears to have an undercut. He also noted that Danes who wanted a Christian burial if they died at sea gave themselves a certain haircut; it‚Äôs not clear what this was, but judging by other Christian styles at the time, it was likely shorter. In the Gesta Danorum, Saxo Grammaticus wrote that the Irish warriors, who engaged in hit and run warfare, shaved the backs of their heads to avoid being grabbed from behind as they fled. The famous Celtic M≈°eck√© ≈Ωehrovice Head depicts a similar hairstyle. A partial shave appears to have been a warrior‚Äôs haircut. More peculiarly, Sidonius described Saxon pirates as having ‚Äúdriven back the frontier of their hair‚Äù with a razor, which ‚Äúreduced their heads and enlarged their faces‚Äù. A few Bronze Age bog bodies in Denmark and Ireland have been found with the front of the head shaved, but with long hair in the back, occasionally with a knot, not unlike the Indian Shikha. This style persisted in medieval Ireland, where it was known as the Culan. It appears to have become quite a popular style; in the 12th Century, Orderic Vitalis lamented Norman noblemen adopting this style; ‚Äúthey shave the front of their heads like thieves, and let their hair grow long in the back like harlots.‚Äù The English parliament warned people against adopting this haircut, lest you be mistaken for Irishman. Conversely, another popular medieval Irish hairstyle was the Glib; shaved on the back and sides, with a long fringe in the front, said to be able to stop a sword. Scandinavian peoples also favoured long hair. According to Alf Hendriksen, the Varangian Guardsmen were easily recognized in Greece by their long hair, along with their chainmail shirts with dragon designs woven into them, and ruby earrings. Earrings were uncommon in Scandinavia, but were popular in Eastern Europe. One style that‚Äôs mentioned in Njal‚Äôs Saga was long hair held back with a woven headband. Several pieces of Viking Age art depict men with long hair gathered up in braids and knots at the back of the head, or at either side of the head, which would keep the hair out of the eyes in battle or at sea. While we have less accounts of Anglo Saxon hairstyles, from their art, it appears they favoured shoulder-length hair, and a moustache, with or without a beard.

There‚Äôs a based Swahili proverb; ‚ÄúMwacha mila ni mtumwa‚Äù; he who abandons his traditions is a slave. The implication is that when you give up your cultural identity, anyone who can offer you something to identify with will be able to manipulate you. ‚Ä¶there‚Äôs evidence suggesting that the Anglo Saxons traded with the Swahili Coast as early as the 6th Century. Beads made of African cowries, amethyst and African ivory rings were found across Anglo Saxon sites, and a few suspected Anglo Saxon beads were found in Tanzania. Dr. Caitlin Green suggests that the small cluster of finds indicate they were carried to Tanzania by an individual trader, as opposed to most mass produced trade beads.

Krodo and Varuna. Our knowledge of Krodo is fragmentary. He was mentioned in the 1492 Saxon Chronicle, wherein Charlemagne destroys a statue of him. Etymologically, Krodo can be linked with Cronos and Saturn, both governing fertility, wealth, renewal, sacred law and time. Some propose a link with the Slavic god Rod, whose worship was mentioned in the 12th century Chronica Slavorum, and was later investigated by Boris Rybakov. Some accounts refer to him as Seater/Sater, and the name of Saturday comes from Old English Sateredaeg. From the Codex Regius, on the Seven Saxon Gods: ‚ÄúBy the wheel was betokened the knit unity, and conjoined concord of the Saxons, and their concurring together in the running one course. By the girdle which with the wind streamed from him was signified the Saxons‚Äô freedom. By the pail with flowers and fruits was declared that with kindly raine he would nourish the Earth, to bring forth such fruits, and flowers. And the day unto which he yet give the name of Sater-day, did first receive by being unto him celebrated, the same appellation.‚Äù His iconography is very similar to that of Varuna. Due to the very similar function and iconography, I believe Krodo and Varuna are cognates.

An old German folk tale about Ostara‚Ä¶ Every spring, Ostara awakens, and breathes life back into the land. Where she sets foot, the grass turns green. The hopping of the hares, some of the first animals to emerge after winter, awakens her. But one year, Ostara awoke later than usual. As she made her rounds, she found a female bird that was on the verge of death. She nursed it back to health, and it began to greet her and travel with her each spring. One spring, Ostara and her bird were greeted by a group of hares, one larger than the others. Her bird and the hare began to fancy each other, and danced together day and night. Before Ostara returned to sleep, she transformed the bird into a hare. Yet, it remained a bird under its new coat of fur; when Ostara returned the next spring, it had laid eggs. The origin of this story is not known, but it could explain why the ‚ÄúEaster Bunny‚Äù became associated with eggs. It‚Äôs also thought that the early Christians adopted the practice of painting Easter eggs from the Persian spring festival, Nowruz. ·õâ

Bright Ostara, when thy times return, all beings of Midgard stir, And round about flock birds from all the boundaries of Asgard. Thou dawning with thy sacred light illuminates all the radiant realm. With our songs, as the skalds of old, we call to thee, Ostara.

I‚Äôve often seen Ostara likened to Freyja. I‚Äôve seen the light, so to speak. While Freyja has a few roles which aren‚Äôt attested for Ostara, such as a warrior, master of sei√∞r, and a receiver of the dead, she shares a few roles with Ostara. Several hymns in the Rig Veda invoke Ushas for protection and help in combat. While this role isn‚Äôt attested for Ostara, it is for Freyja. In MahƒÅyƒÅna and VajrayƒÅna Buddhism, Ushas is known as MƒÅrƒ´cƒ´, and was worshipped by warriors, including the Samurai. MƒÅrƒ´cƒ´ is often depicted riding a boar, as is Freyja with Hlidisv√≠ni. MƒÅrƒ´cƒ´ was sometimes depicted as male-or is this her twin brother Freyr? I‚Äôve heard it proposed that Freyja‚Äôs necklace Br√≠singamen symbolizes the rising sun. The root of the name is br√≠singr, an Old Norse term for fire. One of Freyja‚Äôs titles attested in the Prose Edda is Mard√∂ll; sea-brightener. In Old Norse, -d√∂ll/-dall means bright/radiant. This also relates to Heimdallr, who is attested as the brightest of the Gods, and recovers Br√≠singamen from Loki in the Sk√°ldskaparm√°l. Beowulf also recounts this; ‚ÄúThere was no hoard like it since Hama (Heimdallr) snatched the Brosings‚Äô neck-chain and bore it away with its gems and settings to his shinning fort, away from Eormenric‚Äôs wiles and hatred, and thereby ensured his eternal reward.‚Äù Etymologically, the Old Norse title Freyja means ‚Äú(the) Lady‚Äù‚Ä¶is her personal name Ostara? ·õã

My theory as to why the cult of Ostara didn‚Äôt spread to Scandinavia is because much of Scandinavia would still partially frozen when people would be celebrating in England and continental Germania. According to Bede‚Äôs De Temporum Ratione and Charlemagne‚Äôs Julian Calendar, ƒíosturm≈çna√æ, or Ostarmanoth, would be April, when much of Scandinavia would still be getting significant frost.
