A holy day observed by the pagan Anglo Saxons was M≈çdraniht, or Modranacht, ‚ÄúNight of the Mothers.‚Äù According to Bede, it was celebrated ‚Äúthe year on the 8th calends of January, when we celebrate the birth of the Lord.‚Äù, which would have been the 25th of December. Bede suspected sacrifices were held on this night. One possibility is it may have been the Anglo Saxon equivalent of D√≠sabl√≥t, a celebration of the tribe‚Äôs female ancestors, which was held before J√≥l in Scandinavia. It‚Äôs more likely that it was connected to the worship of the Western Germanic Matres and Matronae (Mothers and Matrons). The Matres and Matronae are known from several altars across England, Germany and France, depicting three women; reminiscent of the Norns. Several altars are inscribed with ‚ÄúMatronis Gabiabus‚Äù, the ‚Äúgiving mothers‚Äù. This also fits with Old Norse Gefn, a nickname for Freyja, and the goddess Gefjon. Three goddesses ruling fate is recurring in Indo European religions; for example, the Norns, the Moirai, Parcae, Hekate, and the Sudiƒçka. The Sudiƒçka or Sudice appear in Slavic folklore. They appear after a child is born, and spin a thread as they foretell the child‚Äôs life, cutting it when the life will end. New parents would leave out offerings of food for the Sudiƒçka, hoping they would make favourable predictions. Many of these Roman altars show the Mothers holding baskets. A few of these altars appeared in Roman camps, and one near Hadrian‚Äôs Wall, possibly made by Germanic auxiliaries. Their placement around military sites suggests that the Mothers were not mere fertility deities, but also protectors, spinning the fates of the soldiers. While M≈çdraniht is a more challenging one to recreate due to fragmentary knowledge, it can still be observed today. ·õâ

Here‚Äôs something you don‚Äôt see every day: a Viking Age Gutnish ‚Äútongue-shaped‚Äù pendant. These were only made on Gotland, and this one was found on the coast of Latvia, where there were Gutnish outposts. These pendants are usually found in high-status womens‚Äô burials, often alongside amulets shaped like a miniature ladle and sieve; both tools used in the production of mead. Since drinking was integral to various ceremonies, these pendants may have been a symbol of an important woman such as a gy√∞ja or a cup bearer.

One unique difference between Germanic paganism and most other Indo European religions is whether the sun and moon deities are male or female. But something I‚Äôve noticed is, while the sun is often personified as male (ex. Surya, Helios) in Indo European religions, S√≥l is the guardian of the sun as opposed to the sun itself. Similarly, the moon is often personified as female (ex. Selene, Luna) while M√°ni is the guardian of the moon. According to the Gylfaginning, the sun is made of fire from Muspelheim, and S√≥l pulls it in a chariot, and holds the shield Svalinn to protect Midgard from its heat. ·õã Painting: The Wolves Pursuing S√≥l and M√°ni by John Charles Dollman, 1909.

I‚Äôve seen a few people compare Heimdallr to Kartikeya, but the Vedic deity Heimdallr most closely resembles is Agni. Heimdallr serves as a connection between the Gods and Midgard, through the Bifr√∂st. Agni, likewise, serves as a messenger and brings all offerings to the Gods through fire. In the Gylfaginning, Heimdallr is attested as having unmatched vision and hearing; he can hear grass growing and the wool growing on a sheep. He would also be able to hear every prayer. As fire is used in every ritual, Agni sees all things, and protects every hearth. The Ayurveda associates Agni with copper, and according to the Landnamab√≥k, each temple go√∞i was to have a hlautbolli made of copper. Another shared role is as a bringer of knowledge. In the R√≠gs√æula, after siring the three classes of humans, R√≠gr (who is introduced as Heimdallr in the prose introduction) returns to teach a boy the runes. One of Agni‚Äôs epithets is Jataveda; he who knows all. Etymologically, Heimdallr combines Heim (world) and -dallr, which likely means bright/radiant, cognate to Old English deall (bright/eminent). In both Eddas, Heimdallr is attested as the whitest of the Gods. One of Agni‚Äôs titles is Jwalana; glowing. Another title of Heimdallr is Vindl√©r; wind-protector(?). Agni‚Äôs titles include Vahni; travels with wind, and Vayusaka; friend of the wind. Heimdallr‚Äôs title Gullintanni, gold-teeth, may refer to flames. In the Lokasenna, Loki tells us Heimdallr has a ‚Äúmuddy back‚Äù from standing guard constantly, and in the V√∂luspa, Yggdrasil is mired in white mud. Heimdallr‚Äôs association with Yggdrasil fits with Agni‚Äôs role as the cosmic pillar at the axis of the universe, linking Heaven and Earth, and bringing a higher level of consciousness. And when Odin hangs from Yggdrasil, he gains divine knowledge of the universe‚Ä¶and the runes. Remember, in the R√≠gs√æula, Heimdallr as R√≠gr gives the runes to humanity. Finally, Agni‚Äôs vahana is an urial ram, and in the Sk√°ldskaparm√°l, Heimdallr is heavily associated with rams. In the Gylfaginning, one of Heimdallr‚Äôs titles is Hallinski√∞i; sloping-horned. ·ö≤

An extremely rare Viking Age ‚ÄúMammen‚Äù brooch. I only know of eight examples, all from East Anglia, likely made in the same workshop in the 10th Century. The decoration is clearly Scandinavian, but the square frame could suggest continental influence. It‚Äôs been proposed that these could depict Gullinkambi, a rooster who lives in Valh√∏ll and wakes the Einherjar up every morning. It could also depict a swan, associated with Frigg, or a swan-maiden, such as V√∂lundr‚Äôs wife.

I‚Äôve had a few less than friendly people tell me I‚Äôll never be a go√∞i because there isn‚Äôt an unbroken line of go√∞ar to initiate into. For those who think this way, I‚Äôve got a question for you‚Ä¶ Imagine with me for a moment that you‚Äôre living in a Hindu or Buddhist country, such as India or Thailand, under British rule in the 19th century. But in this alternate timeline, after putting down several attempted mutinies, the colonial government decides the only way to fully subdue your people is by converting everyone to Christianity. To this end, they round up every priest and religious teacher; every Guru, every monk, and line them up and execute them. What would you do then? Would you just give up? Because that‚Äôs exactly what happened in Europe; Christian leaders such as Olaf Tryggvason made a point of targeting go√∞ar, holy sites, and temples. And our ancestors didn‚Äôt give up. When they fled to Iceland, new lines were formed. I‚Äôve scoured the Sagas for ways one could become a go√∞i; it was not just by inheritance, but also by maintaining a temple or shrine, and by carrying out the duties expected of a go√∞i. In the Saga of Hrafnkel Freysgo√∞i, he becomes a go√∞i through his ardent devotion, and he takes it upon himself to build a temple. Most importantly, a go√∞i relied entirely upon the people he purported to represent, just like modern monks and Sadhus. He‚Äôd get a few tax breaks, but no aid from the king. I suppose anyone could declare himself to be a go√∞i, but if he did a bad job, you‚Äôd know because he would have no following. This is how any go√∞i, modern or historical, should be judged; by his piety, knowledge, and the results he delivers for his tribe.

In North Yorkshire, Roseberry Topping was once known as Othenesberg; √ì√∞inn Hill. A large hoard of Bronze Age tools and weapons was found on the hill, indicating it was used as a ritual site long before the Vikings arrived. Similarly, the Anglo Saxons would bury their dead near Bronze Age barrows. ·ö¨
A few Viking Age rangles from Kievan Rus with full metal handles.

Another gripping beast pendant from Kievan Rus. The gripping beast design became popular with the East Slavs after contact with the Vikings, and this is a locally made variation. Found in Vinnytsia, Ukraine, 10-11th Century.

A Viking Age gripping beast pendant, of the Riddarholmen type. This particular pattern, with the smooth frame, was made in Kievan Rus, and is usually found in Ukraine and Russia. This one was found in the Kyiv Oblast. It‚Äôs unknown what the gripping beast pendants represent. There‚Äôs a few theories; Sigurd fighting Fafnir, Loki bound with the entrails of Narfi (and therefore, chaos controlled), or a spiritual entity without a fixed physical form.

In the Gesta Danorum, priests of Freyr used ‚Äúclattering bells‚Äù; this could be a rangle; a rattle with a series of iron rings at the end. In the Landnamabok, a man named Lo√∞mundr Gamli performed ‚Äúsorcery‚Äù with a ‚Äústick with a ring‚Äù; likely a rangle. Several surviving v√∂lva staffs were found with rattling parts as well. A series of four rangles suspended by a rope were found in the Oseberg Burial; likely to keep evil spirits out-or to keep the person buried inside from rising as a draugr. The Viking Age rangles are very similar to the Shakuj≈ç or Khakkhara staffs used by Buddhist monks. These are a symbol of their status as a monk, and are used to announce a monk‚Äôs presence, during rituals, and to deter dangerous animals. After all, rattles and bells are standard equipment in many Indo-European religions, to attract the attention of the Gods and spirits, and to drive away evil spirits. As a Germanic Gothi would be spending a lot of time in nature, in sacred groves, a rangle would be a vital tool to avoid unwanted encounters with dangerous wildlife. Rangles have also been found in elite burials along with equestrian equipment, which suggests they may have also been attached to horse harnesses. ‚Ä¶I own a rangle, it‚Äôs not hard to see how Starka√∞r was annoyed by them.
A similar sword from Lough Derg, Ireland, 11th Century.
A bronze ferrule from a Viking Age sword hilt, found in Suffolk, 10-11th Century. Looks like it may have had niello inlays. A sword from the Moesgaard Museum has very similar ferrules.
The Storra Hammars I Stone in Gotland appears to depict a man performing the blood eagle. The Valknut and two ravens watching indicates this was a sacrifice to Odin.

The Blood Eagle. We‚Äôve all heard about the infamous blood eagle. Our historical accounts come from skaldic poetry. The most well known account of the blood eagle comes from the Saga of Ragnar‚Äôs Sons, where √çvarr the Boneless executes King √Ülle in this particularly gruesome fashion in revenge for his father Ragnar‚Äôs death. ‚ÄúThey caused the bloody eagle to be carved on the back of √Ülla, and they cut away all of the ribs from the spine, and then they ripped out his lungs.‚Äù The Icelandic poet Sigvatr √û√≥r√∞arson wrote about it in the Kn√∫tsdr√°pa in the early 11th Century; ‚ÄúAnd √çvarr, the one who dwelt at York, had √Ülla's back cut with an eagle.‚Äù The gruesome death of King √Ülle was also attested in the Gesta Danorum; ‚ÄúThis they did at the appointed time; and when they had captured him, they ordered the figure of an eagle to be cut in his back, rejoicing to crush their most ruthless foe by marking him with the cruellest of birds.‚Äù Another account comes from the Orkneyinga Saga. It is described as a sacrifice to Odin, similar method to √çvarr‚Äôs; ‚ÄúEinarr made them carve an eagle on his back with a sword, and cut the ribs all from the backbone, and draw the lungs there out, and gave him to Odin for the victory he had won.‚Äù Another comes from the Reginsm√°l in the Poetic Edda; ‚ÄúSigurth had a great battle with Lyngvi, the son of Hunding, and his brothers; there Lyngvi fell, and his two brothers with him. After the battle Regin said: ‚ÄòNow the bloody eagle with biting sword Is carved on the back of Sigmund's killer; Few were more fierce in fight than his son, Who reddened the earth and gladdened the ravens.‚Äô‚Äù The Norna-Gests √æ√°ttr recalls the same account; ‚ÄúNow the blood eagle With a broad sword The killer of Sigmund Carved on the back. Fewer were more valiant As the troops dispersed A chief of people Who made Huginn glad.‚Äù Snorri Sturlusson describes the same execution in gruesome detail in Heimskringla; ‚ÄúAfterwards, Earl Einarr went up to Halfdan and cut the "blood eagle" on his back, in this fashion that he thrust his sword into his chest by the backbone and severed all the ribs down to the loins, and then pulled out the lungs; and that was Halfdan's death.‚Äù Seeing as a nearly identical image appears in multiple works from different authors, who lived far away from each other in roughly the same time period, I tend to believe it. It may have been less common than ‚ÄúHistory‚Äù Channel would have you believe, but if you saw it, you‚Äôd never forget it. ·ö¨

Nuada was the first high king of the Tuatha D√© Danann, before losing his hand in battle. The Romans likened him to Mars, who is second only to Jupiter as a commander of the Gods. Kartikeya serves as the commander (not father) of the Devas‚Äô army. This could explain Tyr‚Äôs high rank among the √Üsir. In Scandinavia and England, there‚Äôs nearly an equal number of locations bearing Woden‚Äôs and Tiw‚Äôs names. Tyr may have been more commonly worshipped before the Viking Age; my thinking is that the cult of Odin may have grown and overtaken the cult of Tyr when unconventional warfare such as piracy became more common as the Germanic peoples were faced with new threats, such as the Roman Empire and Charlemagne. Tyr governs the more glorious aspects of war, but Odin isn‚Äôt above using cunning and trickery to defeat his opponents. Painting: Nuada Silverarm by Jim Fitzpatrick.

In the Sk√°ldskaparm√°l, Tyr is attested as a son of Odin, but in the Hymskvi√∞a, he‚Äôs the son of Hymir. However, I do wonder if Hymir was Odin in disguise; while the original Hymskvi√∞a was badly damaged, it follows the H√°rbar√∞slj√≥√∞, and like H√°rbar√∞, Hymir taunts Thor, suggesting he wasn‚Äôt strong enough to break his goblet (which Thor smashes over his head). In the Prose Edda, he suggests Thor will freeze if he goes fishing. Hymir also helps Thor almost catch Jormungandr, which escapes; according to the Prose Edda, Hymir cuts the line. The quest for Hymir‚Äôs kettle, and the fishing trip, could have been a trial from Odin to help his sons prepare for Ragnar√∂k.

The Vedic god that most closely resembles Tyr is Kartikeya, also known as Murugan, Skanda, Subrahmanya and Shanmukha. He is a son of Shiva, and a war god, the commander of the army of the Devas. Like Tyr, Mars and Ares, Tuesday is Kartikeya‚Äôs holy day, and like his Roman and Greek counterparts, his weapon of choice is a spear.
Tyr feeding Fenrir by Louis Huard, 1891.

Tiwesd√¶g musings‚Ä¶ The name Tyr comes from PIE dyew-, meaning bright. It was likely a derivative of PIE deyw√≥s; heavenly one, along with Dyaus. In Proto-Germanic, this became Tiwaz, in Old Gothic, Tiews, and in Old English, Tiw. Tyr means simply ‚Äúthe/a God‚Äù, and many of Odin‚Äôs epithets contain -tyr; ex. Geirtyr (spear god), Hrafntyr (raven god), Fimbultyr (mighty god). In the Sk√°ldskaparm√°l, Thor is attested as ‚ÄúChariot-Tyr‚Äù. The arguments claiming Tyr was the ‚Äúoriginal‚Äù Sky Father are based on lazy linguistics. Odin clearly is the Sky Father, and a clear cognate of Shiva, Lugh, etc.; he fathers the Striker (Thor/Indra) and the Divine Twins (Alcis/Ashvins), marries the Earth Mother (Frigg/Jor√∞/Parvati), watches over the ancestral dead (Einherjar/Bhutagana), tests his children‚Äôs hospitality in disguise as Shiva and Zeus are attested as doing, and his golden throne Hlidskjalf is the Germanic understanding of the all-seeing sun eye. Even the name W√≥√∞anaz/√ì√∞inn is etymologically close to Shiva‚Äôs title Ugra; fierce one. According to Tacitus, the Germanic tribes worshipped Mercury (Wodan) the most, followed by Mars (Tyr) and Hercules (Thor). In the Sk√°ldskaparm√°l, Tyr is attested as a son of Odin. In the Hymskvi√∞a he‚Äôs attested as the son of Hymir; who may have been Odin in disguise; he taunts Thor in a similar manner to H√°rbar√∞. Odin‚Äôs titles containing Tyr include; Geirtyr (spear god), Hrafntyr (raven god), Farmatyr (burden god), Fimbultyr (mighty god), Gautatyr (god of the Geats), Sigtyr (victory god), Hertyr (host god), Hroptatyr (sage god), Runatyr (rune god), Hangetyr (hanged god), Valtyr (god of the slain), Veratyr (god of men) and Rei√∞atyr (god of riders). Several of Odin‚Äôs titles contain father; Aldafa√∞r (father of men), Alfa√∞r (Allfather), Herf√∏√∞r/Herjaf√∏√∞r (father of hosts), Galdraf√∏√∞r (father of galdr), J√≥lf√∏√∞r (Yule father) and Sigf√∏√∞r (father of victory). None of Tyr‚Äôs epithets do.

The Gortnacrannagh Idol: this 3-4th Century oaken bog idol was recently found buried in the Roscommon Bog, Ireland, not far from Rathcroghan. It was found alongside animal bones and a dagger, denoting the bog was a sacrificial site. It‚Äôs unclear what the ridges were for; my thinking is it might have been a place to leave small offerings. The Oweynagat cave at Rathcroghan was long believed to be an entrance to the Otherworld, and was called "Ireland's Gate to Hell" in the Middle Ages. In the T√°in B√≥ Regamna, the Morrigan was said to emerge from the cave.

An early Anglo Saxon bird-shaped mount, possibly from a shield or belt pouch, 5-7th Century. This was a recurring motif across the Germanic world, this piece is a more abstract example. I personally see a raptor with its talons outstretched, swooping in for the kill.
A bronze figure of Odin from Gotland, possibly for a small home altar.

The role of statues, and other images of Gods. In Tacitus‚Äôs Germania, a physical statue of Nerthus was toured through the farmlands once a year in a cart, covered with a cloth. People put away all iron tools and weapons and agreed not to fight. Afterwards, it was carefully washed and returned to a sacred grove until the next year. Tacitus also wrote that Germanic priests would carry sacred figures and images taken from sacred groves into battle. Similarly, various accounts describe a statue of Freyr being toured through parts of Sweden and Iceland, to bless the crops for the harvest ahead. √ñgmundar √æ√°ttr dytts, a 14th century Icelandic story, describes a demon living in a statue of Freyr, hinting at an earlier belief in the spirit of Gods inhabiting such things. In Frisia, missionaries recorded that deliberately damaging an altar or idol was a very serious offence, for which the offender could be sacrificed to the respective God. In the fourth century, when faced with a growing Christian insurgency, King Athanaric of the Thervingian Goths decided to weed out the faithful by touring his encampment with a statue. Many came out and made offerings to it, and those who refused, he locked in a church, which he then burned down. During the Christian takeover of Rome, insurgents meticulously defiled statues of the Gods; they‚Äôd smash the hands, with which they were said to accept offerings and bestow blessings, smash the nose, through with they breathe, and finally, they‚Äôd carve a cross on the forehead. They clearly believed that *something* was inhabiting them. In Ancient Greece, statues were offered to the Gods as ‚Äúhomes‚Äù. In the S√∂lkha Practice, a Tibetan Buddhist book, one passage describes asking the Gods to depart after a ritual, or, remain in an image, such as a statue or painting. The Germanic peoples clearly believed the Gods could bless and inhabit such things. With a sacred image, you invite the Gods into your home.

By Ahmad Ibn Fadlan‚Äôs account of the Rus, when the traders arrived at the dock of the market place, they disembarked from their boats, carrying "bread, meat, onions, milk, and alcohol" and went to a tall piece of wood, carved with faces, set in the ground. When the traders reached the idol, they prostrated themselves, and asked the gods for a successful trading mission, saying, "I have brought this offering. I wish you to provide me with a merchant who has many dinars and dirhams and who will buy from me whatever I want to sell without haggling over the price I fix." In the Kjalnesinga Saga, B√∫i thought it was unmanly to prostrate himself before the Gods. √ûorsteinn, the son of the temple go√∞i, accused B√∫i of false worship, and B√∫i was eventually sentenced to outlawry. B√∫i returned and ambushed √ûorsteinn in the temple, where he found √ûorsteinn lying face down in front of a statue of √û√≥rr. Images: reconstructed godpoles in Haukadalur and Eiriksstadir, Iceland.

cleaned_message: This 9th century Anglo Saxon sword was found in a Viking Age burial in Heggestr√∏a, Steinkjer, Norway. Likely a war trophy from a raid on England.

A rune stick from Bergen, Norway. The inscription reads; ·öº·õÖ·õÅ·õö·õö ·õã·õÖ ·ö¶·ö¢ √ó ·ö¶·ö¢·ö±·ö± ·ö¶·õÅ·ö¥ ·ö¶·õÅ·ö¥·ö¥·õÅ √ó ·ö¨·ö¶·õÅ·öæ·öæ ·ö¶·õÅ·ö¥ ·õÖ·õÅ·ö¥·õÅ √ó ·ö¨·ö¥ ·ö† ·öº·ö¢·ö¥·ö¢·õò ·ö¥·ö¨·ö¶·ö¢·õò Heill s√© √æ√∫ Th√≥rr √æik √æiggi, √ì√∞inn √æik eigi. ok f hugum go√∞um! ‚ÄúHail to you May Thor receive you, may Odin own you. and (be) in good spirits!‚Äù Best part is it was carved around 1185, nearly 200 years after the Catholic Church supposedly converted all of Norway. They weren‚Äôt as thorough as they thought.

Two Viking Age trefoil brooches, from opposite ends of the Viking world. The intact one was found in Pskov, Russia, where a complete Viking Age dress was also found. The incomplete one was found in York. This was a popular Anglo Scandinavian pattern, and the motif is thought to have been based on the acanthus flower. The trefoil shape was based on Carolingian strap distributors, encountered by the Vikings while trading and raiding in France.
A Graeco-Egyptian seal, featuring a syncretized image of Hermes-Anubis.

The other day, I saw someone post ‚ÄúSyncretism is a form of universalism‚Äù. I‚Äôm going to have to strongly disagree. First of all, like it or not, our sources on European paganism are fragmentary. Charlemagne and his friends made sure of that. The ‚ÄúDark Ages‚Äù are called such because of the lack of written records, often due to the destruction of all things pagan in the emerging Christian kingdoms, including literature. Germanic pagans are very fortunate in that we have more surviving texts than most to go on, such as the Poetic Edda, the Icelandic Sagas, and medieval anti-pagan laws. Other European cultures aren‚Äôt so fortunate. While the many branches of Hinduism and Buddhism are by no means the same as the ancient European religions, what they are is uninterrupted lines of Indo European religious tradition. They share a common root, and many of our Gods are cognates. Several sects have changed a lot over the centuries, but some, such as Trika Shaivism, have changed very little. I am a Germanic pagan first, foremost and finally, but I have learned a lot from studying Shaivism in particular. I find it made a lot more of our lore make sense, helped the pieces fall into place. And, syncretism wasn‚Äôt unheard of in the ancient world. For example, the ancient Greeks syncretized their religion with Buddhism in Bactria and Egyptian religion in Egypt to strengthen their alliances. Many Romans adopted the cult of Mithras, and it‚Äôs possible that the Saxon cult of Krodo was influenced by their West Slavic neighbours. You can accept that you‚Äôre part of a bigger picture without giving up your unique cultural and religious identity. Some want to piece it all back together without accepting any help from the unbroken lines of Indo-European tradition? Get comfortable, you‚Äôre going to be working on it for a while. ·ö©
Put Ratnika (The Way of the Warrior) by pagan artist Andrey Shishkin, 2020.

Let‚Äôs get something straight‚Ä¶ FOLKISH (adjective) folk‚Ä¢ish ‚ÄúCharacteristic of or based on a traditional culture, or the common people.‚Äù A lot of people don‚Äôt know what this word actually means. Most non-Abrahamic religions are, by definition, folkish, shaped over the centuries by the cultures who founded them and passed them down. And, every European pagan religion involves ancestor worship, binding the faith to its folk. Every culture has an ethnic religion of its own. As for the second part, paganism is folkish in the sense that it was the religion of the common people; in many cases, Christianity initially gained traction among the elite, and therefore, in urban centres. The very word pagan comes from Latin ‚Äúpaganus‚Äù; rustic. Heathen (ON: hei√∞inn, and OE: h«£√æen) means ‚Äúheath dweller‚Äù, and by extension, uncivilized, undeveloped. By the view of the ancient Christians, they were the ‚Äúwoke‚Äù ones, and the pagans were the flyover rural rednecks who had yet to see the correct way. Considering the aspect of nature worship in European pagan religions, it‚Äôs almost fitting. That said, I do not think it necessary to bar non-Germanic people from practicing Germanic paganism if they‚Äôre serious about it. Regardless of the fact that many of us today are of mixed ancestry, Norse paganism has become quite prominent in mainstream media, and may serve as someone‚Äôs first introduction to an ancestral religion, and I‚Äôve often seen people start off as a Norse pagan, dig deeper into their own ancestry, and eventually learn about their own ancestral faith, for example, Celtic and Slavic paganism. ·õü
‚ÄúDonar-Thor‚Äù by Max Friedrich Koch, 1905.

From the Saga of Erik the Red, when the crew was forced to overwinter in North America‚Ä¶ ‚ÄúAfter that they called upon god, praying that he would send them some little store of meat, but their prayer was not so soon granted as they were eager that it should be. Thorhall disappeared from sight, and they went to seek him, and sought for three half-days continuously. On the fourth half-day Karlsefni and Bjarni found him on the peak of a crag. He lay with his face to the sky, with both eyes and mouth and nostrils wide open, clawing and pinching himself, and reciting something. They asked why he had come there. He replied that it was of no importance; asked them not to wonder thereat; as for himself, he had lived so long, they needed not to take any account of him. They begged him to go home with them, and he did so. A little while after a whale was driven ashore, and the men crowded round it, and cut it up, and still they knew not what kind of whale it was. Even Karlsefni recognised it not, though he had great knowledge of whales. It was cooked by the cook-boys, and they ate thereof; though bad effects came upon all from it afterwards. Then began Thorhall, and said, "Has it not been that the Redbeard has proved a better friend than your Christ? This was my gift for the poetry which I composed about Thor, my patron; seldom has he failed me." ·öº

·ö∑·õñ·ö≥·õÅ·öæ·õû A possible Old English cognate of Dharma is Gecynd. Gecynd (pronounced yeh-kund), was a term for nature, including both the natural world and order, and nature as in manner and disposition, and kind or class. It originated from Proto West-Germanic gakundiz, and an Old High German equivalent is gikunt. Derivatives included; Gecynde/Gecyndelic: natural. Gecyndelim: (male and female) genitalia. Mennesc gecynd: human nature. Sundorgecynd: unusual. M√©drengecynd: nature derived from mother. Ealdgecynd: old or original nature. Painting by Angus McBride.

An early Anglo Saxon ‚Äúkeystone‚Äù brooch, with an intact garnet. 5-6th Century. These were made in the southern Saxon kingdoms, and were an imitation of the cloisonn√© brooches made in Kent. Garnet doesn‚Äôt naturally occur in most of Europe, and much of the garnet used in early medieval Europe can be traced back to India and Sri Lanka.

2) Ullr appears on the B√∂ksta Runestone, and a a sword chape was found in Thorsberg Moor with an inscription reading owl√æu√æewaz niwajemariz; ‚ÄúServant of (the glorious one) of no ill renown‚Äù, likely invoking Ullr, or Wodan. In the Prose Edda, Snorri wrote he was the son of Sif, and an archer and skier so great that no one could rival him, and he was a good God to invoke in duels. Three other skaldic poems mentioned Ullr as the son of Sif, and stepson of Thor. In the Sk√°ldskaparm√°l, several kennings are mentioned, ski-god, bow-god, hunting-god and shield-god. A kenning for warrior was Ullr‚Äôs Bowstring (Ullr Alms√≠ma), another was sword-Ullr (Ullr brands) and Ullr‚Äôs Ships (rand-Ullr) for shields. Many of the place names which contain Ullr are in northern Scandinavia; where people were more reliant on wild game than livestock. Hail Ullr!

·ö¢·õö·õö·ö± 1) Ullr is an interesting one. Not much is known about him, but archaeology and etymology tell us he was a very important God to our ancestors. The name Ullr (Old English: Wuldor) spawned from the proto-Germanic Wul√æuz, meaning glorious or shining one. Many locations in Scandinavia bear his name, such as Ullern, Ullensaker, and Ultuna. In the Grimnismal, his hall is called Ydalir; the Yew Dales. He‚Äôs also mentioned in a passage which seems to mention a fire divination ritual; ‚ÄúHis the favor of Ullr and all the Gods Who first the flames will reach; For the house can be seen by the sons of the Gods If the kettle aside were cast.‚Äù A passage in the Atlakvi√∞a links Ullr with oaths; ‚ÄúIt shall go with thee, Atli, as with Gunnar thou heldest The oaths ofttimes sworn, and of old made firm, By the sun in the south, by Sigtyr‚Äôs mountain, By the horse of the rest-bed, and the ring of Ullr.‚Äù A temple was recently unearthed at Lilla Ullevi, near Stockholm, where several large iron oath rings were buried.

A Slavic fylfot or ‚ÄúKolovrat‚Äù pendant, friend‚Äôs puppy for scale. You can see how the arms follow the form of the Little Dipper rotating around the North Star. This was a popular design in Kievan Rus, and this one was found in Chernihiv, Ukraine.

The Sutton Hoo burial contained a sceptre/whetstone, topped with a bronze stag; a symbol that can be traced back to the Steppe. Regarding the ethnonym Anglo-Saxon. The first mention of the Latin term Angli Saxones was by Paul the Deacon in the 8th century, along with the Ealdseaxe, the Old Saxons. The first English use of the ethnonym was by King Alfred the Great. He gave himself the title of Anglosaxonum Rex; King of the Anglo Saxons, after becoming King of Mercia, an Anglian kingdom, as well as Wessex. After Alfred, Edward the Elder used a similar Latinized title; Anglorum Saxonum Rex. In 924, √Üthelstan used a series of similar titles; Rex Angulsexna (King of the Anglo Saxons), and Angelsaxonum Denorumque Gloriosissimus Rex (Most glorious King of the Anglo Saxons and the Danes) when he became King of Jorvik. Finally, Cnut the Great crowned himself Ealles Englalandes Cyningc; King of all of England. There are those who will try to tell you that Anglo Saxon is not a historical term; it most definitely is. Most importantly, it was a term used by Alfred the Great to describe his united people.

Fj√∂turlundr may have been such a sacred grove. ·õâ Painting: The Semnone‚Äôs Grove of Fetters by Carl Emil Doepler, 1905.

A lesser known part of the Sutton Hoo story-the ghost of the King. According to East Anglian folklore, a ghostly figure had been seen around the Sutton Hoo burial mounds prior to their excavation. When anyone approached it, it would vanish. Edith Pretty herself may have seen it, and it may have been one of the factors that made her persist in having the relatively unassuming mounds excavated, despite her illness, and several people telling her it would be a waste of time and resources. To this day, security guards in the British Museum sometimes report strange noises and apparitions where the Sutton Hoo treasures are kept, and occasionally, doors opening seemingly on their own. After all, in the late Anglo Saxon period, there‚Äôs a reason new Christian converts were told to test their faith by spending the night on a burial mound. ·õü

·õü·õä·õè·ö®·ö±·ö® / ·õñ·ö©·õã·õè·ö±·õñ Ostara, spelled ƒíostre in Old English, is the Germanic goddess of the dawn, the shining one who revives the land after winter. The most well known source on her is Bede, who wrote that the pagan Anglo Saxons held feasts in her honour during ƒíosturm≈çna√æ (likely April), which was replaced by Paschal Month and later Easter after the Christian takeover. Jacob Grimm also wrote that Ostaram≈çna√æ was celebrated on the continent, with feasts, games and bonfires in April/May. Some modern playgans egregiously claim that ƒíostre was an invention of Bede, despite the fact that the dawn goddess appears in virtually every branch of Indo-European religion, and in the Rig Veda, Ushas is mentioned more than any other goddess. In Deutsche Mythologie, Jacob Grimm dug further into continental etymological evidence. He notes that in Old High German, the term √¥star (Old Norse/Gothic: austra/√°ustr) ‚Äúexpresses movement towards the rising sun.‚Äù He also noted the many similarities to the Slavic goddess Vesna, and a deity named Austri is mentioned in Gylfaginning, which Sturluson describes as a ‚Äúspirit of light‚Äù. Ostara has several direct cognates; Eos (Greek), Aurora (Roman), Vesna or Zarya (Slavic) and Ushas (Vedic). Her reconstructed Proto Indo European name would be Hausos. In Mahayana and Vajrayana Buddhism, She‚Äôs known as Marici. Ostara‚Äôs sacred animal is the hare. Both in England and Germany, imagery of hares and rabbits were always associated with the spring festivals, going as far back as the Stone Age. As hares are some of the first animals to come out of hibernation, an old German folk tradition said that their hopping is what awakens Ostara from her winter slumber. HƒÅl wes √æu ƒíostre! ·õâ

A stunning Anglo Saxon mount, with a raven or eagle head, 5-7 Century. It has a slight curve on the back, which leads me to believe it was mounted on a vessel.

2) When winter comes, and Ska√∞i comes down to N√≥at√∫n, bodies of water freeze. 1) Thinking about the ill-fated marriage of Nj√∂r√∞r and Ska√∞i, one possible explanation is it could represent the cycle of summer and winter. Ska√∞i is very much an embodiment of winter, and the harsh, unforgiving aspects of nature. Two of her attested titles are √ñndurgu√∞ (ski god) and √ñndurd√≠s (ski D√≠s). Sigrbl√≥t and Hrƒì√æm≈çna√æ; two Germanic spring festivals. An Anglo Saxon or Anglo Scandinavian silver garment hook, with a similar square knot design. Found near York, 7-11th Century. The hook is bent on this one, but it would have been used as a fastener for hose or a belt pouch.

I was talking to a friend about the best English translation of the Bhagavad Gita, and I‚Äôm going to suggest Winthrop Sargeant‚Äôs. The Donderbezem (thunder broom) is a protective stave, likely based on the Hagal rune, used in the Netherlands and northern Germany. A likely holdover from pagan Saxon times. The Neolithic Vinƒça Symbols were a system of proto-writing that emerged in Eastern Europe in the 5-4th Millennia BC. We have no way to translate them, but it‚Äôs easy to see how they influenced the development of the Germanic runic alphabets, and the old Italic scripts.

A few unique facts about the runic alphabets; While it‚Äôs likely that the Elder Futhark was influenced by the Old Latin Alphabet after contact with Rome, half of the characters in the Elder Futhark have no obvious parallels in any of the Italic alphabets or the Greek alphabet. One particularly unique feature is the Elder Futhark and Anglo Saxon Futhorc were the only alphabets at the time which contained a letter for the -ng/ing sound; Ingwaz ·õú and Inguz ·õù. Which brings us to another unique feature of the runic alphabets; each one had letters which represented deities; such as the Ingwaz/Inguz, Tiwaz/Tyr/Tir, and Ansuz/√ìss/≈ås. This doesn‚Äôt occur in any of the Mediterranean alphabets. ·õù·õè·ö©

More on the spear as a tool of enlightenment; Just put this together‚Ä¶in the H√°vam√°l, when Odin hangs from Yggdrasil, he pierces himself with Gungnir, and returns from this ordeal with divine knowledge of the runes and the universe. More on the Othala gravestone‚Ä¶ Around 600AD, the stone was carved. A closer look at the Sutton Hoo axe-hammer‚Ä¶ In the Gesta Danorum, Mjolnir is described as an axe-hammer; a weapon that was very popular from the Stone Age to the early Bronze Age. Wodensd√¶g musings‚Ä¶in most Indo-European religions, the Sky Father‚Äôs weapon is a spear, be it Odin‚Äôs Gungnir, Lugh‚Äôs fiery spear, or Shiva‚Äôs Trishul. Mankind‚Äôs oldest known weapon is the spear; with it, we fought our way to the top of the food chain and vanquished our enemies, striving higher and higher. Over the centuries, the spear has taken many forms, but has always been there. The oldest known worked wooden artifact is a spear. With the spear, we bent the world to our will. And, throughout Indo-European lore, the Sky Father‚Äôs spear is used to attain higher things. Odin sacrifices himself using Gungnir to attain the runes, and Shiva‚Äôs Trishul represents many things, but especially, the three powers of will, knowledge and action, with which one can realize any goal. Perhaps that‚Äôs why the spear is sacred to the highest of the Gods-a primordial weapon with which humans shaped the world to our will. Maybe even a gift from the Sky Father himself. ·ö∏

March 7th is on the full moon that marked what our Anglo-Saxon forebears called Hrƒì√æm≈çna√æ, or in modern English, The month of Hrethe. During this month we worship this Goddess, but who is she? Well if we use what information we have we can get a decent idea. Another Anglo-Saxon name for this month is called Hlydamonath. This is very obviously a cognate to the name of the Goddess Hludana who is referenced on Roman stone altars in northern Germany and the Netherlands. A kenning for J√∂r√∞ is also Hl√≥√∞yn. All of these names (except J√∂r√∞) roughly translate to the same meaning, ‚Äúloud or noisy‚Äù. Referring to the more harsh or noisy winds that occur during the month. In Sk√°ldskaparm√°l J√∂r√∞ is called "The floor and base of winds‚Äô hall". With all of this in mind. I think it makes the most sense to conclude that Hrethe is just another kenning for the glorious Earth Mother, Erce. Hail to the love of the Sky Father Woden! Hail to the mother of the steadfast Striker Thunor! Hail the genuine and giving Erce!

cleaned_message: Several amulets resembling kubbstol (a stool carved from a tree trunk) chairs have been found in high status womens‚Äô burials from the Viking Age. These likely depict the Seidhjell; a ritual seat a v√∂lva would use when she performed sei√∞r. My thinking is the design of the chair would help keep the v√∂lva upright whilst she was in a trance state.

The Viking Age rock carvings at Bidston Hill. Located in northwestern England, with carvings of S√≥l, M√°ni, a horse and two wolves, possibly Hati and Sk√∂ll. Thought to have been carved around 1000AD. Norse and Anglo Saxon pagans often built shrines on sacred hills, this could have been one such holy site.

An amazing find from Denmark; a brooch with a raven eating a fallen warrior. In the Saga of Egill Skallagrimsson, a kenning for a warrior was Hrafngrennir (raven feeder), along with Ulfgrennir (wolf feeder) and Arngrennir (eagle feeder). Each of these animals were heavily associated with Odin, and were known to follow warbands, and appear after a battle to eat the dead. In Celtic paganism, the Morrigan takes the form of a raven to carry the souls of the dead to the afterlife; and the raven on this brooch does look like it could be carrying the body off. Another kenning was Feitir Folkstara (fattener of the war-starling). Conversely, an Old Norse insult was Hrafnasueltir (raven starver), implying cowardice. ·õ¶

An Anglo Saxon bracteate found in Undley, with the Roman wolf and twins motif. It‚Äôs possible that after their contact with the Roman Empire, the Anglo Saxons recognized Romulus and Remus as an incarnation of the Divine Twins.
Another one of my crown jewels: an Anglo Saxon gilded decorative mount, found in Grimsby, Lincolnshire, 6th Century. Likely depicts the Alcis Twins, and/or Hengist and Horsa.
A very nice wooden ‚Äúhusgud‚Äù figure from the Telemark Museum, Norway. Thought to have been carved around 1015AD. May depict Odin; notice how one eye is squinted shut.

My crown jewel: a Viking Age strap end, depicting Odin with Freki and Geri. The right eye has been scratched in antiquity with a sharp object, which was often done with images of Odin in the Viking Age. Found in Linton, North Yorkshire. ·ö¨

An 8-9th Century Irish enamelled mount, likely from a reliquary or a large crucifix. It was found in East Anglia, which suggests it was taken by a Viking as a war trophy. Many fragments of Celtic ecclesiastical metalworks were taken and made into jewelry and coin weights by the Vikings.

This 8-9th Century Irish hanging bowl was found in a Viking Age burial in Skei, Norway. Possibly used for serving, washing or even holy water. Aside from the shape, the decoration is similar to examples found in Anglo Saxon sites. If the hanging bowls found in Anglo Saxon burials are indeed of Celtic origin, this could hint at a longstanding Germanic tradition of pilfering Celtic tableware. As many hanging bowls are lavishly decorated, they likely would have belonged to the Celtic elite. Stealing one off of a Celtic chieftain‚Äôs table would make it a prized war trophy for a Viking or Anglo Saxon warlord. Especially if they did have an ecclesiastical purpose; attacks on an enemy‚Äôs religious sites were not unheard of among Indo-European cultures.

Two mounts from an Anglo Saxon (Celtic?) hanging bowl. Found in Hertfordshire, 6-7th Century. The enamel in the escutcheon would have been red in its day. The hanging bowls found in Anglo Saxon burials often have Celtic-style decoration; it‚Äôs likely that they were looted from the Celtic elite.

‚ÄúFreya‚Äù from Rebild. This wooden statue was found in a peat bog in Rebild Skovhuse, Denmark, wrapped in cloth. Possibly an image of Nerthus; in Germania, Tacitus described an image of Nerthus being carried in a chariot, covered with a cloth veil. It was carved from a birch bole, 1.05m tall, Bronze Age to Iron Age. Note the abstract face; Tacitus also wrote the Germanic tribes saw it unfit to depict the Gods in human likeness.

One of my many takeaways from reading other Hindu and Indo-European sacred texts, such as the Rig Veda, Puranas, and Ishwara Gita, is that they ultimately back up much of what‚Äôs conveyed in the Poetic Edda. If someone tries to tell you the Poetic Edda is trash, they very likely have an agenda.

The Sami god Horagalles: an Uralic cognate of Thor. In Sami religion, Horagalles, also spelled Thora Galles, often called Tiermes/Aijeke ("grandfather"), is the Thunderer/Striker god. He is often depicted as a wooden figure with a nail or piece of flint in the head and with a hammer. It has been suggested that his name was influenced by that of Germanic Thor; after all, the Norse and Sami traded extensively in the Viking Age. The Vikings sold Sami reindeer hides as far as the Middle East and Byzantine Empire, where they were prized for their soft inner coat. The hammer wielding thunder god appears in other Uralic cultures; Ukko, Taara, and Tharapita. His hammer is called Wetschera, Aijeke Wetschera or Ajeke veƒãƒãera. The nail or stone in the head is not unlike the forehead injury that Thor sustained in his battle with Hrungnir. Horagalles punishes "demons" who frequent the rocks and mountains (trolls?); he destroys them with his lightning, bow, and hammer. The rainbow is his bow, "Aijeke dauge".
‚ÄúThor, God of Thunder‚Äù by Richard Doyle, 1872.

He through his majesty thinks on all beings on Midgard, on the √Üsir and Vanir through high on Hli√∞skjalf. Come to our hearths that gladly welcome thee and heal all sickness, Odin, in our families. May thy bright Gungnir, when thrown down from Asgard, flieth over Midgard, pass us unharmed by. Thou, Kjalarr, hath a thousand medicines; may no harm fall upon our folk. Slay us not, nor abandon us, Odin, let not thy noose seize us. Grant us thy blessings and fame among the living. Preserve us evermore, mighty √Üsir, with thy grace. ·ö®·õö·ö¢

A mummified head from the Tashtyk Culture, a branch of the Scythians who inhabited Siberia in the Iron Age, 1-4th Century. His clay burial mask preserved his head beautifully. A CT scan revealed this man had an undercut, a long moustache, and multiple surgical scars.

A prayer to Tyr, based on a Rigvedic Mitra hymn. Tyr, stirreth men to battle: Tyr sustains both Midgard and Asgard, Tyr beholdeth men with eyes that never close. To Tyr bring your sacrifices. Foremost be he who brings thee mead, O Tyr, who strives to keep thy sacred Law. He whom thou helpest never is slain or conquered, on him, from near or far, falls no defeat. Joying in sacred mead and free from sickness, with knees bent low on Midgard, Following closely the √Üsir‚Äôs statute, may we remain in Tyr's gracious favour. Mighty and courageous, Tyr was born with fair dominion, King, Disposer. May we enjoy the grace of Him, rest in his loving kindness. The great Tyr, to be served with worship, who stirreth men, is gracious to the warrior. To Tyr, him most highly to be praised, offer in fire thy sacrifices. The gainful grace of Tyr, supporter of the race of man gives splendor of most glorious fame. Tyr whose glory spreads afar, he who in might surpasses Asgard, Surpasses Midgard in his renown. All Midgard‚Äôs races have repaired to Tyr, ever strong to aid, For he sustaineth all the Gods. Tyr to Gods, to living men, to him who strews the holy grass, Fulfills the sacred Law.

"Men knew that the gods whom they served could not give them freedom from danger and calamity, and they did not demand that they should. We find in the myths no sense of bitterness at the harshness and unfairness of life, but rather a spirit of heroic resignation: humanity is born to trouble, but courage, adventure, and the wonders of life are matters for thankfulness, to be enjoyed while life is still granted to us. The great gifts of the gods were readiness to face the world as it was, the luck that sustains men in tight places, and the opportunity to win that glory which alone can survive death." -Hilda Ellis Davidson, from Gods and Myths of Northern Europe

In Native American Religion, existence is conceptualized as a great cedar tree divided into 3 realms. The Thunderbird, which is held in very high regard, resides in the highest of these realms, or the heavens at the top of the cedar tree. The thunderbird is always at constant conflict with a snake/water panther who resides at the bottom of these realms or the realm of the dead. (Think of Perun in the form of an eagle who is constantly fighting with Veles in the form of a snake in Slavic lore) Perun‚Äôs conflicts with Veles result with lightning striking the earth. Much like how the thunderbird sends storms and winds. In the Germanic perspective, there is also an eagle that sits at the top of Yggdrasil, with a hawk that sits between its eyes called Ve√∞rf√∂lnir. Which means (wind-witherer) The eagle is never specifically named, but given the fact these parallels are so shockingly ancient. I think the ‚Äúunnamed eagle‚Äù, that sits at the top of Yggdrasil, is actually Hr√¶svelr. A j√∂tunn in the form of an eagle who is the source of winds. His name has been translated as 'corpse-swallower', or as 'shipwreck-current'. He is called Hr√¶svelg, who sits at heaven‚Äôs end, a giant, in the shape of an eagle; from his wings they say the wind comes over all people. ‚Äî Vaf√ær√∫√∞nism√°l, 37 Thank you to Sagnama√∞r Stark on here for helping me put this together!

This is pretty cool-a Celtic potin from France, depicting a deity with its hand in a wolf‚Äôs mouth. The myth of a god selflessly sacrificing his hand extends beyond the Germanic world. It most likely depicts the Celtic god Nuada (aka Nodons), who was likened by the Romans to Mars, who was also likened to Germanic Tyr. Nuada was invoked in battle and for healing, and was the first high king of the Tuatha De D√°nann-until he lost one of his hands in battle.
Note the two sticks in the petroglyph‚Äôs hand.

This post will be about the odinic aspects of Nanabozho, a spirit, or shamanic figure of the Native American Ojibwe tribe. To start off, despite their only ancient connection being the Ancient North Eurasians roughly 25,000 years ago, Nanabozho, and Othin are portrayed very similarly between Germanic, and Ojibwe culture. (As you can see I‚Äôm the image below this post) Nanabozho is usually described as a trickster, who assisted in the creation of the world. The trickster aspect may make you think of Loki, but keep in mind that Othin is a master of manipulating many things in order to get his way. Othin is a master shaman/priest, and as we can see in the 9 herbs charm; he creates 9 herbs from a cut up snake that humanity can use for medicinal purposes, and when he creates mankind he sends his wolves Geri, and Freki to teach Askr, and Embla (the first man and woman) how to live off the land. Nanabozho was sent by Gitche Manitou (The Great spirit) in the form of a rabbit to teach humanity the names of the animals, plants, and how the plants could be used for medicinal purposes. Nanabozho is considered the inventor of fishing, and hieroglyphs much like how Othin gave the runes to humanity. He is the founder of the Midewiwin, the shamanic practicers of medicine. (There are other shamanic groups in the Ojibwe tribe. This is just one of them) They were very secretive, and were usually the outcasts of society, much like the rune-masters of Germanic society, who I have no doubt also practiced medicine. Nanabozho is also said to have traveled all over the world, and while doing so killed many monsters. Much like Othin, Nanabozho sacrifices himself, and gives humanity divine knowledge; such as communicating with the spirits of the land, or teaching humans how to make flint weapons. The flint, or rock comes from the conflict between Nanabozho and his brother. He ripped his brother apart while fighting him, and the parts of his body were flung across Earth, and became different kinds of rocks, stone, or flint. (Reminds me of Othin killing Ymir who‚Äôs body would become Midgard) In many stories he takes the form of different animals, and even different forms of humans, man or woman. This reminds me of when Othin took the form of a medicinal woman in order to get into the personal chambers of Rindr after the death of Baldr. Othin also is well known to take the form of animals, such as eagles, fish, ravens, snakes, etc. It is shared that Nanabozho takes the form of ravens, coyotes, hares, spiders, and more. It depends on the region that the tribe is from. These animals are usually chosen because they are hard to catch making it easy for him to escape the situation he is in. Nanabush (a spirit of oral traditonal storytelling) often experiments with capitalistic means. These means can be greedy, manipulative, and money driven. (Much like Hermes or Mercury) Because of their worldly desires, chaos often ensues. However, as Nanabush develops deep relationships with those around them, they become more intune with themselves, and their surroundings. Furthermore, as Nanabush becomes more receptive to their surroundings, they are used to guide people through life experiences, and teach moral lessons. As you can see. This is very odinic.

Vedic copper weapons from Gungeria, Madhya Pradesh, India. Very similar to the later Bronze Age antennae swords and axes used in Europe. The war clubs or ‚Äúbar celts‚Äù at the bottom are very similar to the Yamnaya war club from the Kutuluk Kurgan. An ideal shape for smashing a human skull.

Notes on the Germanic wolf man motif‚Ä¶ The example on top was found in a Viking Age cremation burial in Ekhammar, Sweden, along with a bronze horned Odin figure. Come to think of it, most examples of the Germanic wolf man motif come from burials. Many were also placed alongside iconography of Odin. The example from Ekhammar is also holding what appears to be a snake, another image attributed to Odin, attesting the ability to communicate with the dead. Another theory that they could depict ancestral spirits, with a wolf fylgja or totem (such as the Ylfings clan), and while I still believe this to be likely; these could very well depict servants of Odin, or Odin, collecting the souls of the dead. The most obvious parallel would be Anubis, the jackal-headed receiver of the dead, and of course, the Egyptians had a lot of contact with the Indo-European Hittites. This could highlight a more esoteric role of the pan-Indo European werewolf cults; collecting souls in service of Odin.

A few examples of the looped square/Hannunvaakuna symbol; a Viking Age pendant from Sweden, a gold bracteate from Lyngby, Denmark, and a 9-12th Century ski from Kemij√§rvi, Finland. Looking at that first amulet, perhaps this is a protective symbol because it represents the omnipresent vigilance of the guardians of the four directions/four winds; Nor√∞ri, Su√∞ri, Austri and Vestri in Germanic religion, and Agni, Varuna, Yama and Soma in the Vedas. See also the Hellenic Anemoi, and the Roman Venti.

An intriguing Vendel Era pendant recently unearthed in Norway. Upright, it seems to show a bearded man, on its side, a classic Salin type I Germanic beast motif. note how the moustache morphs into a stylized muzzle. Likely a berserkr/wolf warrior amulet, with a man in the process of transformation into a wolf warrior.

Just put this together about Au√∞umbla‚Ä¶ In the Puranas, Prithvi, the Vedic Earth Mother, appears in the form of a cow. Prithu, an avatar of Vishnu, milks her, and her milk provides the Earth with vegetation. In the Gylfaginning, Au√∞umbla‚Äôs milk sustains Ymir. In Germania, Tacitus wrote that a statue of Nerthus was carried in a cart pulled by two cows. Au√∞umbla could be the primordial incarnation of the Earth Mother, who awakened the Sky Father. In contrast, the Sky Father is sometimes depicted riding a bull; ex. Shiva, Sabazios and Zeus.

The origin of the Sun Wheel symbol‚Ä¶ This amazing weather phenomenon is known today as a ‚Äúsundog‚Äù. It‚Äôs caused by refraction of light by ice crystals in the atmosphere, and very likely inspired the sun wheel/sun cross, the oldest continually used solar symbol in history.

üá¨üáßSaturday's march in Gda≈Ñsk under the banner "No more brother wars!" is over. It is time for its summary. First of all we would like to wholeheartedly thank all of our friends from Poland and abroad, who honoured us with their presence on that day; as well as those who could not make it, but helped us with the preparations, support and promotion. Nation-wide and Europe-wide delegations (Czech Republic - National Social Front; France - Les Nationalistes; Bulgaria - Bulgarian National Association, Ukraine S14) amounted to the success of the march. Participation of about 150 people, considering the Covid-19 pandemic and the weather condition, was more than satisfactory. We believe that the great feats of oratory performance by the Neptun statue, done by represantitves of Niklot, Zarzewie for Identity, as well as our guests from abroad, reached a vast audience, and fed the flaming hearts, that will further intensify our activism. March was conducted without any obstructions. Our Pan-European, socialist and unity slogans were heard loud and clear in the streets of Gda≈Ñsk, and we are not planning to stop on that. It is a mere introduction, to what we can achieve. Believe. It appears wrong, that nationalism goes in pair with chauvinism. We put an emphasis, that the latter should never have anything to do with the first. Only together, with cooperation and coexistence, can we defeat the dangers that face Europe. LGBT, modern left wing, capitalism, liberalism and the influx of ethnically foreign immigrants - are only a few of our common obstacles, that we have to overcome as nations of Europe. Our fight is a fight against the modern world. Against the modern world of bastardized values, stagnation, apathy and hedonism. We will not allow such image of our society, and we will attempt to show alternative options on every step possible. In the international sphere, it is Europe of free nations. No more brother wars! Long live Europe of Nations!
See you tomorrow brothers!

CFDs are very popular because professional traders, brokers, hedge funds, etc are always looking for ways to maximize profit. So cutting out COMEX is to their advantage since they don't have to pay them a fee. So they want to move as far away from Physical and exchanges as possible. So (((they))) want to promote CFDs as much as possible That's how Citadel makes their money. They make bids and offers that are slightly worse than the underlying market and they pocket the difference That's how Robinhood can allow trading "for free" they send all their orders to Citadel. So you aren't trading for "free" you're paying in worse prices instead of a commission

CFD = Contract For Difference. It's effectively buying/selling against your broker as opposed to buying/selling the actual underlying contract at an exchange. Brokers do this because they can buy or sell at lower rates as there are no exchange fees when they offer CFDs. They then pass along the savings to you. So if you want exposure to paper gold/silver you can get it cheaper and more efficiently than buying Futures or physical The downside is if the Broker goes bust you become a creditor of the bank for whatever your position is, Think Lehman. When you buy at COMEX it's one transaction You-> Broker (eg. Lehman)->COMEX COMEX guarantees the gold/silver you bought. Lehman just arranges the transaction. So when Lehman went bust you still own the paper gold/silver since they just arranged the trade and your counterpart is COMEX CFD - Two transactions #1 You "I buy 100oz Gold CFD" -> Broker "We sell you 100oz gold CFD @ 2000" #2 Broker->Buys 100oz COMEX Gold at @ 1999 to hedge your trade and pockets the difference as profit. So if the broker goes bust you don't own the Gold, you get in line with other creditors

cleaned_message: This is a neodyme magnet coin slide I bought off eBay for my business. CuNi coins slide down quickly, Silver coins push against the magnetic field and slide down visibly slower, iron copies / fakes stick like glue. Heavy silver plated coins and high copper content coins can fool it, but they are rare. In conjunction with scales it is superb and has saved me a lot of time and money over the years. It is very simply made from balsa wood with Neodyme magnets and a soft landing pad. Should be easy to make at home. Hope this helps.
